{This type of structure is quite typical for Caro-Kann, Scandinavian, and Slav. The knowledge of this type of position will also be quite useful for our repertoire against the Two Knights Variation. Very often, you can get this structure with the pawn on c3. White has a space advantage, good control of the e5-square, and the possibility of playing on the semi-open e-file. If White manages to keep the centre under control and avoid piece exchanges, he can consider active actions on the kingside. On the other hand, Black has a solid position without weaknesses. Very often, by putting pressure on d4, Black tries to prove that White's centre is overextended. Exchanges of minor pieces are usually in Black's favour since with every exchange, White's space advantage becomes less significant. The advance ...c6-c5 is another major idea in this pawn structure. After the exchange of the pawns \"c\" and \"d\", we get a typical position with pawn majorities. The evaluation of such positions depends on the piece activity and the control of the d-file. Therefore, every case should be evaluated concretely. The advance ...b7-b5 is another major idea in this structure. The idea is to secure the control of the d5-square. Sometimes, when White has a pawn on c4, this advance is connected with a pawn sacrifice.}  *

