{ This is another version of the typical Caro-Kann/Scandinavian/Slav structure. Very often, in our variation, we get this structure with a bishop on g7. The setup with ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7 is good for Black if he had managed to solve the problem with the light-squared bishop. In the position on the diagram, Black is doing fantastic since the light-squared bishops had been already exchanged. Besides increasing the pressure on d4, the g7-bishop prevents White from creating kingside activity. In the long run, Black's main idea is to execute the advance ...c6-c5. For instance, a possible continuation would be } 1. Qc2 c5 2. dxc5 Qxc5 { [%csl Gc2,Gc5][%cal Ga8d8,Ge6e5,Gf7f5,Ge5e4] Very often, in positions with queens on the board, the side which has kingside majority tends to be better. In this position, for example, the advance of Black's central pawns will eventually weaken the white king. Besides the advance of the kingside pawns, Black can also opt for a minority attack by means of ...b7-b5-b4. } *[Event "?"]
