{Let's start with one typical mistakes. After the moves} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Be6 {White often plays} 7. d4 $2 {which is a huge positional mistake. Surprisingly, this error has been committed by some strong players, including Nakamura (as seen in this game) . The problem is that after} Bd5 8. Qe3 Bxf3 {White is forced to recapture with the g-pawn.} 9. gxf3 ({In case of} 9. Qxf3 {, the play might continue} Qxd4 10. Be2 Nd7 11. O-O e6 12. Rd1 Qf6 $15 {White does not have enough compensation for the pawn.}) 9... Nd7 {[%cal Gd7f6] In my opinion, this move is quite logical. Black definitely wants to have a knight on f6 in order to make sure that the kingside is sufficiently protected. The following couple of moves are quite logical -} 10. c3 Nf6 11. Bd3 e6 12. Qe2 {This move is slightly inaccurate since White loses control of the dark squares on the kingside (in particular f4-square) .} ({More logical would have been} 12. Bd2 Bd6 13. O-O-O {By relying on the g-file, White is going for a kingside activity. Black has a variety of moves and plans in this position. If you want to play very simple chess, something like ...Qc7 followed by ...0-0-0, is more than enough. In this structure, exchanging the dark-squared bishops (possibly via the f4-square) is Black's most important strategic idea. Also, remember that the move ...g7-g6 is always useful. Another very creative way of handling the position is} Nd5 14. Qe4 b5 $1 {Quite a typical move in this structure. Besides gaining space on the queenside, Black also stabilizes the d5-knight. A logical sequence is} 15. h4 h5 16. Rde1 Kd7 17. Kb1 g6 $15 {Note that the moves ...h7-h5 and ...g7-g6 are quite typical for this structure. In this way, we fix the kingside structure and White does not have any breaks. At the same time, the black king is perfectly placed on the d7-square. As already mentioned, Black is planning to exchange the dark-squared bishops via f4. Every endgame is favourable for him. It's also very important to point out that White does not have a constructive plan at all.}) 12... Bd6 13. h4 Qc7 14. h5 Bf4 {Black is following his general plan - exchange of the dark-squared bishops.} ({Another very good continuation would be} 14... Nd5 15. Bd2 Nf4 16. Bxf4 Bxf4 $15 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Ge8c8,Ge6e5] This position with opposite-coloured bishops is definitely in Black's favour. White cannot find a safe haven for the king. At the same time, after castling long, Black is ready to open the position by means of the advance ...e6-e5. We know how important is the attack in positions with opposite-coloured bishops.}) 15. Be3 h6 16. O-O-O O-O-O $13 {According to the computer, this position is balanced. In return for his doubled pawns, White enjoys good central control and can potentially put pressure on g7. Practically speaking, however, Black's play remains easier due to his static advantage.} 17. Kb1 Kb8 18. Rdg1 Rhg8 19. Rh4 Bd6 20. f4 Qe7 21. f5 e5 22. dxe5 Qxe5 23. Re1 Ka8 24. Ra4 c5 25. Bc2 Rge8 26. Qc4 Qd5 27. Qe2 Qc6 28. Rh4 Nd5 29. Ba4 Qb6 30. Bxe8 Nxc3+ 0-1

