{Let's start with one online blitz game played by the huge Caro-Kann expert Pavel Eljanov.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Be6 7. Bc4 {Statistically speaking, this harmless move is one of White's most popular choices against out variation. With this move, White just wants to get a solid position out of the opening.} Bd5 {The most precise continuation. Besides being generally useful, this move is an invitation for a Carlsbad pawn structure.} ({In many online blitz games, I have tried} 7... Bxc4 8. Qxc4 Qd5 9. Qe2 c5 {[%cal Gb8c6] The idea is to follow with ...Nc6, thus securing a stable space advantage in the centre. Indeed, if Black manages to stabilize the position, the control of the d4-outpost would give him a long-term static edge. The problem is that after} 10. O-O Nc6 11. b3 e6 12. Bb2 {[%cal Gc2c4,Ga1d1,Gd2d4] White is ready to quickly open up the position by preparing the advance d2-d4.}) 8. Bxd5 cxd5 9. Qa4+ $6 {This is a dubious decision. In this type of Carlsbad structure, White should avoid the exchange of the queens since he is mainly trying to create kingside activity. The following couple of moves are quite natural.} Qd7 10. Qxd7+ Nxd7 11. d4 e6 12. Bf4 b5 13. O-O Be7 {Even though this move is perfectly natural for a blitz game, I find it a bit slow.} ({Better would have been} 13... Nb6 $1 {preventing the advance a2-a4 which is White's only source of counterplay. White should try to open the position before Black manages to complete the development.}) 14. Ne5 {This slow move allows Black to stabilize his static advantage.} ({White should have played} 14. a4 b4 15. c3 bxc3 16. bxc3 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gb1b7] White's queenside weaknesses are compensated by the superior development. Additionally, Black should always reckon with the possible invasion via the b-file. A logical follow-up would be} Nf6 17. Rab1 Ne4 18. Rfc1 Bd6 $11 {with dynamic equality. Nevertheless, if provided with enough time, Black might overtake.}) 14... Nxe5 15. Bxe5 f6 16. Bg3 Kd7 17. Rfe1 Rhc8 {Black managed to fully consolidate. Now, Eljanov is ready to conduct his minority attack on the queenside.} ({In my opinion, starting with} 17... b4 {[%csl Rc2,Rd4][%cal Gh8c8,Gc8c4] would have been more precise. The idea is to fix the c2-pawn. Now, Black is ready to proceed with ...Rhc8-c4. In this way, he puts simultaneous pressure on c2 and d4.}) 18. Re2 a5 19. Kf1 Rc4 20. Rd2 Rac8 21. Rc1 a4 {Eljanov wants to push his a-pawn all the way to a3, thus fixing the a2-pawn.} ({More thematic solution would have been} 21... b4 {which is again designed to fix the c2-pawn. By the way, option of ...a5-a4-a3 is still on the table. The following example line shows how the game might unfold in this position.} 22. Ke2 h5 $1 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gh5h4] An important move. Black is not going to win the game by only attacking the queenside weaknesses. We need additional targets on the queenside. If allowed, Black will proceed with ...g7-g5 followed by ...h5-h4. In case of} 23. h4 {a good idea will be} a4 {[%cal Ga4a3] planning to fix the a2-pawn by means of a4-a3. The following line illustrates how Black can win by combining play on both wings.} 24. Bf4 a3 25. b3 Rc3 26. Be3 g5 $1 {Another thematic move. Now, White should either accept a weakness on h4 or go for} 27. hxg5 fxg5 {[%cal Gh5h4] when Black is strategically winning. Besides playing against all the queenside weaknesses, Black can also create a distant passed pawn by means of ...h5-h4 followed by .. .g5-g4. For instance, after} 28. Rh1 h4 29. Kd1 g4 $19 {White is already lost.}) 22. a3 b4 23. axb4 Bxb4 24. c3 Be7 $15 {Black's advantage is out of question. Later on Eljanov managed to win. I leave the remaining part of this blitz game without comments, but I suggest that you would take time to study it.} 25. Rd3 R8c6 26. f3 Rb6 27. Rc2 Rb3 28. Bf4 a3 29. bxa3 Bxa3 30. Ke2 Rb2 31. Rxb2 Bxb2 32. Kd2 Ba3 33. Kc2 g5 34. Be3 h5 35. Kb3 Bd6 36. h3 Rc8 37. Rd2 Rb8+ 38. Kc2 Ra8 39. Kb2 h4 40. Rc2 Kc6 41. Kb3 Rb8+ 42. Ka2 Bf4 43. Bxf4 gxf4 44. Re2 Kd6 45. Rb2 Rxb2+ 46. Kxb2 e5 47. Kc2 Kc6 48. Kb2 Kb5 49. Kb3 exd4 50. cxd4 f5 51. Kc3 Ka4 52. Kc2 Kb4 53. Kd3 Kb3 0-1

