{Here is another good example of a minority attack.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Be6 7. Bc4 Bd5 8. Bxd5 cxd5 9. Qe2 {This retreat is more sound than 9.Qa4+. White should try to keep the queens on the board. Without the light-squared bishops (and with pairs of knights exchanged) , however, White's attacking chances on the kingside are not realistic.} e6 10. d4 Bd6 {This is the best square for the bishop. Keeping the diagonal h2-b8 under control is quite important in this structure. For instance, in positions with a white bishop on f4, Black cannot easily prepare the minority attack with ... Rb8.} 11. Bg5 Qc7 12. O-O O-O 13. Bh4 {[%cal Gh4g3] In this structure, White would be glad to exchange the dark-squared bishops. Therefore, the idea behind his last move is Bg3.} Nd7 14. Bg3 b5 $1 {Well-timed advance. Black makes use of the fact that the b2-pawn is hanging after 15.Qxb5 Rab8.} 15. Rfc1 Rab8 16. c3 {Sooner or later White must go for this move. Otherwise, at some point, Black will be able to fix the queenside structure with ...b5-b4.} Rfc8 17. a3 a5 18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19. Ne1 {[%cal Ge1d3] Remember this maneuver which is so thematic for the Carlsbad structure. The white knight is heading for the perfect d3-square. Black should strike immediately with} b4 $1 ({A slow move such as} 19... Rc7 $6 {would be a strategic mistake. The problem is that after} 20. Nd3 {[%cal Ge2g4,Gh2h4,Gd3f4,Gf4h5,Gc1e1,Ge1e3,Ge3g3] Black does not have constructive ideas on the queenside. Even if we manage to prepare the advance . ..b5-b4 by putting the knight on c6, White can always answer with b2-b4 and even put the knight on c5. At the same time, White has plenty of time to organize a kingside attack. A possible idea is h2-h4 followed by Qg4. Then, he can provoke some kingside weaknesses by means of Nf4-h5 and Re1-e3-g3. The attack is going slowly but Black has nothing to do in the meantime.}) 20. axb4 {This solid continuation tends to be passive.The following sequence is quite logical -} ({When possible, in such structures, White should try to play} 20. cxb4 Rxc1 21. Rxc1 axb4 22. a4 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Gb2b3] This is a classical reaction to ...b5-b4. White wants to proceed with b2-b3. The control of the c-file and the protected passed pawn promise White a huge advantage in the endgame. At the same time, the weakness on d4 is irrelevant. Therefore, Black should play very energetically -} b3 $1 23. a5 Qb4 24. Qa6 Qd2 25. Nd3 h5 $13 {[%cal Gd7f6] Black has an excellent counterplay. He is ready to proceed with ...Nf6-e4.}) 20... axb4 21. c4 dxc4 22. Rxc4 Nb6 23. Rxc8+ Rxc8 $15 {Black is slightly better in view of the vulnerable IQP. At the same time. White has enough counterplay to balance the position.} 24. Nf3 Qd5 25. h3 h6 26. Qd2 Qb3 27. Rc1 Rxc1+ 28. Qxc1 Nc4 29. Ne5 Nxe5 30. dxe5 Qd3 31. Qa1 Qd4 32. Qc1 Qxe5 33. Qd2 Qe4 34. f3 Qc4 35. Kf2 g6 36. Ke3 e5 37. Qd3 Qc1+ 38. Qd2 Qc5+ 39. Kd3 Kg7 40. Qe3 Qd5+ 41. Kc2 Qc4+ 42. Kd2 Qc7 43. Qe4 Qc5 44. Qe3 Qa5 45. Kc2 Qa4+ 46. Kc1 Qb5 47. Kc2 Qc4+ 48. Kd2 Qd5+ 49. Kc2 h5 50. Qe4 Qxe4+ 51. fxe4 f5 52. exf5 gxf5 53. Kb3 e4 54. Kxb4 f4 55. Kc4 h4 56. b4 Kf6 57. Kd4 e3 58. Kd3 Ke5 59. Ke2 Kd4 60. b5 Kc5 61. g3 hxg3 62. Kf3 Kxb5 63. h4 Kc4 64. h5 g2 65. Kxg2 e2 66. Kf2 Kd3 67. Ke1 Ke3 68. h6 f3 69. h7 f2# 0-1

