1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Be6 7. c4 { With this move, White not only grabs space but also takes the d5-square from our bishop. Later on, he can establish a strong pawn centre with d2-d4. On the downside, White is not sufficiently developed. The queen can be easily harassed by means of ...Nd7-f6. Hence, in many cases, White's centre often tends to be vulnerable. } 7... Nd7 { [%cal Gd7f6] The most logical continuation. The next move is going to be ...Nf6. Depending on where the white queen will go, Black can consider ...Bf5 followed by ... e7-e6, ...Bg4, or ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7. In this game, White played the straightforward but dubious } 8. Ng5 { The move invites an exchange operation which tends to be favourable for Black. The game continued } 8... Nf6 9. Nxe6 { This is practically forced. If the queen retreats somewhere, Black will answer with ...Bf5 (g4) and ...e7-e6. In such a case, it's not clear what the knight is doing on g5. } 9... Nxe4 10. Nxd8 Rxd8 { Black is already slightly better. The drawback of the advance c2-c4 becomes obvious now. The weakness of the d4-square is quite annoying for White. In this position, White played } 11. b4 { White grabs space on the queenside and takes the c5-square under control. The idea is to follow with d2-d3 when Black will be unable to answer with the thematic ...Nc5. On the downside, White's position is way too overextended here. } 11... e6 { The most natural move. Now. White cannot play d2-d3 since the b4-pawn is hanging with check. } 12. a3 Be7 { With this passive move, White practically admits the failure of his opening strategy. } 13. Be2 ( { The problem is that } 13. d3 { is well met by } 13... Nd6 $15 { [%cal Gd6f5] followed by ...Nf5. Black is better in view of the weak d4-square. } ) 13... O-O 14. Ra2 Rd7 $17 { [%cal Gf8d8] Black is ready to double the rooks on the d-file. White is doomed to passivity. } 15. f3 Nd6 16. g4 Rfd8 ( 16... Bg5 $17 { [%cal Gf8d8,Gg5f4] } ) 17. d3 Bf6 18. h4 Ne8 19. Kf2 Nc7 20. Rd1 Bxh4+ 21. Kg2 e5 22. Rh1 Be7 23. Rh5 Bf6 24. g5 Be7 25. f4 exf4 26. Bxf4 Ne6 27. Be3 g6 28. Rh4 Bxg5 29. Bxg5 Nxg5 30. a4 Re8 31. b5 c5 32. Kf2 Kg7 33. a5 Rd6 34. Rg4 h6 35. Rg3 f5 36. Bf1 f4 37. Rg4 Rf6 38. Re2 Rxe2+ 39. Bxe2 b6 40. a6 Ne6 41. Bf3 Nd4 42. Bd5 g5 43. Rg1 Nf5 44. Kf3 Ne3 45. Ke4 Kg6 46. d4 cxd4 47. Kxd4 h5 48. Be4+ Kh6 49. c5 bxc5+ 50. Kxc5 g4 51. Re1 h4 52. Bc6 h3 53. b6 axb6+ 54. Kxb6 Nd5+ 55. Kc5 Rxc6+ 56. Kxc6 Nb4+ 57. Kd6 Nxa6 58. Ke5 f3 59. Kf4 f2 60. Rf1 Kh5 61. Rxf2 Nc5 62. Rd2 Ne6+ 63. Kg3 Ng5 64. Rd5 h2 65. Kxh2 Kh4 66. Kg2 Nf3 67. Kf2 Ng5 68. Ke3 Nh3 69. Rf5 Kg3 70. Rf8 Kh2 71. Rg8 g3 72. Kf3 Ng1+ 73. Kg4 Kg2 74. Ra8 Nh3 75. Ra2+ Nf2+ 76. Kf4 Kh2 77. Kf3 Kh3 78. Ra8 Kh2 79. Rg8 Nh1 80. Rh8+ Kg1 81. Rh7 1-0[Event "Titled Tuesday intern op 29th Nov Late"]
