{This is another instructive example featuring the exchange operation initiated by 8.Ng5. The first 10 moves are the same as the previous game.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Be6 7. c4 Nd7 8. Ng5 Nf6 9. Nxe6 Nxe4 10. Nxd8 Rxd8 11. d3 {This is White's main move. The idea is to follow with Be3. Still, White needs to play precisely in order to equalize. The critical position arises after} Nc5 12. Be3 e5 13. O-O-O Ne6 {[%cal Gf8c5] This is a key move in Black's strategy. The idea is to execute the strategically favourable exchange of the dark-squared bishops by means of ...Bc5. This exchange would allow Black to get firm control of the d4-square.} 14. g3 {The most logical move. White wants to continue with Bh3, thus exchanging the problematic light-squared bishop for the black knight.} Bc5 15. Bh3 {White follows his idea.The following couple of moves are quite logical -} ({According to the computer, White should have initiated a dynamic play by means of} 15. Bxc5 Nxc5 16. b4 Ne6 17. Re1 f6 18. f4 {Without this resource, White's position would have been strategically terrible. Black, however, has a nice positional solution at his disposal -} Ke7 19. fxe5 f5 $13 {[%cal Gd8d7,Ga7a5] with an excellent compensation for the pawn. Black is going to proceed with ...Rd7 followed by ...a7-a5. The weaknesses on the d-file, as well as the problematic white bishop, give Black an excellent play.}) 15... Bxe3+ 16. fxe3 Ke7 17. Kc2 h5 18. Bxe6 Kxe6 $15 {Black is slightly better in this rook endgame due to the following factors: 1) Pressure along the d-file 2) Good central control 3) Mobile kingside pawns 4) Active king We are now ready to create more weaknesses with ...f7-f5 followed by ...h5-h4. I will not comment on the remaining part of the game since it's not related to the opening.} 19. h3 Rh6 ({Another option would have been} 19... f5 {[%cal Gh5h4]}) 20. Rhf1 Rg6 21. Rf3 $2 (21. Rg1 a5 $15) 21... Rg5 (21... e4 $19 22. dxe4 Rxd1 23. Kxd1 Rf6 $19) 22. Rdf1 f6 23. Kc3 Rh8 24. d4 e4 25. Rf4 Rxg3 26. Rxe4+ Kf7 27. h4 Re8 28. Rxe8 Kxe8 29. Kd3 Rh3 30. Rf4 Ke7 31. Ke4 g6 32. d5 c5 33. d6+ Ke6 34. d7 f5+ 0-1

