{Now, we shall take a brief look at two of my online blitz games featuring some classical Caro-Kann\/Scandinavian structures that might arise after 7.c4.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Be6 7. c4 Nd7 8. d4 {This is White's usual continuation. Of course, there is nothing more logical than seizing space in the centre. Obviously, Black answers with} Nf6 {Now, White faces an important choice. Depending on the position of the white queen, Black will decide on the future of his light-squared bishop. In the following games, we will examine different queen retreats. In this particular game, my opponent played} 9. Qh4 {In my opinion, this move is not challenging since it allows Black's optimal setup -} Bf5 10. Be2 e6 {If you manage to get this typical position, without running into tactical problems, you are doing fine. Black has a very solid position without weaknesses. Also, the fact that a pair of knights has been exchanged reduced the impact of White's space advantage.} 11. O-O Be7 {It becomes clear that the white queen is misplaced. Therefore, my opponent spent a tempo on} 12. Qf4 O-O 13. b3 h6 {When you find time, try to include this move. It's always useful to make room for the light-squared bishop.} 14. Bb2 Qa5 {This is a typical way of connecting the rooks in Scandinavian structures. Besides the obvious idea of ...Rfd8, Black also wants to exchange the dark-squared bishops via a3. Such an exchange will further weaken White's centre. Additionally, in this structure, the queen is very well placed on the 5th rank. For instance, at any moment, Black can consider ...Bg4 followed by ...Qf5.} ({Another quite typical idea is} 14... a5 {The threat of ...a5-a4 is very annoying for White. In such a case, White should reckon with both ...a4-a3 and ...axb3. Therefore, White often answers this advance with} 15. a3 {planning to meet ...a5-a4 with b3-b4. Now, however, Black can use the weakness of the b3-pawn by means of} Qb6 {Suddenly, it transpires that White does not have a very comfortable way of defending the b3-pawn. For instance,} 16. Qe3 {will be answered with} Rfd8 {[%cal Gc6c5] when Black is all set for the thematic advance ...c6-c5.}) 15. a3 {There are two ideas behind this move: 1) preventing the exchange of the dark-squared bishops 2) freeing the a1-rook Now, I have decided to play for simplifications with} Bg4 16. Rfd1 Qf5 {Black is always ready for an endgame in this structure. Of course, White declines the invitation with} 17. Qe3 ({The move} 17. Qc7 {should be seriously considered. Nevertheless, after} Rfe8 18. Qxb7 Rab8 19. Qxc6 Rxb3 20. Bc1 Reb8 $13 {Black's piece activity provides an excellent compensation for the pawn.}) 17... Rfd8 18. h3 Bxf3 {This is another typical exchange in such structures. Usually, Black follows with a strong pressure on the d4-pawn. On the other hand, the bishop pair is not such an important factor in this position.} 19. Bxf3 Rd7 20. Rd3 Rad8 {Black keeps increasing the pressure on d4.} ({I have missed the move} 20... e5 {which would have created practical problems for White.}) 21. Rad1 a6 $6 {This move is way too passive.The game went} ({A very nice idea would have been} 21... h5 $13 {[%cal Ge7d6,Gd6f4] after which Black can eventually consider the maneuver ... Bd6-f4. The advance ...h6-h5 prevents White from gaining space on the kingside.}) 22. Qe2 Qf4 $6 {Another passive move that plays into White's hand.} 23. g3 Qc7 24. Kg2 Re8 25. h4 $16 {White has a stable advantage in this position. Since the centre is well-protected, White can slowly prepare his kingside expansion based on g3-g4-g5.} Red8 26. Qc2 Rc8 27. Qe2 Rcd8 28. Qe3 Re8 29. Qe5 Bd6 30. Qe2 e5 31. dxe5 Bxe5 32. Bxe5 Rxd3 33. Bxc7 Rxe2 34. Bxe2 Rxb3 35. Rd8+ Kh7 36. Be5 Ne4 37. Rd3 Rb1 38. Re3 f5 39. f3 Nc5 40. Bd4 Nb3 41. Bd3 Rd1 42. Bxf5+ g6 43. Rxb3 gxf5 44. Rxb7+ Kg6 45. Be3 Rd3 46. Kf2 Rxa3 47. Rb6 Ra2+ 48. Kf1 Ra3 49. Ke2 Ra2+ 50. Bd2 a5 51. Rxc6+ Kf7 52. Rxh6 a4 53. Ra6 Ra1 54. h5 a3 55. h6 a2 56. h7 Rh1 57. Rxa2 Rxh7 58. Ra7+ 1-0

