{This is another online blitz game of mine. Since it was played without increment, the quality of play is far from optimal. Nevertheless, I find it instructive in terms of understanding the pawn structure. The first 8 moves repeat the previous game} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Be6 7. c4 Nd7 8. d4 Nf6 9. Qe3 {I find this move more logical than 9.Qh4 which was played in the previous game. Still, it allows our perfect setup based on} Bf5 10. Be2 e6 {We can safely say that Black has already solved the opening problems.} 11. O-O h6 {Once again, I include this generally useful move.} ({An active and objectively good way of development would have been} 11... Bd6 12. h3 O-O $13 {In this structure, the idea behind ...Bd6 is increasing the control of the e5-square. At some point, Black will proceed with ...Qc7 followed by ...c6-c5. Hence, in this setup, it will be very difficult for White to establish a knight on e5.}) 12. b3 Be7 13. Bb2 O-O 14. Rad1 {With some minor differences, the position is quite similar to the previous game. Once again, I opted for} Qa5 {Given the fact that the white rook is not on a1, this move is even more justified now.} ({It goes without saying that} 14... a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] planning ...a5-a4 remains a perfectly valid option.}) 15. a3 Rad8 16. Qc1 Rfe8 ({As usual, Black can play} 16... Qb6 {This move makes a lot of sense when White has already played a2-a3. For instance, now, 17.Qc3 is well met by ...Ne4. Another point is that after} 17. b4 $6 a5 $15 {White will find himself with queenside weaknesses.}) 17. b4 {We should never be afraid of this move. As a rule, we welcome every move which overextends the queenside.} Qc7 {Now, in any moment, White should reckon with the advance ...a7-a5.} 18. h3 Ne4 {This typical blitz move was played with the idea of ...Bf6. Also, at any moment, the idea of exchanging a pair of knights by means of ...Ng5 comes into consideration.} ({Even better would have been to start with} 18... a5 {when after} 19. Bc3 Ne4 {gains in power. White should already be careful with his overextended position. The following sequence illustrates the nature of play in such positions.} 20. Rfe1 axb4 21. axb4 Ra8 22. Bd3 Nxc3 23. Qxc3 Bxd3 24. Rxd3 Ra2 $15 {Black is slightly better. White's pawns on the 4th rank can easily become targets.}) 19. Rfe1 Bf6 {This is a step in the wrong direction. The bishop is better placed on e7 from where it puts pressure on b4.} ({Therefore, better would have been} 19... a5 $13) 20. Bd3 $6 {This dubious move allows Black to force favourable simplifications.} ({White should have stabilized the position with a move such as} 20. Qe3 $14 {, thus keeping a slight advantage.}) 20... Ng5 $1 {This is the point. Now, after} 21. Bxf5 Nxf3+ 22. gxf3 exf5 $13 {the position is objectively balanced, but Black's play is practically easier due to the vulnerable white king. Eventually, I managed to win the game.} 23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. d5 Bxb2 25. Qxb2 cxd5 26. cxd5 Qf4 27. Qc3 Rd8 28. Rd4 Qg5+ 29. Kh2 Rd6 30. Qe3 Qd8 31. Qe5 Qd7 32. a4 Kh7 33. Rd2 a6 34. a5 Kg8 35. Qd4 Qd8 36. Qe5 Rg6 37. Qxf5 Qd6+ 38. f4 Qxb4 39. Rc2 Qe1 40. Rc8+ Kh7 41. h4 Qg1+ 42. Kh3 Qg2# {Normal} 0-1

