{Sometimes, White tries to prevent the moves ...Bf5 and ...Bg4. In such cases, we will play setups based on ...g7-g6 followed by ...Bg7. In the following couple of games, we will see how to handle this type of positions. Let's start with another online blitz game of mine.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Be6 7. c4 Nd7 8. d4 Nf6 9. Qd3 {This retreat is designed to prevent ...Bf5. At the same time, the alternative ... Bg4 can be countered with Ne5. Nevertheless, we have a third option at our disposal -} g6 {This move is good in three cases: 1) when ...Bf5 and ...Bg4 are impossible 2) when White has wasted some tempis 3) when we have a clear idea of how to solve the problem with our misplaced light-squared bishop Provided that we don't have problems with the light-squared bishop, the dark-squared bishop is excellently placed on g7. Besides putting strong pressure on the d4-pawn, the bishop makes it impossible for White to develop a kingside attack. The following couple of moves are quite natural.} 10. Be2 Bg7 11. O-O O-O 12. b3 Bg4 $1 {I award this move with an exclamation mark mainly because of it's instructive value. After completing the development, sorting out the problem with the light-squared bishop is our main priority. Black will eventually exchange the bishop for the white knight.} 13. Bb2 e6 14. h3 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Qa5 {Once again, we see this typical move. If allowed, Black will start putting pressure on the d4-pawn by means of ...Rfd8 followed by the maneuver ...Ne8-d6-f5. The queen can eventually go to the kingside.} 16. a4 Rfd8 17. Bc3 Qg5 {Given the fact that this is a blitz game, I wanted to keep more tension in the position.} ({Even better would have been} 17... Qf5 18. Qe3 {It goes without saying that White should refrain from the exchange of the queens.} h5 $1 {Remember this advance which is quite thematic for the pawn structure. Besides preventing White from gaining space on the kingside, Black also prepares the maneuver ...Nh7-g5. Combined with doubling the rooks along the d-file, this maneuver will add tension to the position. The following sample line is quite characteristic.} 19. Rfd1 Rd7 20. Rac1 Rad8 21. b4 Nh7 22. a5 Ng5 23. Be2 Qe4 $13 {Black managed to execute all of his ideas. White is under a lot of pressure since his position tends to be quite overextended.}) 18. b4 Qh4 {Another move which is designed to keep the tension in the position. I was already planning the maneuver ...Nd7-e5. Even though the position is objectively balanced, playing with White is quite difficult because his centre often becomes a target.} ({The alternatives} 18... Ne8) ({and} 18... Rd7 {fit into the spirit of the position as well.}) 19. b5 Nd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7e5] This strong move was probably underestimated by my opponent. The idea is ... Ne5.} 20. Qe4 $6 {This is already a huge inaccuracy. When you gain some experience in this type of position, you will see that your opponents will make a lot of seemingly unprovoked mistakes.} Qxe4 21. Bxe4 Rac8 {Black follows the same policy - keeping maximum tension in the position. White should now reckon with the threat of ...cxb5.} ({Objectively speaking, stronger would have been} 21... Nc5 {when after} 22. dxc5 Bxc3 23. Rad1 Bd4 24. bxc6 bxc6 25. Bxc6 Rab8 26. g3 Bxc5 $15 {Black is slightly better in view of his superior bishop. Additionally, the f2-pawn is a very nice target.}) 22. Ba5 $2 {After this mistake, White's position is falling apart.} ({White should have played} 22. bxc6 bxc6 23. Ba5 {Now, the following sequence seems quite logical:} Bxd4 24. Bxd8 Bxa1 25. Rxa1 Rxd8 26. Rd1 Kf8 27. Bxc6 Ke7 28. Bxd7 Rxd7 29. Rb1 $15 {/= Black is marginally better but White should be able to hold this endgame.}) 22... b6 23. bxc6 Nb8 {At this point, my opponent resigned since his position collapses.} ({Of course, even better would have been} 23... Nf6 $19 {winning a piece.}) 0-1

