{ The following example shows how well the setup with ...Bg7 works when White is playing slow moves. } 1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Be6 7. c4 Nd7 8. b3 { Played with the obvious intention to activate the dark-squared bishop via the long diagonal. Nevertheless, this slow approach neglects the development of the kingside. } 8... Nf6 9. Qe3 g6 { Even though there is nothing wrong with ...Bf5, when our opponent plays slow (and non standard) moves, we often prefer to fianchetto the bishop. } 10. Bb2 Bg7 11. d4 O-O 12. h3 { As already explained, in this structure, the light-squared bishop is Black's biggest problem. Therefore, with his last move, White prevents the move ...Bg4. The problem is that White is way behind in the development. } ( { Of course, in case of } 12. Be2 { Black would have played } 12... Bg4 { getting ready to exchange the light-squared bishop for the knight. The game might continue } 13. O-O Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Qc7 15. Rfe1 e6 16. Rad1 Rfd8 $13 { Black has sufficient counterplay in view of the possibility to put pressure on d4. } ) 12... b5 $1 { This thematic advance is the most energetic way of using White's lag in development. } 13. Bc3 bxc4 14. bxc4 Ne8 { Black keeps increasing the pressure. The next move is going to be ...Nd6. White's position is way too overextended. } 15. Ne5 Qc7 { This is the human approach to the position. } ( { The computer suggests } 15... Qc8 $5 { [%cal Gc8a6] keeping the option of ...Qa6 under favourable circumstances. } ) 16. Bd3 Nd6 17. g4 $2 { This is already a huge mistake. After this move, White cannot find a safe heaven for the king. } ( { Normal would have been } 17. O-O Nf5 18. Bxf5 Bxf5 $13 { with a balanced position. } ) 17... Rac8 18. Qe2 c5 $17 { After this advance, White's position is falling apart. The tactical justification is } 19. d5 Bxd5 20. cxd5 c4 $17 { [%cal Gd6b5] with ...Nb5 to follow. Black has a huge advantage and later won the game. } 21. Bxg6 Nb5 22. Bxh7+ Kxh7 23. f4 Nxc3 24. Qc2+ Kg8 25. Qxc3 f6 26. Nc6 Qxf4 27. Nxe7+ Kf7 28. Nf5 Rfe8+ 29. Kd1 Rc5 30. Rc1 Rxd5+ 31. Kc2 Rb8 32. Qe3 Rxf5 33. Qxa7+ Kg8 34. gxf5 Qe4+ 35. Kd2 Bh6+ 0-1[Event "?"]
