{In this game, we will start examining White's most principled variation - 7.b3. The starting position arises after the moves} 1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Be6 7. b3 {The most ambitious continuation. After putting the bishop on the active b2-square, White can consider castling long. In this line, he often tries to attack on the kingside. In this position, Black's main move is by far 7...Nd7. Nevertheless, I have decided to provide a solid alternative that does not require any theoretical knowledge. In this game, Solak played} Bd5 8. Qe3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Qd5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge7e6] Black is aiming for the reliable Caro-Kann/ Scandinavian structure which will be achieved with the moves ...Nd7 and ... e7-e6. Of course, White should refrain from exchanging the queens on d5. The arising Carlsbad structure with colours reversed is very good for Black. The most ambitious approach to the position is} 10. Qe3 Nd7 11. Bb2 e6 12. O-O-O {This plan is the critical test for Black's concept. By keeping the queens on the board, White shows his intention of attacking on the kingside. In order to secure his king's safety, Black should castle long. Solak played} Nf6 13. Bc4 Qa5 {[%cal Gf8a3] This is the best square for the queen. By defending the a7-pawn, Black is preparing the move ...0-0-0. Another important positional idea is ...Ba3. Exchanging the dark-squared bishops is Black's dream in this structure. Having only a light-squared bishop, White would have nothing to oppose to Black's play on the dark squares.} 14. Kb1 O-O-O 15. Bc3 {This is an attempt to displace Black's queen. At the same time, White is overprotecting the d2-pawn.} ({The straightforward} 15. g4 {is well met by} Ba3 16. Bc3 Bb4 17. g5 Bxc3 18. dxc3 Nd7 $13 {when Black has an excellent counterplay in view of his superior structure and the tandem queen + knight.}) 15... Qc5 16. Qf3 Qh5 $1 {Black is consistent in his intention of exchanging the queens. It turns out that White cannot avoid the trade of the queens in a favourable way. The game went} 17. Qxh5 Nxh5 18. g3 Nf6 {Black is doing completely fine. As usual, he is interested in exchanging the dark-squared bishops. In that regard, a possible idea would be ...Bc5-d4. At the same time, the light-squared bishop is completely useless. After} 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. c3 f5 $11 {the position is equal but playing with Black is a bit easier since his bishop has better prospects. The game eventually ended in a draw.} 21. Be2 Kd7 22. Bh5 Ke7 23. f4 Bg7 24. Kc2 Rd7 25. Rhe1 Rhd8 26. Re3 a5 27. Bf3 Rd6 28. d4 b5 29. Red3 b4 30. c4 Bxd4 31. Bxc6 Bb6 32. Bg2 Rxd3 33. Rxd3 Bg1 34. Rxd8 Kxd8 35. h3 Bh2 36. g4 fxg4 37. hxg4 Bxf4 38. Kd3 Ke7 39. Bc6 f5 40. gxf5 exf5 41. Bb7 Kf6 42. Ba8 Ke5 43. Bb7 Bg5 44. Bc6 Be7 45. Bb7 Bc5 46. Bc6 Kf4 47. Bb7 Kg4 48. Bc6 Kh3 49. Ke2 Kg3 50. Bb7 h5 51. Bf3 h4 52. Bb7 h3 53. Bc6 Kf4 54. Bb7 Kg3 55. Bc6 Kh2 56. Kf1 Be7 57. Bb7 Kg3 58. Ke2 a4 59. Bc6 Bd6 60. Bb7 a3 61. Bc6 Kf4 62. Bb7 Ke5 63. Kd3 f4 64. Bf3 h2 65. Bh1 Bc5 1/2-1/2

