{This game is an excellent example of handling the thematic Caro-KannScandinavian pawn structure. After the moves} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Be6 7. b3 Bd5 8. Qe3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 {Black played} e6 {instead of the slightly more precise 9...Qd5 which was featured in the previous example. Nevertheless, in this particular line, the understanding of the pawn structure is far more important than the knowledge of concrete theory.} 10. Bb2 Nd7 11. Be2 {In my opinion, this plan is a little bit passive.} ({More ambitious would have been} 11. O-O-O Nf6 12. Bc4 {This is the best square for the bishop. Now, Black does not have the option of ...Qd5. White is now ready to expand on the kingside by means of g2-g4. Black can try to exchange the dark-squared bishops by playing} Bc5 13. g4 Bd4 {Nevertheless, I believe that after} 14. c3 Bb6 15. h4 $14 {White is retaining some initiative. Of course, it goes without saying that Black's position remains solid.}) 11... Nf6 12. O-O {The plan with 0-0 is quite harmless for Black. As a matter of fact, the white bishop is not well placed on b2 since it can be easily exchanged in the future.} Be7 13. Bd3 $6 {This is just a waste of time. White's seemingly active bishops will be easily neutralized.} ({More natural would have been} 13. d4 {when the game will continue with} O-O 14. c4 Qa5 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gd8d7,Ga8d8,Ge7a3] We have already examined similar positions. Since two pairs of minor pieces have been already exchanged, the impact of White's space advantage is heavily reduced. Black is ready to double the rooks on the d-file. At the same time, the threat of exchanging the dark-squared bishops via a3 is always in the air. In some cases, Black can even try to maneuver the dark-squared bishop to g7. White, on his turn, struggles to find a constructive plan.}) 13... O-O 14. Qh3 $6 {This is a dubious decision. Black wants to play ...g7-g6 anyway.} g6 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ge7f8,Gf8g7] With this move, Black not only restricts the light-squared bishop but is also planning to proceed with ...Re8 followed by ...Bf8-g7. Of course, another possibility would be ...Nd5 followed by ...Bf6. The following couple of moves are quite logical.} 15. Qh6 Re8 16. a4 a5 17. Bc4 Bf8 18. Qf4 Bg7 {Black managed to execute his perfect regroupment. Now, the threat is ...Nh5. White does not have any constructive ideas in this position.} 19. d4 {Black already has an obvious target - the d4-pawn. It's important to point out that the inclusion of the moves a2-a4 and ...a7-a5 also works in Black's favour. For instance, the advance c2-c4 will weaken the b4-square. In that sense, the d5-square is like a stronghold for the black knight.} Nd5 20. Qe4 Qf6 {Now, Black is ready to double the rooks on the d-file. The game continued} 21. Rad1 Red8 22. g3 Rd7 23. Rd2 Rad8 24. Rfd1 Qe7 {[%cal Ge7b4,Gd5c3] Black is planning to execute the slightly weakened b4-square by means of ...Qb4 followed by ...Nc3. In this case, the d4-pawn will become quite vulnerable. Even though the computer evaluates the position as equal, in a practical game, Black's play is easier. Eventually, the Italian grandmaster managed to win the game.} 25. Bf1 Qb4 26. c4 Nc3 27. Bxc3 Qxc3 28. Rd3 Qb4 29. h4 h5 30. Bg2 Qd6 31. f4 Bxd4+ 32. Kh1 Qc5 33. Bf3 Kg7 34. Kg2 Rd6 35. Qe2 Bf6 36. Rxd6 Rxd6 37. Rxd6 Qxd6 38. Qd1 Qa3 39. Kh3 Qb2 40. Qd3 Bd4 41. Bd1 Kf8 42. Bc2 Qa1 43. Bd1 f5 44. Qd2 Ke7 45. Bf3 Qc3 46. Qxc3 Bxc3 47. c5 Bd4 48. Be2 Bxc5 49. Bc4 Kf6 50. Kg2 Bd4 51. Kf3 e5 52. fxe5+ Bxe5 53. Kg2 Bc3 54. Kf3 Be1 55. Kf4 Bd2+ 56. Kf3 g5 57. hxg5+ Bxg5 58. Kf2 Ke5 59. Bf7 h4 60. gxh4 Bxh4+ 61. Ke3 Bg5+ 62. Kd3 Bh4 63. Be8 Ke6 64. Bg6 Bf2 65. Ke2 Bg1 66. Kf3 Ba7 67. Kf4 Bb8+ 68. Ke3 Ke5 69. Be8 Kd6 70. Bg6 Ke6 71. Be8 Kd5 72. Bd7 f4+ 73. Kd3 Kc5 74. Bg4 Kb4 75. Kc2 b5 76. axb5 cxb5 77. Bf3 Be5 78. Bc6 Bf6 79. Bd5 Bg7 80. Bc6 Be5 81. Bd5 a4 82. bxa4 Kxa4 83. Bc6 Kb4 84. Kd3 Kc5 85. Bf3 Bd6 86. Be4 Bc7 87. Bf3 Be5 88. Ke4 Bb8 89. Kd3 Kb4 90. Bc6 Bc7 91. Kd4 Bd6 92. Kd3 Kc5 93. Bf3 Be7 94. Ke4 Bg5 95. Kd3 Bh4 96. Ke4 Bg3 97. Kd3 Bf2 98. Ke4 Be3 99. Kd3 Kd6 100. Ke4 Kc6 101. Kd3+ Kc5 102. Kc3 Bg1 103. Kd3 Kb4 104. Bc6 Be3 105. Bd7 Bf2 106. Ke4 Bg3 107. Kd3 f3 108. Kc2 f2 109. Bh3 Ka3 110. Bf1 b4 111. Bc4 b3+ 112. Kb1 Bf4 113. Ba6 Kb4 114. Kb2 Be5+ 115. Kc1 Kc3 116. Kd1 b2 117. Bd3 b1=Q+ 118. Bxb1 f1=Q# 0-1

