{After showing a reliable alternative, I would like to start dealing with Black's main answer to 7.b3 - 7...Nd7. Let's start with one instructive game by GM Pavel Eljanov who is one of the biggest experts in this system.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Be6 7. b3 Nd7 {This is the most principled choice. Black is planning to proceed with ...Nf6 followed by either ...Bf5 or ...Bg4.} 8. Bb2 Nf6 9. Qe2 $6 {I find this continuation strategically dubious in view of Black's reaction in the game. As we will see in the following examples, 9.Qe3 and 9...Qb4 are much more challenging.} Bg4 {This is the point. As we have seen on many occasions so far, in this line, Black is more than happy to get rid of the light-squared bishop. Now, Eljanov will gladly exchange the bishop for the f3-knight.} 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 g6 $1 {As mentioned in the introduction, when Black manages to solve the problem with his light-squared bishop, it's better to develop the dark-squared bishop via g7. In this way we secure better protection of the king and also prepare an eventual exchange of the dark-squared bishops. Additionally, when White plays d2-d4, the g7-bishop will be putting pressure on the pawn. In the game, White played} 12. d4 {which is quite harmless.} ({An interesting try would have been} 12. Ba6 $5 {when Black should go for the following forced sequence -} Qc7 13. Bxf6 exf6 14. Qxf6 Rg8 {[%cal Gf8g7]} 15. Kf1 Be7 16. Re1 Kf8 17. Rxe7 Qxe7 18. Qxe7+ Kxe7 19. Bxb7 Rad8 20. Ke2 Kd6 $13 {During the game, Eljanov calculated this line and concluded that Black has an excellent play in this complex endgame.}) 12... Bg7 13. Be2 Qa5+ {I like this inclusion. The idea is to provoke the advance c2-c3. In this way, White not only closes the way of the b2-bishop but is also unable to castle long. The following couple of moves are quite logical.} 14. c3 O-O 15. O-O Rfd8 16. Rfe1 e6 17. Bf1 Nd5 {[%cal Gc6c5] Black has arranged his pieces in a perfect way. He is now threatening to carry out the thematic break ...c6-c5. After the eventual dxc5, Black will have an obvious advantage in view of his more active pieces and strong control of the d-file. In order to prevent this advance, White played} 18. a3 {The idea of this little pawn move is to answer ...c6-c5 with b3-b4.} ({After} 18. g3 c5 19. dxc5 Qxc5 $13 {we can witness Black's dream scenario. For the time being White has passive pieces and a queenside majority which is totally irrelevant. At the same time, After doubling the rooks on the d-file, Black can expand in the centre with ...e6-e5 followed by ...f7-f5, and ... e5-e4. In some cases, even the advance ...b7-b5-b4 might be an idea.}) 18... Qb6 19. Bc4 Qc7 {Before retreating the queen to the c7-square, Black wanted to provoke the move Bc4. White should now reckon with the advance ...b7-b5.} ({In my opinion, better would have been} 19... c5 {when White should go for the following sequence:} 20. Bxd5 Rxd5 21. c4 Rf5 22. dxc5 Rxf3 23. cxb6 Rxb3 24. Bxg7 Kxg7 25. bxa7 Rxa7 $15 {Even though White can hold with a precise play, Black retains excellent practical chances in this endgame.}) 20. a4 a5 {Still, Black is on the better side of the equality. In the game, Eljanov tried to win for a long time but White managed to keep everything together.} 21. Rad1 Rab8 22. Bc1 Qd7 23. Bg5 Re8 24. Bf1 h6 25. Bh4 Ne7 26. Bxe7 Qxe7 27. Qe4 Qa3 28. Qc2 Rbd8 29. Bd3 Re7 30. h4 h5 31. g3 Qd6 32. Re3 Qd7 33. Qe2 Qc7 34. Kg2 Rd6 35. Be4 Red7 36. Bf3 Qb6 37. Qc4 Bf6 38. Ree1 Kg7 39. Rb1 Qa7 40. Re2 Rc7 41. Re3 Rdd7 42. Ra1 Be7 43. Ra2 Rd8 44. Qe2 Bf6 45. Rd2 Qb8 46. Ra2 Rdd7 47. Rd3 Qd8 48. Be4 Rd6 49. Rf3 Kg8 50. Qc4 Bg7 51. Qc5 Rcd7 52. Qc4 Kh8 53. Qc5 f5 54. Bb1 Rd5 55. Qc4 c5 56. Re2 cxd4 57. Rxe6 R7d6 58. Rxd6 Qxd6 59. Qc8+ Qd8 60. Qxd8+ Rxd8 61. cxd4 Rxd4 1/2-1/2

