{In this blitz game of mine, we will see how Black can attack on the queenside when White has castled long. The first 9 moves are quite familiar to us.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Be6 7. b3 Nd7 8. Bb2 Nf6 9. Qh4 Bf5 {We have already seen this position. Black is planning to proceed with ...e7-e6 followed by ...Be7. At this point, White played} 10. Bc4 {Even though the bishop is actively placed on this position, it can potentially be chased aways by the advance ...b7-b5.} e6 11. O-O-O Be7 12. Qg3 $6 {In my opinion, this is just a waste of time. As we know, in positions with opposite castles, every single tempi is very important.} ({The most principled approach to the position would have been} 12. Nd4 Bg6 13. f4 O-O 14. g4 {This type of play is quite typical for the variation. White wants to deliver the advance f4-f5. At this point, it's important for Black to start with} Bc5 {kicking the knight back. After} 15. Nf3 Be4 16. Ng5 Bd4 $13 {Black has an excellent counterplay since he managed to neutralize the powerful b2-bishop.}) 12... O-O 13. h4 {White is planning to push the h-pawn all the way to h6. Such kind of attack, however, is quite slow.} a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] This is how I usually handle such positions. The idea is to follow with ...a5-a4.} ({According to the computer, even better would have been} 13... Qa5 14. Kb1 Rad8 15. h5 h6 $17 {with a huge advantage for Black. White does not have any constructive ideas. At the same time, Black can consider ...b7-b5 followed by the march of the c-pawn.}) 14. Nd4 a4 {This typical blitz move is not precise enough.} ({Black should have preserved his light-squared bishop by playing} 14... Bd6 15. Qe3 Bg6 $17 {with ...a5-a4 to follow. White does not have enough attacking resources.}) 15. Nxf5 exf5 16. h5 $2 {This move is already a huge mistake after which Black's attack becomes devastating.} ({White should have played} 16. bxa4 Rxa4 17. Bb3 {when the queenside is more or less stabilized.}) 16... b5 17. h6 g6 18. Bd3 axb3 19. axb3 Ba3 20. Bxa3 Rxa3 21. Kb2 Qd4+ 22. c3 Qa7 23. Qe5 Ra2+ 24. Kc1 Qa3+ 0-1

