{In this example, we shall take a look at the move 7.Be2 which leads to a typical Scandinavian structure.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Be6 7. Be2 {White does not have huge ambitions in the opening. He just wants to prepare the advance d2-d4 and obtain a stable position. The game went} Nd7 8. d4 Nf6 9. Qd3 {This is the best retreat square for the queen. The point is that White wants to prevent his opponent from playing ...Bf5 followed by ...e7-e6. Black, however, still has the option of playing} Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6] As always, Black needs to prioritize the future of the light-squared bishop. In this particular case, I don't like the plans with ...g7-g6 since then it will be difficult to find a good spot for the light-squared bishop.} 10. O-O e6 11. h3 Bh5 {The most natural move.} ({Another possibility would have been} 11... Bf5 12. Qd1 Bd6 13. c4 O-O 14. Re1 Qc7 $13 {I like this active setup because it does not give White the chance to occupy the e5-square. Additionally, Black is perfectly ready to execute the thematic ...c6-c5 break.}) 12. c4 Be7 {The setups with ...Be7 are a little bit more passive but very solid. The following couple of moves are quite natural.} 13. Be3 O-O 14. Rac1 Qc7 15. Ne5 Bxe2 16. Qxe2 Rfd8 {Since two pairs of minor pieces have been already exchaged, White's space advantage is not that significant. Additionally, the e5-knight is kind of unstable. Black can always undermine it's position by means of the thematic advance ...c6-c5. Therefore, White played the prophylactic} 17. Nd3 ({Another natural continuation would have been} 17. Rfd1 {In this case, Black's best strategy would be to carry out the thematic} c5 {The position arising after} 18. Rd3 Ne8 19. Nf3 h6 20. b3 cxd4 21. Bxd4 Bf6 $11 {is balanced. We have already discussed this structure in the introduction.}) 17... a5 {Gaining space by advancing the a-pawn is a typical strategy in this structure. Besides restricting the mobility of White's pawns, in this way, Black also tries to provoke queenside weaknesses.} ({Another very typical idea would have been} 17... Ne8 $13 {[%cal Ge7f6,Ge8d6,Gd6f5] Black wants to put maximum pressure on the d4-pawn. He is going to proceed with ...Bf6 followed by the maneuver ... Nd6-f5. At some point, White should take care of the vulnerable d4-pawn.}) 18. Rfd1 a4 19. Qf3 Rac8 {The idea of this move is to continue with ...b7-b6 followed by ...c6-c5. Black has an excellent counterplay. I leave the remaining part of the game without comments.} ({The move} 19... Ne8 {was possible again.}) 20. g4 b6 21. Kg2 c5 22. g5 Nd7 23. d5 exd5 24. cxd5 Bd6 25. Rc4 b5 26. Rh4 Nf8 27. Nf4 Ng6 28. Nxg6 hxg6 29. Re4 Re8 30. h4 Rxe4 31. Qxe4 Qd7 32. Qf3 Re8 33. h5 gxh5 34. Qxh5 Re4 35. Rh1 Kf8 36. Qf3 Qg4+ 37. Qxg4 Rxg4+ 38. Kf3 Rb4 39. Rb1 Ke7 40. Re1 Kd7 41. Re2 Rh4 42. b3 1/2-1/2

