{In this game of Eljanov, White tried another interesting continuation - 7.Qf4.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Be6 7. Qf4 {With this move, White sidesteps all the ideas based on ...Bd5 or ...Nd7-f6. Additionally, by putting the queen on f4, White makes it difficult for Black to play ...Bg4 or . ..Bf5 in the future. On the downside, the white queen is often vulnerable to the advance ...e7-e5. In the game, Eljanov went for the critical} Bd5 8. b3 Nd7 9. Bb2 f6 $1 {[%cal Ge7e5] This is the critical response. Black is planning to proceed with ...e7-e5 on the next move. In order to prevent this idea, White played} 10. d4 ({The position arising after} 10. O-O-O e5 {[%cal Gd8a5,Ge8c8] is quite favourable for Black. He is ready to proceed with ...Qa5 followed by . ..0-0-0. In this case, Black has an advantage.}) 10... Qa5+ $1 {Once again, Eljanov goes for the most precise continuation. Now, White should either exchange the queens or weaken his position by playing c2-c3.} 11. Qd2 {White has nothing better than this move.The following couple of moves are quite logical -} ({In case of} 11. c3 $2 e5 12. dxe5 O-O-O $17 {Black has a huge advantage due to the superior development.}) 11... Qxd2+ 12. Nxd2 O-O-O 13. O-O-O e5 {Black does not have any problems whatsoever. Moreover, he is already fighting for the initiative. Later on, Eljanov managed to outplay his opponent and win the game.} 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 fxe5 16. Nc4 $2 Bc5 $17 17. f3 e4 18. Be2 b5 19. fxe4 Bxe4 20. Bg4+ Kc7 21. Rhe1 Bxg2 22. Ne5 Rhe8 23. Nd3 Bd6 24. Rg1 Be4 25. Be2 g6 26. h4 h5 27. Kb1 Bf5 28. Bf3 Re3 29. Bh1 Bg3 30. Nb4 Rxd1+ 31. Rxd1 Be4 32. Na6+ Kb6 33. Bxe4 Rxe4 34. Nb8 Bxb8 0-1

