{This file features some options that are not discussed in the model games. I have used some of the analysis that GM Pavel Eljanov provided in his lecture for the Modern Chess camp Caro-Kann Defence - Pawn Structures, Tactical Ideas, Endgames, and Theoretical Trends. Of course, I modified them and made important additions.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 ({After} 5. Nxf6+ exf6 {White gets an inferior version of the similar structure that arises in the Open variation because the knight is usually placed better on e2 than f3 in such positions.} 6. d4 ({Another way for White is} 6. Bc4 Bd6 7. Qe2+ {trying to force the queen exchange as there is no 7... Be6 now. This is exactly how Karjakin played against me.} Qe7 (7... Be7 $5 {is an option if we would like to keep the queens on the board.} 8. O-O O-O 9. d4 Bd6 10. c3 Na6 11. Qc2 Re8 12. Nd2 Nc7 13. Bd3 g6 14. Ne4 Bf8 $11 {0-1 (43) Karjakin,S (2773) -Navara, D (2737) Saint Louis 2017}) 8. Qxe7+ (8. d4 Be6 9. O-O Bxc4 10. Qxc4 O-O 11. Re1 Qd7 12. Bd2 Na6 13. a3 Rfe8 $11 {1/2 (39) Vachier Lagrave,M (2779) -Nepomniachtchi,I (2775) Zagreb 2019}) 8... Kxe7 (8... Bxe7 $5 9. O-O Be6 {is also possible.}) 9. O-O Rd8 {Black is very solid in these endgames once he gets the king off the e-file.} 10. Re1+ ({In one of the recent GM games, Black equalized without problems after} 10. d4 Kf8 11. c3 Be6 12. Bb3 Nd7 13. Re1 Re8 14. Bxe6 {1/2 (14) Heimann,A (2624) -Donchenko,A (2631) Neumarkt in der Oberpfalz 2019}) 10... Kf8 11. d4 {1-0 (49) Paichadze,L (2550) -Arutinian, D (2551) Tbilisi 2020} a5 $5 12. a4 Na6 13. c3 Nc7 $11 {[%cal Gc8e6]}) 6... Bd6 7. Bd3 (7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Qc7 9. h3 Rd8 10. c3 Nd7 11. Qc2 Nf8 12. Be3 Be6 13. c4 Ng6 14. Bd3 Qd7 15. Bxg6 hxg6 16. Rfd1 Bxh3 17. gxh3 Qxh3 18. Qe2 Re8 19. d5 c5 {0-1 (19) Frolyanov, D (2556) -Ivanisevic, I (2593) Moscow 2019}) 7... O-O 8. O-O Bg4 (8... Re8 {is also a good option for Black.} 9. h3 Nd7 10. c3 Nf8 11. Qc2 Be6 12. Re1 Qd7 $13 {1-0 (59) Radjabov, T (2765) -Artemiev, V (2716) chess. com INT 2020}) 9. h3 Bh5 10. Re1 (10. Be4 Re8 11. Qd3 Bg6 12. Bxg6 hxg6 13. Bd2 Nd7 $11 {1/2 (51) Karthikeyan,M (2617) -Shtembuliak,E (2577) New Delhi 2019}) 10... Nd7 $13) 5... Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Be6 {This is the move that I prefer for Black. We develop the bishop and discourage White from playing d2-d4.} 7. b3 {This is the best way to fight for an advantage as White would like to develop his bishop to the long diagonal.} Nd7 8. Bb2 Nf6 9. Qe3 {Again, this is the best try among several alternatives.} ({According to the computer, White's most challenging option is} 9. Qb4 {In this case, Black's most practical solution would be going for an endgame after} Qc7 10. Bd3 Nd5 11. Qe4 Qf4 {The key move in our strategy. After the exchange of the queens, Black will enjoy a solid position. A logical follow-up would be} 12. c4 Qxe4+ 13. Bxe4 Nf6 14. Bc2 {At this point, Black should make a decision regarding the pawn structure. In my opinion, the most promising is} g6 ({The alternative} 14... Bg4 15. Nh4 e6 {is playable as well. For instance, after} 16. h3 Bh5 17. g4 Bg6 18. O-O-O Bd6 19. Rhe1 O-O $13 {we get a typical Caro-Kann/ Scandinavian structure which is quite reliable for Black.}) 15. O-O-O Bg7 16. Rde1 Nh5 {Another important idea. In order to avoid the exchange of the dark-squared bishops, White should play} 17. Ne5 {Hence, Black should no longer reckon with annoying ideas such as Nd4 and Ng5.} Rd8 $13 {Black has an excellent counterplay.}) 9... Nd5 $5 {This is a reasonable novelty, asking the queen where it will go and trying to play ...Bf5 in better circumstances.} (9... Bf5 10. Nd4 {was played in the game Nakamura-Lenderman in the US Championship.} Bg6 (10... Qd7 {is the alternative. Here, White has a choice of playable options to obtain a slight initiative based on this bishop pair advantage.} 11. Nxf5 (11. O-O-O {This would be my preference since after} Nd5 12. Qe2 {White can also put pressure on Bf5 with g2-g4 before taking it.} h5 13. g3 h4 14. Bg2 (14. Nxf5 Qxf5 15. Bg2 Nf6 16. f4 $14) 14... O-O-O 15. Nxf5 Qxf5 16. Be4 $14) 11... Qxf5 12. Bd3 Qh5 {1/2 (26) Bernadskiy,V (2554) -Shimanov,A (2587) Bastia 2019} 13. f4 $14) 11. f4 Qa5 12. Bc4 e6 13. f5 $1 Bxf5 14. O-O O-O-O 15. Nxf5 exf5 {Good attack and defense by both sides up to this point. White had some options, although black position is solid enough in all cases.} 16. Bxf7 (16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. c3 Kb8 18. Qf4+ Qc7 19. Qxc7+ Kxc7 20. d4 b5 21. Bxf7 Ba3 $11) (16. Bc3 Qc5 17. d4 Qd6 $1 18. Rxf5 Qxh2+ $1 {An important resource.} 19. Kxh2 Ng4+ 20. Kg1 Nxe3 $11) 16... Qxd2 $1 {This was better than the game continuation, although it seems risky for Black.} (16... Rxd2 17. Kh1 Ng4 18. Qe6+ Kb8 19. h3 Rd6 20. Qxf5 Qxf5 21. Rxf5 Nh6 22. Rf2 $16 {1/2 (144) Nakamura, H (2736) -Lenderman, A (2634) Lichess.org INT 2020 1/2 (144) Nakamura, H (2736) -Lenderman, A (2634) Lichess.org INT 2020}) 17. Be6+ $1 (17. Qxa7 Ne4 18. Be6+ Kc7 19. Be5+ Bd6 20. Rad1 Bxe5 $1 {Black holds thanks to this queen sacrifice.} 21. Rxd2 Rxd2 22. Qa5+ Kd6 23. Bc4 Bd4+ 24. Kh1 Nf2+ 25. Kg1 Ne4+ $11) 17... Kb8 18. Be5+ Ka8 19. Qxd2 Rxd2 20. Bxf5 Nd5 21. Rf3 Bc5+ 22. Kh1 Bd4 23. Bxd4 Rxd4 24. c4 $1 (24. Bxh7 Rh4) 24... Nc7 (24... Nf6 25. Re1 Rd2 26. a4 $16) 25. Bc2 g6 26. Kg1 {White keeps a slight edge in the endgame, but it should be drawish.}) 10. Qd3 {This should be the best choice for White as he prevents 10. ..Bf5 with this move.} (10. Qe2 Bf5 11. Nd4 Bg6 12. h4 h5 $11 {An important point behind Nd5 is that Black cannot play f2-f4 as Nakamura did in his game. Black has a reliable position.}) (10. Qd4 Bf5 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 e6 13. O-O Nf6 $11) (10. Qe5 Qc7 11. O-O-O {1-0 (44) Makhnev,D (2466) -Banzea,A (2394) Chess.com INT 2023} Qxe5 12. Nxe5 f6 13. Nc4 Bg4 14. Re1 O-O-O $13 {[%cal Ge7e5]}) 10... Nf6 $5 {This retreat is the best choice if Black is happy with a move repetition.White does not seem to have a good way to keep the queens on the board, so he should probably play the endgame after} (10... a5 $5 {is a reasonable alternative, trying to provoke a weakness on b4 if White goes 11.a4.} 11. a3 (11. c4 Nf6 12. Qe3 Bf5 13. Nh4 Bg6 $11) 11... Nf6 12. Qe3 Nd5 13. Qd3 Nf6 14. h3 Qxd3 15. Bxd3 Bd5 16. Be2 e6 17. c4 Be4 (17... Bxf3 $5 18. Bxf3 Be7 19. O-O O-O 20. d4 Rfd8 $11) 18. d3 Bg6 19. Ne5 Nd7 $11) 11. g3 ({or} 11. h4 {trying to gain some space on the kingside or develop the rook to h3.} h5 $5 (11... Qxd3 $5 12. Bxd3 Bd5 {should be equal with the bishop on b2.}) 12. Ng5 Qc8 13. O-O-O Bf5 14. Qg3 Qd7 15. Nf3 Ng4 16. Nd4 Bh7 $13 {Black will complete his development soon and have a solid position.}) 11... Qxd3 12. Bxd3 Bd5 13. Be2 Rd8 $11 {This position is quite reliable for Black. He can complete development with ...g6, . ..Bg7 and white's dark-squared bishop will be neutralized.} *

