{ This lecture deals with the extremely fashionable } 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 { This seemingly harmless system is a hard nut to crack. It's not a surprise that this line was tested by many top-level players. The main strategic justification of this setup is that White enjoys pleasant risk-free play in the symmetrical endgame arising after the exchange of the queens. The move 3... Bg4 is well met by 4.h3, trying to get the bishop pair. Additionally, White keeps the option of playing e4-e5. This advance is especially effective against the system with 3...g6. My choice for Black is } 3... Qc7 { This little queen move prepares a transition into a favourable symmetrical structure by means of ...dxe4 followed by ...e7-e5. This structure is quite favourable for Black in the long-term. In order to fight for an advantage, White should handle it very energetically. At this point, White has two main directions - 4.Nc3 and 4. exd5 followed by c2-c4. In this lecture, you will find in-depth analysis of these two moves. At the end of the lecture, you shall take a look at model games which explain how to handle the symmetrical structure when White plays passively. } *[Event "?"]
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.e4 c6 2.Nf3 d5 3.d3"]
[Black "3...Qc7 4.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B10"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[PlyCount "34"]
[SourceVersionDate "2024.02.29"]

{In this file, we are going to examine, White's most ambitious continuation -} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 Qc7 4. Nc3 {By putting pressure on d5, White tries to exploit the disadvantage of Black's last move. Additionally, White is going for a quickpiece development. On the downside, the knight is often misplaced in front of the c2-pawn which cannot be used in the fight for the centre.} dxe4 5. dxe4 {This is the most popular continuation. White not only fights for the centre but also opens the way for the light-squared bishop. His next move is going to be Bc4.} ({An interesting alternative is} 5. Nxe4 {Black has a wide range of options in this position, but I prefer} Nf6 {which is very much in the spirit of what I have suggested against the line 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 dxe4 4.Nxe4. White's most challenging move seems to be} 6. Qe2 {planning to take on e4 with the queen. Otherwise, Black will proceed with ...Nxe4 followed by ...e7-e5.} ({After} 6. Nxf6+ exf6 $13 {we see the thematic structure which was covered in the first installment of the Caro-Kann repertoire. In this particular position, the structure is favourable for Black in view of White's misplaced f3-knight.}) 6... Nxe4 7. Qxe4 Be6 {I have decided to recommend this creative move in order to stay in the spirit of our line against Two Knights Variation. It goes without saying that Black can play 7...Nd7 as well. We are now ready to proceed with the thematic maneuver ...Nd7-f6. In my opinion, White's most promising line goes} 8. c4 Nd7 9. Bd2 Nf6 10. Qe3 Bf5 11. Bc3 {Even in this case, however, Black can get a decent version of the typical Caro-Kann/ Scandinavian structure by playing} h6 {making room for the bishop in the event of Nh4.} 12. Ne5 e6 $13 {Black has a decent counterplay. We have discussed such structures in the previous lecture.}) 5... e5 {This thematic pawn structure can be reached via many different openings (often with colours reversed) . From a static point of view, Black is doing great due to the misplaced c3-knight. After developing his pieces with simple moves such as ... Nf6, ...Nbd7, ...Be7, and ...0-0, Black can consider expanding on the queenside by means of ...b7-b5. At the same time, Black often maneuvers one of his knights to the d4-square. Taking into account these considerations, White should try to pose concrete problems by playing very energetically. The best move is} 6. Bc4 {The bishop belongs to the a2-g8 diagonal. At the same time, White is ready to answer 6...Nf6 with 7.Ng5. At this point, Black should start with} b5 {It's important to include this move. Otherwise, White will secure the light-squared bishop by playing a2-a4. Note that this advance is a double-edged decision. Even though Black wins space, his queenside becomes a bit overextended. White can use this drawback by means of the typical a2-a4 advance.} 7. Bb3 h6 {Before developing his knight on f6, Black should start with this move. Otherwise, White will play Ng5.} 8. O-O {This is the traditional continuation. Before going for active continuations, White completes the development.} ({The main alternative is} 8. a4 {White makes use of Black's overextended queenside. The idea is to weaken the c4-square by provoking ...b5-b4. At the same time, however, Black often makes use of the space provided by the b4-pawn.} b4 9. Nb1 {The knight is heading to c4 via d2.} ({An important alternative is} 9. Ne2 Nf6 10. Ng3 {White is going for a kingside attack. Later on, he can proceed with Nh4-f5 followed by Qf3. In such a scenario, Black will find himself under very strong pressure.} ({A bit too slow is} 10. O-O {In this case, Black can play} Nbd7 11. Ng3 Ba6 12. Re1 O-O-O $13 {with ...Nc5 to follow. Suddenly, Black is the one who overtakes the initiative. White has problems to find a good spot for the queen.}) 10... c5 $1 {It turns out that this seemingly anti-positional advance is very effective in this pawn structure. Besides winning space on the queenside, Black secures the c6-square for the knight. This idea is especially good when the white knights are far away from the c4/d5 complex.} 11. Bd5 {This move marks the beginning of a forced sequence which does not promise White any advantage.} ({The calm approach} 11. Bc4 Nc6 12. c3 {can easily enable Black to fight for an advantage. For instance, the following line provides a good illustration of Black's ideas in this structure.} bxc3 13. bxc3 Be7 14. O-O O-O 15. Nh4 Na5 $17 {Black has an obvious advantage. The c4-bishop can no longer stay on the diagonal a2-g8. When the bishop retreats somewhere, Black is ready to answer with ...c5-c4, gaining even more space.}) 11... Nxd5 12. Qxd5 Bd6 {This simple move solves all the problems. It turns out that the rook in untouchable in view of ...Bb7, and ...Nc6. The most logical continuation seems to be} 13. Nf5 Bxf5 14. exf5 Qc6 15. Qxc6+ Nxc6 $11 {when the position is equal.}) ({The continuation} 9. Nb5 {leads to a forced play which will result in a draw if both sides play precisely. The following couple of moves are pretty forced} cxb5 10. Bd5 Bb7 11. Nxe5 Bxd5 12. Qxd5 Nf6 13. Qxa8 Qxe5 14. Qb7 {So far, everything was forced. This position was reached in the game 1-0 (22) Bick, G (2391) -Atwell,R (2024) Los Angeles 2023.Now, Black should go for the complications arising after} ({A mistake is} 14. Be3 $2 {when after} Bd6 {White does not have compensation for the sacrificed material. In the only game which featured this position, White played} 15. Rd1 $2 {which is another mistake.0-1 (37) Ongut, T (2281) -Berczes, D (2446) Hungary 2022 At this point, Black could have played} bxa4 16. Qxa7 O-O $19 {with a winning position.}) 14... Bc5 $1 15. Qc8+ Ke7 16. Qxh8 Bxf2+ 17. Kxf2 Nxe4+ {Black is out of risk due to the vulnerable white king. It's not a surprise that all the lines end with a perpetual.} 18. Kf3 {The most natural move.} ({Another possible line would be} 18. Kf1 Qf5+ 19. Ke2 Qf2+ 20. Kd1 Qxg2 21. Re1 Qf3+ 22. Re2 Qf1+ 23. Re1 Qf3+ $11 {with a perpetual.}) 18... Nc6 19. Be3 {Covering the d4-square is White's most logical reaction.} ({I have also tried} 19. Rd1 {You can take a look at the following funny line which ends in a draw.} Qf5+ 20. Ke3 Qf2+ 21. Kxe4 Qe2+ 22. Be3 Qxg2+ 23. Kd3 Ne5+ 24. Kd4 Qg4+ 25. Bf4 Qxf4+ 26. Kd5 Qc4+ 27. Kxe5 f6+ 28. Kf5 Qxc2+ 29. Kf4 Qf2+ 30. Ke4 Qe2+ 31. Kd4 Qe5+ 32. Kd3 Qd5+ 33. Kc2 Qc4+ 34. Kb1 Qe4+ $11 {Despite having two extra rooks, White cannot escape the perpetual.}) 19... Qh5+ 20. Kxe4 Qg4+ 21. Kd3 Ne5+ 22. Kd2 Qxg2+ 23. Bf2 Qd5+ 24. Ke2 Qf3+ 25. Kf1 Qxh1+ 26. Ke2 Qe4+ $11 {with a draw.}) 9... Nf6 10. Nbd2 c5 {[%cal Gb8c6] Even though the white knight has direct access to the c4-square, I like this natural approach. We are ready to follow with ...Nc6. After the moves} 11. O-O Nc6 12. Re1 Be7 {White is at a crossroads. An interesting continuation seems to be} 13. Bd5 {trying to exploit the weakness of the d5-square. White is planning to continue with Bxc6 followed by b2-b3 and Bb2.} ({More traditional way of handling the structure would be} 13. c3 {In this case, however, Black can fight for an advantage.} O-O 14. Qc2 Rb8 {An important move in such structures. Black makes use of the space provided by the b4-pawn. The queenside tension is particularly annoying for White since he should always reckon with ...bxc3.} 15. Bc4 {An attempt to stabilize the queenside. If allowed White will probably continue with Nb3 on the next move.} ({After} 15. Nc4 $6 Be6 {Black is already better due to the vulnerable b3-bishop. The following sample line illustrates one of Black's tactical ideas in this type of position.} 16. Bd2 bxc3 17. bxc3 $2 Rxb3 18. Qxb3 Na5 $19 {Black is winning a piece.}) 15... bxc3 16. bxc3 Na5 $15 {Once again, we see this thematic idea. In case of Ba2, Black will gladly play ...c5-c4. At the same time, Bf1 will be answered with ...Be6 with an advantage for Black.}) 13... Bb7 14. Bxc6+ {White should play this move before Black manages to put his rook on d8.} ({The position arising after} 14. Nc4 Rd8 15. Bxc6+ Bxc6 16. Qe2 Bxe4 17. Nfxe5 O-O $15 {is better for Black in view of his better development and powerful bishop pair.}) 14... Bxc6 15. b3 Rd8 16. Qe2 {White will be trying to prove that the weakness of the c4-square is more relevant than Black's space advantage on the queenside. It turns out, however, that Black can challenge the blockade on the light squares by means of} Bb7 17. Bb2 Nd7 18. Nc4 Ba6 $13 {Black has an excellent counterplay. After ...f7-f6, we can either play ...Nb6 or maneuver the knight all the way to d4.}) ({Surprisingly challenging continuation is the rare} 8. Qe2 {White's idea can be seen after} Nf6 9. a4 b4 10. Nd1 {Via d1, the knight will land on the wonderful e3-square. In this case, our ideas with ...c6-c5 will be less effective. We should therefore use the c5-square for the knight. Black's most precise reaction is} Nbd7 11. Ne3 Nc5 {The problem is that after} 12. Nc4 {Black should decide how to handle the pressure on e5. In my opinion, we should opt for the following sequence -} Be6 13. Ncxe5 Bxb3 14. cxb3 Bd6 15. Nc4 Ncxe4 16. Be3 O-O {Black has an excellent counterplay. His active piece play provides enough compensation for the weakened queenside. According to the computer, White's best continuation is} 17. O-O-O {The white rook immediately joins the game while the king will find a safe shelter on b1 or a2.At this point, Black should first exchange the e3-bishop by means of} ({Nothing gives} 17. O-O {when after} Bc5 18. Rad1 Bxe3 19. Nxe3 Rfe8 $13 {[%cal Gc6c5] Black has an excellent position. He is ready to follow with ...c6-c5.}) 17... Bf4 {After} 18. Kb1 Bxe3 19. Nxe3 Rfe8 20. Rhe1 c5 21. Qc2 {[%cal Ge3c4] the computer tries to speculate on the slightly unstable e4-knight. White is planning to continue with Nc4 followed by doubling the rooks on the e-file. It turns out, however, that after} Qf4 22. Nc4 Re6 23. Re2 Rae8 24. Rde1 g6 $11 {Black has nothing to worry about since White is unable to improve the position.}) 8... Nf6 9. Re1 {Before going for a2-a4 followed by Ne2, White wants to overprotect the important e4-pawn.} ({More straightforward is} 9. a4 b4 10. Ne2 {White is planning to generate his typical kingside activity starting with Ng3. In this case, Black should probably continue with} Nbd7 {sticking to the plan based on ...Ba6 and ...Nc5.} ({The problem is that the strategically desirable} 10... c5 $6 {runs into} 11. Nxe5 Qxe5 12. Bf4 $16 {when White has tremendous compensation for the sacrificed piece.}) ({If Black wants to stick to the plan with ...c6-c5, he should start with} 10... Be7 {and only after} 11. Ng3 {continue with} c5 {In this case, we should be ready to play a position with compensation after sacrificing the e5-pawn in order to obtain the bishop pair. The critical continuation is} 12. Bd5 Nc6 13. Nxe5 ({After} 13. Bxc6+ Qxc6 14. Nxe5 Qe6 15. Nd3 O-O $44 {Black's bishop pair, good development, and space advantage on the queenside give him an excellent compensation for the pawn.}) 13... Nxd5 14. Nxc6 Nc3 15. bxc3 Qxc6 $44 {Once again, Black enjoys a decent compensation due to the bishop pair and the better pawn structure.}) 11. Ng3 {This position was reached in the game 0-1 (82) Kovalev, V (2582) -Firouzja, A (2777) Chess.com INT 2023 At this point, my suggestion would be} Ba6 12. Re1 O-O-O 13. Bd2 Nc5 14. Qc1 Nxb3 15. cxb3 c5 $11 {Black has an excellent position. The space advantage, as well as the bishop pair, offer good long-term prospects.}) ({I have also checked} 9. Nh4 {After this move, we need to reckon with two options plans: 1) the immediate f2-f4 2) h2-h3 followed by Qf3. Fortunately, Black has enough resources to neutralize these attacking ideas.} Nbd7 10. h3 {The most natural continuation.} ({After} 10. f4 b4 11. Na4 Ba6 12. Re1 O-O-O $15 {Black manages to overtake the initiative.}) ({Another logical continuation is} 10. a3 {planning to answer} Nc5 {with Now, Black can neutralize White's slight initiative by means of the thematic} 11. Ba2 Be6 12. Qf3 Bxa2 13. Rxa2 Ne6 {Structurally speaking, Black is doing more than fine in view of his space advantage and the misplaced c3-knight. He just needs to reckon with the idea of Nf5. A very good way of fighting against this last resource is} 14. Be3 Nh7 15. Raa1 g6 $13 {followed by ...Be7. I would already give preference to Black's position.}) 10... Nc5 11. a3 Be7 {We shouldn't hurry with a move such as ...Nxb3. The problem is that after cxb3, White will start putting pressure on the semi-open c-file.} 12. Be3 {For the time being, White proceeds with the development. His idea is to answer} O-O {with} 13. Ng6 {It turns out, however, that this seemingly active continuation is quite harmless. Black can just continue with} Re8 14. Qf3 a5 15. Ba2 Be6 16. Bxe6 Nxe6 17. Nxe7+ Qxe7 $13 {The queenside space, as well as the misplaced c3-knight, give Black a slightly preferable position. He can proceed with ... Rad8 followed by ...Nd4.}) 9... Nbd7 10. a4 b4 11. Ne2 {This position was reached in the game 1-0 (37) Alekseenko, K (2703) -Karjakin, S (2757) Moscow 2021. Now, the simplest would have been} Nc5 12. Bc4 {The most natural continuation.} ({The position arising after} 12. Ng3 Nxb3 13. cxb3 Bd6 14. Be3 O-O 15. Qc2 Be6 16. Rac1 c5 {is pretty solid for Black. The c5-pawn is untouchable in view of . ..Rfc8. A possible continuation would be} 17. Nf5 Bxf5 18. exf5 e4 19. Nd2 Rfe8 20. h3 Rad8 $13 {when Black enjoys an excellent counterplay.}) (12. Ba2 Be6 13. Bxe6 Nxe6 {Transposes to the main line}) 12... Be6 13. Bxe6 Nxe6 {Black has nothing to worry about. He is ready to complete the development by means of ...Bc5 followed by ...0-0. The game might continue with} 14. Ng3 Bc5 15. Qe2 O-O 16. Nf5 Rfe8 17. Qc4 a5 $13 {Black's harmonious setups and the space advantage on the queenside provide enough compensation for the weakened c4-square.} *

