{The following model games are dedicated to the line} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 Qc7 4. exd5 cxd5 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 {This is another principled way of using the move 3...Qc7. Besides putting pressure on d5, White is also planning to harass the black queen by means of g2-g3 followed by Bf4. Black's most principled reaction is} e6 {Besides covering the d5-pawn, we are also planning to follow with ...Bb4 on the next move.} 7. g3 {This is one of the two main lines. White prepares Bf4 on the next move but allows ... Bb4. The main alternative 7.a3 will be examined later.} Bb4 {It goes without saying that Black should immediately seize the opportunity to pin the knight. Besides reducing the pressure on d5, we can also consider creating imbalances by playing ...Bxc3.} 8. Bf4 ({Too passive is} 8. Bd2 dxc4 9. dxc4 {This position was reached in the game 1/2-1/2 (36) Schmakel, S (2416) -Matviishen, V (2538) Philadelphia 2023 CBM 215 Extra. Now, Black could have played the natural} O-O {If allowed, we can keep improving the position with obvious moves such as ... Nc6, ...Rd8, and ...e6-e5. White can try to make use of the move Bd2 by going for an endgame -} 10. Nb5 Qe7 11. Bxb4 Qxb4+ 12. Qd2 Nc6 13. Qxb4 Nxb4 14. Rd1 {White wants to exercise a Catalan type of pressure in this endgame. It turns out, however, that after} Bd7 15. a3 Bxb5 16. axb4 Bc6 $13 {Black manages to solve all the problems.}) 8... Qe7 {I don't like this move since the queen is often misplaced on e7.} ({Better would have been} 8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qa5 {when White has different ways of sacrificing the c3-pawn. In any case, his compensation should be enough only for a draw.} 10. Bg2 {The most natural continuation.} ({Slightly more ambitious would be} 10. Bd6 Qxc3+ 11. Nd2 {By keeping the black king in the centre, White will try to use his superior development. Black, however, can easily neutralize Whtie's initiative. The following line shows how we should handle such positions.} Nc6 {[%cal Gf6g8,Gc3f6,Gg8e7] White should act quickly. Otherwise, Black can even find time to play ...Ng8-e7 followed by ...Qf6. A logical sequence would be} 12. Rc1 Qa5 13. Bg2 Qd8 14. cxd5 Nxd5 15. Ba3 Nce7 $11 {Black is ready to castle. White still needs to prove his compensation for the pawn.}) ({Dubious is} 10. cxd5 $6 {when after} Qxc3+ 11. Bd2 Qa3 {White does not have enough compensation for the structural problems.} 12. Qc1 {White has nothing better than playing for compensation in the endgame.} ({The position arising after} 12. dxe6 Bxe6 13. Qb1 {was reached in the game.0-1 (28) Obregon,C (2517) -Krysa, L (2516) Villa Martelli 2021 CBM 205 Extra. Now, the simple} Bd5 $17 {would have provided Black with a huge advantage.}) 12... Qxc1+ 13. Rxc1 O-O 14. Bg2 Nxd5 $15 {In my opinion, White's compensation for the pawn is not sufficient.}) 10... Qxc3+ {White has nothing better than playing for compensation in the endgame arising after} 11. Qd2 Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2 O-O 13. Ne5 {Nevertheless, Black can solve the development problems with very simple moves. For instance, after} b6 14. a4 Bb7 15. Rhb1 Nbd7 16. Nxd7 Nxd7 17. a5 Rfd8 $11 {Black has nothing to worry about. White's compensation is enough only for a draw.}) 9. d4 $6 {This move does not fit into the spirit of this line. The obvious of c4-c5 backfires.} ({White should have played} 9. Bg2 $14 {followed by 0-0 and Re1. In all these lines, the black queen will be misplaced on e7.}) 9... O-O 10. c5 $2 {Principled and wrong.} ({The lesser evil would have been} 10. Bd3 {Of course, after} dxc4 11. Bxc4 b6 $15 {Black enjoys a comfortable advantage.}) 10... Ne4 $17 {Black has a huge advantage. He is ready to proceed with ...Nc6 followed by ...e6-e5. Eventually, Liang managed to win the game.} 11. Qb3 Nc6 12. Bd3 e5 13. Bxe4 exf4 14. O-O dxe4 15. Nd5 Qd8 16. Nxb4 Nxb4 17. Qxb4 exf3 18. Rfe1 Qd7 19. Qc4 fxg3 20. hxg3 Qh3 21. Qf1 Qh6 22. Re4 Be6 23. Rd1 Rad8 24. Rh4 Qg6 25. Re1 Bg4 26. Qc4 h5 27. d5 Rfe8 28. Rf1 Qe4 0-1

