{Let's take a look at what happens if White sacrifices the c4-pawn by playing} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 Qc7 4. exd5 cxd5 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 e6 7. g3 Bb4 8. Bg2 {In my opinion, sacrificing the c4-pawn is more principled and energetic than 8.Bf4.} dxc4 {Of course, Black should accept the challenge. As you will see from the analysis, White has compensation but nothing more than that. If both sides play precisely, the game will end in a draw.} 9. Bf4 {White keeps playing energetically. Passive moves would easily lead to a better position for Black.} ({The main alternative is} 9. O-O cxd3 10. Qa4+ Nc6 {The only game in which this position was reached continued with} 11. Nb5 $2 {which is already a serious mistake.This position occurred in the game 0-1 (30) Ciorgovean, I (2305) -Danielyan,V (2346) Chess.com INT 2023. Now, Black could have played} ({White should have played} 11. Nd4 {Even in this case, however, the precise sequence} Bxc3 12. bxc3 O-O 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Ba3 Rd8 15. Qxc6 Qxc6 16. Bxc6 Ba6 $44 {solves all the problems. Black would enjoy fantastic compensation for the exchange.}) 11... Qa5 12. Qxa5 Bxa5 13. Nd6+ Ke7 $17 {with a huge advantage. White does not have any compensation for the sacrificed material.}) 9... Qa5 10. dxc4 {The most concrete approach to the position.The critical position is being reached after} ({In case of} 10. O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 cxd3 12. Qxd3 O-O $13 {White still needs to prove his compensation with very energetic moves. The price of each move is definitely higher for White in this position.}) 10... Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Qxc3+ 12. Nd2 O-O 13. O-O Nc6 14. Rc1 {White is relying on his better development and bishop pair. Black should decide where to retreat the queen. Even though 14...Qd3 is a perfectly valid option, more practical is} Qb4 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gb4e7] Black wants to stabilize the position with natural moves such as ...Rd8 and ...Qe7. Later on, he can consider expanding in the centre with ...e6-e5. Once again, energetic play is required from White. The computer gives} 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Nf3 {White is trying to establish full domination on the dark-squares. Nevertheless, Black can change the trend by means of} e5 $1 17. Bxe5 c5 $13 {planning to make use of the weakened diagonal a8-h1. We are not afraid to double our pawns after Bxf6 since the light-squared bishop will dominate the knight. In my opinion, Black has excellent chances in this complex position.} *

