{The next examples are dedicated to 7.a3.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 Qc7 4. exd5 cxd5 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 e6 7. a3 {This prophylactic move is directed against 7...Bb4. Of course, if allowed, White still wants to proceed with g2-g3 followed by Bf4. Additionally, Black should reckon with the threat of Nb5. Therefore, the most precise move order starts with} a6 {Covering the b5-square is vital for Black. Our idea is to answer} 8. g3 {with} dxc4 9. dxc4 Bd6 {Black not only develops his bishop but also prevents Bf4. Now, he is ready to develop the queenside by means of .. .b7-b6 and ...Bb7. An important position arises after} 10. Bg2 b6 11. O-O ({Note that the aggressive} 11. Nd4 Bb7 12. Ndb5 $2 {does not work in view of} axb5 13. Nxb5 Bxg2 14. Nxc7+ Bxc7 15. Rg1 Bc6 $19 {when Black has a winning advantage. The material is about equal but the white king is very weak.}) 11... Bb7 12. Qd3 {Pay attention to this precise move. Actually, this is prophylaxis against the generally desirable ...Nbd7. In this case, White is ready to continue with Rd1 followed by Bf4. Therefore, in the positions with a white queen on d3, Black should play} Nc6 {The b7-bishop is closed only temporarily. Very often Black initiates exchange operations with ...Ne5, before or after ... Rd8.} ({Less precise is} 12... Nbd7 {when White can play} 13. Rd1 Be7 14. Bf4 Qc8 15. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ga1d1] with a slight advantage. White is now ready to double the rooks on the d-file. At the same time, due to the annoying f4-bishop, Black will face problems connecting the rooks.}) 13. Bg5 {The most natural way of developing the dark-squared bishop.} ({In case of} 13. Be3 {the simplest solution would be} Ne5 (13... Rd8 $5 {is possible as well.}) 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bxb7 Qxb7 $13 {Black is doing fine. After completing the development, he will start putting pressure on the c4-pawn. Additionally, White should always watch for the advance ...b6-b5.}) 13... Rd8 {This is the more ambitious approach to the position.} ({Even simpler would have been} 13... O-O {Black is not afraid of the structure arising after} 14. Bxf6 gxf6 {White does not have attacking chances on the kingside. At the same time, the move ...gxf6 increases Black's central control. If White plays passively, Black's bishop pair will tell in the long run. The only drawback is that White can force a draw by means of the following sequence -} 15. Ne4 Be7 16. Qe3 f5 17. Qh6 fxe4 18. Ng5 Bxg5 19. Qxg5+ Kh8 $11 {with perpetual to follow.}) 14. Qe3 Bc5 15. Qf4 Qxf4 {Duda keeps playing ambitiously. The arising endgame tends to be a little bit risky due to the vulnerable b6-pawn.} ({Black should have played} 15... Bd6 $11 {when White has nothing better than repeating the position.}) 16. Bxf4 Nd4 $6 {This inaccuracy could have led to a huge trouble.} ({Better would have been} 16... Bd6 {The position arising after} 17. Be3 Bc5 18. Bxc5 bxc5 19. Na4 Nd7 $13 {is quite playable for Black. After safely protecting the c5-pawn, Black can consider playing on the b-file.}) 17. Nxd4 Bxg2 18. Nxe6 Bxf1 19. Nxd8 Bxc4 20. Nb7 {This move was followed by a draw offer which was accepted.} ({Instead,} 20. Nc6 $16 {would have provided with with a huge advantage. The threat of b2-b4 is very annoying. Additionally, Black should reckon with Re1.}) 1/2-1/2

