{Let's take a look at another game by Duda. The first 12 moves repeat the previous game -} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 Qc7 4. exd5 cxd5 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 e6 7. a3 dxc4 8. dxc4 a6 9. g3 Bd6 10. Bg2 b6 11. O-O Bb7 12. Qd3 Nc6 13. Be3 {We have already mentioned this continuation in the comments to the previous example. By developing the bishop on e3, White is targeting the b6-pawn. As we have pointed out, Black's simplest solution tends to be 13...Ne5. Nevertheless, true to his fighting spirit, Duda gave preference to the ambitious} Rd8 {Black's idea is to answer} 14. Qe2 {with} Na5 {immediately targeting the c4-pawn. At this point, White played the natural} 15. Nd2 ({An interesting alternative would be} 15. Na4 Qxc4 16. Qxc4 Nxc4 17. Bxb6 Nxb6 18. Nxb6 O-O $13 {The strong bishop pair gives Black very good counterplay in this complex endgame. Let's take a look at one example.} 19. b4 {This position occurred in the game 1-0 (47) Ponkratov, P (2624) -Murzin, V (2542) Sochi 2022 CBM 208 Extra. Now, Black's most precise continuation would have been} Bb8 $1 {With this elegant retreat, Black opens the way of his rook and creates the potential threat of ...Ba7. The following lines provide good illustration of the nature of this position.} 20. Nc4 Bd5 21. Rac1 g6 22. Nfe5 {The most logical continuation. After the exchange of the light-squared bishops, White wants to seize control of the c6-square.} ({Another possibility is} 22. Nfd2 Ba7 23. Nb3 {By maneuvring with his knights, White tries to make use of Black's queenside weaknesses. Black, however, has enough dynamic resources to maintain the balance. For instance, he can play} Ne4 24. Bxe4 Bxe4 25. Nc5 Bd3 26. Rfd1 Bxc4 27. Rxd8 Rxd8 28. Rxc4 Rd2 $13 {with an excellent counterplay.}) 22... Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c7,Gf8c8] The most precise move. Black is ready to double the rooks on the c-file and proceed with ...Ba7. At the same time, white knights lack stability.}) 15... Bxg2 16. Kxg2 O-O 17. Rac1 {This natural move is slightly less precise since it allows ...Bc5. Black wants to exchange the dark-squared bishops in order to take control of the important d4-square.} ({Better would have been} 17. b4 {Still, after} Nc6 18. Rac1 Be5 $13 {Black has decent counterplay. One of his ideas is ...Bxc3 followed by ...e6-e5, and ... Nd5. In positions with majorities on different wings, the activity of the pieces is the most important factor. Of course, the control of the open d-file is another important element.}) 17... Bc5 18. Bg5 {Played with the intention to capture on f6. As we have seen in the previous example, however, Black gladly allows the doubling of his pawns. The game went} Nc6 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. Nf3 f5 {A thematic move in this structure. Black not only gains space on the kingside, but also plays against the white knights. With his last move, he prevents the move Ne4.} ({Another good idea would have been} 20... a5 $5 {fixing White's queenside majority. Note that} 21. Ne4 {will be answered with} Be7 {with ...f6-f5 to follow.}) 21. Rfd1 Qb7 {After the exchange of the light-squared bishops, the queen is very well placed on b7. Besides creating threats against the white king, it often supports the advance ...b6-b5.} 22. Kg1 Nd4 23. Nxd4 Bxd4 24. Nd5 Bg7 $15 {Black is already slightly better due to the superiority of his bishop over the white knight. Additionally, Black enjoys a very good central control. For instance, by means of ...Qe4 he can force a favourable endgame. Later on, Duda managed to win this game.} 25. Nf4 Qe4 26. Re1 Qxe2 27. Rxe2 Rd4 28. c5 Rc8 29. b4 Bh6 30. Rc3 bxc5 31. bxc5 Bxf4 32. gxf4 Rxf4 33. Rd2 Rc6 34. Rd7 Kg7 35. h3 Kf6 36. Kg2 Re4 37. Rd2 Re5 38. Rdc2 Rd5 39. Rc4 h5 40. h4 e5 41. a4 a5 42. f3 f4 43. R4c3 Rd4 44. Rb2 Rxa4 45. Rb7 Rb4 46. Ra7 Rb5 47. Rd3 Rbxc5 48. Rdd7 Ke6 49. Re7+ Kd5 50. Red7+ Rd6 51. Rxf7 Rg6+ 52. Kf2 Kc4 53. Rfd7 Kb4 54. Rdb7+ Rb5 55. Rd7 Rc6 56. Rd2 Rc3 57. Rb2+ Rb3 58. Ra2 Ra3 59. Re2 Rc3 60. Rb2+ Rb3 61. Re2 Rb1 62. Rd7 a4 63. Re4+ Ka3 64. Rd3+ R5b3 65. Rd5 R3b2+ 66. Re2 Rxe2+ 67. Kxe2 Kb3 68. Rxe5 a3 69. Rb5+ Kc2 70. Rc5+ Kb2 71. Rb5+ Ka1 72. Rxh5 a2 73. Kd3 Kb2 74. Rb5+ Kc1 75. Ra5 a1=Q 76. Rxa1 Rxa1 77. Ke4 Ra4+ 78. Kf5 Kd2 79. h5 Ke3 0-1

