{ In the following couple of games, we will see what happens when Black is allowed to develop his knight via d7. We are already familiar with the first ten moves. } 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 Qc7 4. exd5 cxd5 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 e6 7. a3 a6 8. g3 dxc4 9. dxc4 Bd6 10. Bg2 b6 11. Be3 { In my opinion, this natural move is not precise. First of all, Black manages to achieve the harmonious setup based on ...Bb7 and ...Nbd7. Secondly, clarifying the position of the bishop at such an early stage is not advisable. The following couple of moves are quite natural } 11... Bb7 12. Rc1 Nbd7 13. O-O O-O 14. b4 Rac8 { Black's play in this structure is pretty straightforward. With his last move, he already starts speculating on the vulnerability of the c4-pawn. Our next moves are ...Rfd8 followed by the eventual ...Qb8. Note that whenever White retreats the f3-knight, we have the active option of ...Ne5. After the eventual exchange of the light-squared bishops, Black can also create threats against the white king. Another important element in this position is White's overextended queenside. As we will see, Black can often make use of it by employing the break ...a6-a5. On the other hand, White lacks constructive ideas. His play mainly revolves around the pressure on b6 and the advance c4-c5. If Black is careful enough, however, he has enough resources to neutralize these ideas. } 15. Na4 Rfd8 16. Qe2 Bc6 { When White has committed to Na4, the idea of ...Bc6 followed by ...Qb7 gains in strength. The game followed with } 17. Nb2 Qb7 18. Rfd1 Ne5 { when Black started overtaking the initiative. } ( { Another very thematic idea would be } 18... Bf8 { [%cal Ga6a5] with ...a6-a5 to follow. As mentioned earlier, we should always consider undermining White's overextended queenside. In this structure, Black can also consider the advance ...e6-e5. Very often, this idea is connected with ...e5-e4 followed by ...Ne5. } ) 19. Ne1 $2 { After this mistake, Black gets a huge advantage. } ( { Better would have been } 19. Nxe5 Bxg2 20. Nbd3 Be4 21. f3 Bxd3 22. Nxd3 h6 $13 { With queens on the board, I would take Black since the white king is potentially vulnerable. The advance ...e6-e5-e4 is always quite annoying for him. } ) 19... Bxg2 20. Nxg2 Nf3+ $17 { Black's advantage is out of question. Later on, Naroditsky managed to win this online blitz game. } 21. Kh1 Bc7 ( 21... Ng4 $17 ) 22. Nd3 Qe4 23. Nde1 Nxe1 24. Qxe1 h6 25. Kg1 Ng4 26. Bf4 Rxd1 27. Rxd1 Qxe1+ 28. Rxe1 Bxf4 29. Nxf4 Rxc4 30. Rd1 Ne5 31. Rd6 Rc6 32. Rd8+ Kh7 33. h4 g5 34. hxg5 hxg5 35. Ne2 g4 36. Kf1 Nf3 37. Nd4 Rc1+ 38. Ke2 Re1+ 39. Kd3 Rd1+ 40. Ke3 e5 41. Nc6 Rc1 42. Rd6 f5 43. Rf6 Rc3+ 44. Ke2 Rxc6 45. Rf7+ Kg6 46. Rf8 e4 47. Ke3 Kg5 48. Rg8+ Rg6 49. Re8 Rd6 50. Rg8+ Kf6 51. Kf4 Ne5 52. Rf8+ Nf7 53. Rb8 Rd3 54. Rxb6+ Nd6 55. Rxd6+ Rxd6 0-1[Event "EU-ch Rapid"]
