{ The following example shows how flexible Black's setups is when White tries to put pressure on the queenside. Our position of interest arises after White's 17.Na4. Up to this point, all the moves are quite natural. } 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 Qc7 4. exd5 cxd5 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 e6 7. a3 dxc4 8. dxc4 a6 9. g3 Bd6 10. Bg2 b6 11. O-O Bb7 12. Qe2 O-O 13. Be3 Nbd7 14. Rfd1 Rfd8 15. Rac1 Rac8 16. b4 Qb8 17. Na4 { This is White's most natural continuation. As pointed out earlier, the advance c4-c5 is White's only constructive idea in this position. } 17... Be7 { This elegant retreat is the simplest solution. Of course, the b6-pawn is not hanging because at the end of the line, Black will take on f3, thus winning a piece. We are now ready to continue with ...Bc6 followed by either .. .Qb7 or ...Qa8. } 18. Bf4 { White wants to exchange the dark-squared bishops via d6. On the other hand, the black queen will now occupy the favourable a8-square. } ( { In my opinion, more to the point would have been } 18. c5 { White should go for this advance if he wants to make use of the queenside majority. The game will continue } 18... bxc5 19. Nxc5 Nxc5 20. Bxc5 Bxc5 21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 22. Rxc5 Qa8 $13 { Black's active pieces offer him an excellent counterplay in this position. White can hardly exploit the queenside majority since his king is potentially vulnerable. } ) 18... Qa8 19. Bd6 { White is consistent in his plan. The problem is that his idea backfires after the thematic } 19... Bxd6 20. Rxd6 b5 $1 { after which Black overtakes the initiative. Both players should always watch for this break. } 21. Nb2 bxc4 22. Rxc4 Nd5 $2 { This mistake gives White the chance to obtain a slight advantage, } ( { Black should have played } 22... a5 $15 { The idea is to open the a-file for the queen. Note that the move 23.b5 will be met by 23...Bd5, closing the d6-rook and winning the battle for the c-file. Black is already better. } ) 23. Ng5 ( 23. Rxc8 Qxc8 24. Nc4 $14 ) 23... N7f6 24. Rxd8+ Rxd8 25. Nd3 h6 26. Nxe6 Re8 27. Bh3 Bc8 28. Ndc5 fxe6 29. Qe5 Qc6 30. Rd4 a5 31. Bf1 axb4 32. axb4 Qb6 33. h4 Kh8 34. Bd3 Nxb4 35. Na4 Nxd3 0-1[Event "Titled Tuesday intern op 18th Jan"]
