{ In this example, we are going to examine some of White's deviations on move 7. After } 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 Qc7 4. exd5 cxd5 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 e6 7. Bg5 { is one of White's most serious alternative to the main lines. It's not a surprise that this move has also been tried by Anish Giri. } ( { Completely harmless is } 7. cxd5 { The structure arising after } 7... Nxd5 8. Nxd5 exd5 9. d4 Nc6 { is quite favourable for Black. In symmetrical structures, the activity of the pieces is the most important factor. Here, Black is ready to proceed with simple moves such as ...Bd6, ...0-0 and ...Bf5 or ...Bg4. For instance, after } 10. Be2 Bd6 11. O-O O-O 12. Be3 Bf5 { Black was already slightly better in the game 0-1 (54) Gurel, E (2345) -Tari, A (2556) Almaty 2022 CBM 212 } ) ( { The immediate } 7. Nb5 $6 { is well met by } 7... Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 Qe7 { Black does not have any problem whatsoever. He can complete the development with simple moves such as ...a7-a6 followed by ...Nc6, and ...0-0. The attempt to make use of the b5-knight by means of } 10. Qf4 $6 O-O 11. Nc7 $2 { backfires. Black can answer with } 11... Nh5 12. Qe5 Nc6 13. Qxh5 Qxc7 $17 { with a huge advantage in view of the superior development. 0-1 (29) Sadhwani,R (2555) -Pultinevicius,P (2492) Chess.com INT 2021 CBM 203 Extra } ) ( { Of course, the simple developing move } 7. Be2 { is always an option. In my opinion, After castling, White would like to follow with moves such as Nb5 and Bf4. Therefore, Black's most precise reaction is } 7... Bb4 { Later on, we are ready to follow with .. .Nc6 and ...0-0. A possible continuation is } 8. Qb3 Nc6 9. O-O { This position was reached in the game 1-0 (43) Pridorozhni, A (2564) -Rozum, I (2529) Khanty-Mansiysk 2021. At this point, the following pawn sacrifice is quite promising - } 9... O-O 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 exd5 12. Qxd5 Be6 13. Qe4 Qd7 $44 { Black has an excellent compensation for the pawn. He is ready to follow with natural moves such as ...Rad8 and ...Rfd8. } ) 7... Be7 { This simple developing move is the simplest solution to all the problems. In his game against Anish Giri, Naroditsky played 7...Bb4 which is good but a little bit more complicated. White can try to take advantage of the pressure on d5 by playing } 8. Be2 Nc6 9. O-O O-O 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. cxd5 { It turns out, however, that Black has two good solutions. The simplest one is } 11... Bxc3 ( { Another good possibility is } 11... Ne7 $5 12. dxe6 Bxe6 $44 { with excellent compensation for the pawn. Black's bishop pair is quite strong in this position. } ) 12. bxc3 exd5 $13 { The position is balanced, but the asymmetrical pawn structures offers good chances to play for a win. Black will follow with simple developing moves. } *[Event "?"]
