{ Let's get back to the starting position of the variation - } 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 Qc7 { The following examples show how Black should handle the symmetrical structure arising after ...dxe4 followed by ...e7-e5, provided that White plays passively. } *[Event "Titled Tuesday intern op 01st Feb-B"]
[Event "Chess.com INT"]
[Site "Chess.com INT"]
[Date "2022.02.02"]
[Round "1"]
[White "Mogranzini, Roberto"]
[Black "Andreikin, Dmitry"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "B10"]
[WhiteElo "2459"]
[BlackElo "2724"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[PlyCount "68"]
[EventDate "2022.02.02"]
[EventType "swiss (blitz)"]
