{As we have pointed out in the introduction, Black's main objective in this line is to get a favourable symmetrical pawn structures by means of ...dxe4 followed by ...e7-e5. The following couple of examples show what happens when White does not go for an energetic play.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 Qc7 4. Nbd2 {This move tends to be very passive. Depending on where the light-squared bishop will go, we will see either Philidor or Pirc with colours reversed. Instead of 4.Nbd2, White should have opted for one of the two main moves - 4.Nc3 or 4.exd5.} e5 {Since there is no pressure on d5, Black is not forced to rush with ...dxe4. In the game, only after} 5. g3 Nf6 6. Bg2 {Andreikin played} dxe4 {This is a typical reaction to Bg2. The idea is that after} 7. dxe4 {the white bishop cannot operate on the diagonal f1-a6. This structure is comfortable for Black unless White has something very energetic and concrete at his disposal. Playing on the queenside is Black's main strategy in this structure. Therefore, when possible, we try to gain queenside space by means of ...b7-b5 and ...a7-a5. The fight for the d-file is another very important positional element here. In my opinion, White's position is slightly more unpleasant due to the passive g2-bishop. In the game, Andreikin played} Be6 {I like this move, even though it's by no means forced. Since we are going to play on the queenside, the control of the diagonal a2-g8 is very important. Of course, there is nothing wrong with the simple 7...Be7.} 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Ng5 {Quite a reasonable move. Otherwise, Black can secure his light-squared bishop by playing ...h7-h6 on the next move. The following couple of moves are quite logical.} Bg4 10. f3 Bc5+ 11. Kh1 Bh5 {Black's most important task is bringing the light-squared bishop to the diagonal g8-a2. Therefore, after castling, Black can consider ideas such as ...Ne8 followed by ...f7-f6 and ...Bf7, of course without blundering anything.} 12. Nb3 Bb6 {It's preferable ot keep the bishop on the diagonal a7-g1. Now, in order to develop his own bishop on the active e3-square, White should allow the exchange of the dark-squared bishops. This exchange is quite favourable for Black since it enables him to fight for the dark squares in the centre. At the same time, White's remaining bishop is quite passive on g2.} 13. Qe2 O-O 14. Be3 {White plays into Black's hand. At the same time, it's difficult to critisize this natural move.} ({Another continuation would have been} 14. a4 a5 {Of course, we should prevent our opponent from gaining space on the queenside.} 15. Nh3 Nc5 16. Nxc5 Bxc5 $13 {[%cal Gf6d7,Gf7f6,Gh5f7] Black is doing more than fine. His next moves are going to be ...Nd7 followed by ...f7-f6, and ... Bf7. Later on, he can start playing on the queenside. Even the advance ... b7-b5 comes into consideration.}) 14... a5 15. a4 Rfd8 16. Nh3 Ne8 $1 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gh5f7] Of course! Activating the light-squared bishop should be our priority. We are now ready to proceed with ...f7-f6 followed by ...Bf7.} 17. Nf2 f6 18. Nd2 {The knight has nothing to do on b3. Therefore, White would like to relocate it on c4.} Bxe3 19. Qxe3 Qb6 {This is one of the many possible options. Due to the superior activity of his minor pieces, Black is interested in exchanging queens. The endgame is quite favourable for him.} 20. Qxb6 Nxb6 21. Rfd1 Nc7 {It turns out that there are very bright perspectives for this knight. A possible maneuver is ...Ne6-d4 (c5) . Another idea is ... Na6-c5 (b4) . Black starts gradually overtaking the initiative.} 22. Nd3 Na6 {Andreining prefers this square for the knight because on e6 it would close the way of the light-squared bishop.The game continued} ({Nevertheless, I would have preferred} 22... Ne6 23. Kg1 Nd4 24. Ne1 Bf7 $15 {[%cal Gd8d6,Ga8d8] with an excellent position for Black. He is now ready to double the rooks on the d-file. White is under a strong pressure.}) 23. Kg1 Bf7 24. b3 Rd4 $15 {Black is better. After doubling the rooks on the d-file, he will follow with the advance ...c5-c4. Andreikin managed to convert his advantage without efforts.} 25. Kf2 Rad8 26. Ke2 c5 27. Nf2 c4 28. Rab1 c3 29. Nf1 Nb4 30. Rxd4 Rxd4 31. Rc1 Nd7 32. Nd1 Na2 33. Ra1 Bxb3 34. cxb3 c2 0-1

