{This example shows how easily Black can outplay his opponent due to the superior activity of his minor pieces.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 Qc7 4. g3 {This move is even less flexible than Nbd2. White immediately shows his intention to put the bishop on g2. Therefore, Black can already clarify the structure with} dxe4 5. dxe4 e5 {As we have seen in the previous example, the arising symmetrical positions are favourable for Black due to the passive g2-bishop. The game continued} 6. Bg2 Nf6 7. O-O Bc5 {I like this move quite a lot. Since the exchange of the dark-squared bishops is generally favourable for Black, there is no good square for the c1-bishop on the diagonal c1-h6. Therefore, White opted for a plan based on b2-b3 and Bb2. As we will see, this kind of development is far from optimal.} 8. Qe2 O-O 9. Nbd2 a5 $1 {We already know that gaining space on the queenside is an essential part of Black's strategy. This move is even more effective when the white queen is already committed to e2. Black is planning to use the misplaced queen by playing ... b7-b6 followed by ...Ba6.} 10. b3 b6 11. Bb2 Ba6 12. Nc4 {This self-pinning move is not a good idea. The problem is that Black is going to carry out the advance ...b6-b5 with all the comfort.} ({The lesser evil would have been the anti-positional} 12. c4 {Of course, after} Nbd7 $15 {Black keeps a slight advantage. Later on, he can proceed with ...Bd6 followed by ...Nc5. In the long-run, Black will be fighting for the weakened squares d4 and d3.}) 12... Nbd7 13. a4 $6 {This dubious move would only make the advance ...b6-b5 more effective.} ({A reasonable alternative would have been} 13. Ne1 {Nevertheless, after} b5 14. Nd2 Rfd8 $15 {[%cal Gd7f8,Gf8e6] Black can rely on a stable advantage. Now, he is ready to follow with the typical maneuver ...Nd7-f8-e6. As you know, maneuvering our minor pieces to the d4-square is a key element in our strategy.}) 13... Rfe8 14. Ne1 $2 {White makes another mistake in a difficult position. The game went} b5 15. axb5 cxb5 16. Nd2 b4 17. Nd3 Bb6 $19 {Black has a winning advantage. His next moves are going to be ...Nc5 and ... Rad8. White cannot withstand the pressure. Later on, Fedoseev managed to win.} 18. Rac1 Nc5 19. Rfd1 Rad8 20. Qf3 Bxd3 21. cxd3 Qb8 22. Bf1 Ne6 23. Nc4 Bd4 24. Qe2 Qc7 25. Ra1 Ra8 26. Rdc1 Qd8 27. Bxd4 Nxd4 28. Qb2 Nd7 29. Ne3 Nb6 30. Bh3 g6 31. Kg2 Qd6 32. Bg4 h5 33. Bd1 Nb5 34. Nc4 Nxc4 35. dxc4 Nc3 36. Bf3 Red8 37. Qc2 Qc5 38. Re1 Rd4 39. Re3 Rad8 40. Rae1 Rd2 41. Qc1 Ra2 42. Kg1 Rdd2 43. Rf1 Qd4 44. h4 Kg7 45. Qe1 Rab2 46. Qa1 Ra2 47. Qe1 Rdb2 48. Bg2 Rxb3 49. f4 Ne2+ 0-1

