{This is another example which features the setup with b2-b3 followed by Bb2. Compared to the previous game, Aronian handled the structure more precisely. The position after move 8 is the same as in the previous game.} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 Qc7 4. Qe2 dxe4 5. dxe4 e5 6. g3 Nf6 7. Bg2 Bc5 8. O-O O-O 9. b3 {This time, White go for the fianchetto without the preliminary Nbd2. From a structural perspective, however, there is no too much of a difference. Once again, Black should opt for our familiar idea} a5 {planning to proceed with ...b7-b6 followed by ... Ba6 at some point.} 10. Bb2 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Re8 {This move is always useful. Of course, Black could have started with the immediate ...b7-b6.} 12. Ne1 {The idea behind White's setup becomes clear. After Nd3, he wants to play f2-f4 at some point.} b6 13. Nd3 Ba6 14. c4 {White wants to block Black's queenside play, even at the price of weakening important central squares. If Black does not play energetically, White will prepare the advance f2-f4 by playing Kh1. Shimanov reacted with} Rad8 15. Kh1 Bb4 {I like this energetic move. The immediate threat is ...Bxd2 followed by ...Nc5. Also, at some point, Black can play ...c6-c5 and go for the maneuver ...Nd7-b8-c6-d4.} 16. Nxb4 axb4 17. f4 c5 $13 {Black has a decent counterplay in this position. His next move is going to be ...Bb7, this putting an indirect pressure on e4. After provoking f4-f5, he can carry out the maneuver ...Nd7-b8-c6-d4. Shimanov even managed to outplay his famous opponent.} 18. a3 bxa3 19. Rxa3 Bb7 20. f5 Nb8 21. Nb1 Nc6 22. Nc3 Nd4 23. Qf2 Ra8 24. Rfa1 Rxa3 25. Rxa3 Ra8 26. Rxa8+ Bxa8 27. Bc1 h6 28. Qa2 Bc6 29. h3 Qb7 30. Nd5 Qa8 31. Qb2 Bxd5 32. exd5 h5 33. Be3 Qc8 34. Bxd4 exd4 35. Qf2 Qc7 36. Qe1 Kf8 37. b4 Qe7 38. Qa1 Kg8 39. bxc5 bxc5 40. Qd1 Qe3 41. Kh2 d3 42. Bf3 Qf2+ 43. Kh1 d2 44. Qe2 Qxg3 45. Qd3 Qxh3+ 46. Kg1 Qg3+ 47. Kf1 Ng4 0-1

