{This version of IQP arises when Black managed to carry out the advance ... e6-e5. Compared to the classical version of this structure in which White has a pawn on e3, this situation is more favourable for Black in view of the following factors: 1) Counterplay on the e-file 2) Possibility of putting pressure on the diagonal a7-g1 3) Outpost on c4 For instance, all the endgames with heavy pieces are quite acceptable for Black. In such positions, Black's counterplay on the e-file prevents White from focusing on the isolated pawn. As you will see from the model examples, Black can often play for a win in this structure.}  *

