{ At the beginning, we shall take a look at some examples featuring the advance ...e6-e5. The following fragment is taken from the game Meister, J - Khalifman, A, 2003. } 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 { The most popular continuation. After Bf4, White wants to put his knights on f3 and d2. This is considered the most harmonious placement of the minor pieces. } 6... Bg4 { This move is always an important part of our plan. Before playing ...e7-e6, we need to get our light-squared bishop out of the pawn chain. } 7. Qb3 Qd7 { This natural move is my recommendation. From the d7-square, the black queen enables the resource of ...Bd6. The main alternative is 7...Qc8 with the idea to sidestep the idea Nf3-e5. This continuation, however, tends to be too passive. } 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 { This is an important moment. Given the fact that our queen is already on d7, White is threatening Ne5. In my opinion, the simplest solution is } 9... Bxf3 { I prefer to get rid of the light-squared bishop. In such positions, you can often see Black going for the maneuver ...Bh5-g6. The problem is that after an eventual exchange on g6, White can use our h6-pawn as a hook. The advance h2-h4-h5 becomes particularly annoying. } ( { One of White's ideas can be seen after } 9... Be7 $6 10. Ne5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 $18 { winning a piece. } ) 10. Nxf3 Bd6 { Our entire system is based on this active move which contributes to the fight for the e5-square. It's very important that taking on b7 is not advantageous for White. Most of the games continue } 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. O-O { You will get this tabiya in most of your games. } ( { Of course, we should start with } 12. Qxb7 { which does not bring White any dividends. It turns out that after } 12... Rb8 13. Qa6 O-O { White does not have a comfortable way of defending the b2-pawn. The most natural continuation is } 14. O-O { completing the development. } ( { An important direction is } 14. Bb5 Rb6 15. Qa4 Ne7 { [%cal Gf8b8] when the b5-bishop is very unstable. Black is ready to continue with ...Rfb8. The b2-pawn is in danger. } 16. O-O { White has nothing better. } ( { Trying to save the b2-pawn by means of } 16. b3 $6 { is quite dubious since the c3-pawn becomes vulnerable. Black can immediately take advantage of it by playing } 16... Ne4 17. Rc1 Rc8 { increasing the pressure on c3 to the maximum. The game 0-1 (48) Morozevich,A (2590) -Oll,L (2645) Groningen 1997 went } 18. Bd3 { At this point, Black could have played } 18... Rbc6 { when the following sequence seems quite logical - } 19. Bxe4 dxe4 20. Ne5 Ra6 21. Qd7 Qxd7 22. Nxd7 Rxa2 23. O-O Nd5 24. Nc5 Nf4 $13 { Black's active pieces give him an excellent counterplay. } ) 16... Rfb8 17. Bd3 Qc7 $11 { Before taking on b2, Black covers the a7-pawn. It becomes clear that White cannot keep the material advantage. Black enjoys a comfortable equality. } ) ( { Protecting the pawn with } 14. Rb1 $6 { is passive and slow. Black can strike in the centre with } 14... Rb6 15. Qa4 e5 $36 { overtaking the initiative. } ) 14... Rb6 { Black should start with this move. } ( { The immediate } 14... Rxb2 $4 { runs into } 15. Bb5 $18 { when White is winning on the spot. } ) 15. Qa3 { Compromising the queenside structure is the only way to keep the material advantage. Black can develop an excellent play against White's weaknesses. A logical sequence would be } 15... Qxa3 16. bxa3 Rc8 17. Rab1 Na5 18. Rxb6 axb6 19. Rc1 { This position was reached in 9 games. Practice, as well as concrete analysis, confirm that Black has a very comfortable play. The most popular move is } 19... Nc4 ( { A decent alternative is } 19... Ne8 20. Kf1 Nd6 { This position was reached in the game 1/2-1/2 (21) Plat, V (2543) -Sadhwani, R (2409) Pardubice 2018. Black's play is very easy from a practical perspective. We are ready to follow with ...Nac4 and ...Ra8. White's extra pawn does not have any value. } ) 20. Bxc4 dxc4 { The idea of this move is to free the d5-square for the knight. Of course, taking with the rook is possible as well. } 21. Nd2 Nd5 22. a4 Kf8 23. Kf1 { This position was reached in the game 1-0 (23) Marton Bardocz, S (2313) -Marez,S (2571) LSS email 2008. Now, the simple } 23... Ra8 24. Nxc4 Rxa4 $11 { would have provided Black with a comfortable equality. } ) 12... O-O 13. Rae1 { [%cal Gf3e5,Gf2f4] White usually prefers to put the a1-rook to e1. There two reasons for that: 1) the queen often joins the kingside play via d1 without spoiling the connection between the rooks 2) the f1-rook usually supports the advance f2-f4 It's very important that White is now ready to play Ne5 followed by f2-f4. With our queen on d6, we are not ready to take on e5 because of the fork. As a rule, when White is ready to jump on e5 with the knight, we should retreat the queen! Therefore, the most precise move in this position is } 13... Qc7 $1 { With this move, Black makes sure that Ne5 will be answered with ...Nxe5. As we will see in the following model games, the structure arising after dxe5 is usually favourable for Black. } 14. Qd1 { The queen has nothing to do on b3. Therefore, White starts concentrating his forces on the kingside. } 14... Rab8 { With this move, Black indicates his intention to start a minority attack on the queenside. } 15. Re3 g6 { The advance ...g7-g6 is always useful in this pawn structure. Black restricts the d3-bishop and frees the g7-square for the king. } 16. Nd2 { This move is played with the idea to prepare the advance f2-f4 (something that we shouldn't allow that easily) . The drawback of this retreat is the reduced control of the e5-square. This position was reached in the game Meister, J - Khalifman, A, 2003. At this point, Black could have started with } 16... b5 { with the obvious intention of playing ...b5-b4. Even though the immediate 16...e5 is possible as well, it's better to first create some targets on the queenside. An interesting position arises after } 17. b4 a5 18. a3 axb4 19. axb4 e5 20. dxe5 Nxe5 { As we have explained in the introduction, this version of IQP is much more favourable for Black in comparison with the classical IQP positions. In this particular position, Black can also benefit from the weak c3-pawn. White's attempt to establish a blockade on d4 by playing } 21. Nb3 { is very well met by } 21... d4 22. Nxd4 Nd5 $13 { with an excellent counterplay for Black. } 1/2-1/2[Event "Titled Tuesday intern op 15th Feb Early"]
