{This is another instructive example featuring the advance ... e6-e5. The first 13 moves are left without comment since they repeat the previous example.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qd7 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Bxf3 10. Nxf3 Bd6 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Rae1 Qc7 {This is the most straightforward continuation. Black, however, is very well prepared for it. We should immediately play} 14. Ne5 Nxe5 {Otherwise, White will support the knight with f2-f4. In the game, White played} 15. Rxe5 {This version of the Carlsbad structure is pretty harmless for Black. White does not have huge attacking potential on the kingside for two reasons: 1) the light-squared bishop can be easily neutralized by means of the advance . ..g7-g6 2) the f6-knight is a very stable defender Black can either try to carry out a minority attack or deliver the advance ...e6-e5. Given the fact that White has good control of the b5-square, the second scenario seems more realistic.} ({More ambitious is} 15. dxe5 {which will be examined in the following model games.}) 15... g6 {Never forget to play this move. It practically kills White's attacking potential on the kingside.} 16. Qd1 Rae8 {I like this thematic move a lot. Black starts preparing the advance ...e6-e5. His next move is going to be ...Nd7. At the same time, if the advance ...e6-e5 does not work for some reason, the rook can always go to b8 and prepare a minority attack. Tempis are not of crucial importance in this static position. The game went} 17. Qe2 Nd7 18. Re3 e5 19. dxe5 Rxe5 20. Rxe5 Nxe5 {Once again, we have reached this important structure. I remind you that this version of IQP is more favourable than the classical one with a pawn on e3 due to the following reasons: 1) Black has very nice counterplay on the e-file 2) Black can often make use of the diagonal a7-g1 3) The c4-square becomes an outpost since after b2-b3 the c3-pawn will become weak 4) Black can often put pressure on b2 when the advance b2-b3 will again weaken the c3-pawn In this particular position, queen and knight fight quite successfully against queen and light-squared bishop. Black can often initiate a dark square strategy which will be quite annoying for White. Since White does not have sufficient control of the d4-square, the advance ...d5-d4 is often annoying for him. The position is objectively equal, but playing with Black is easier.} 21. Re1 {This natural move fails to put pressure on the e-file.} ({In case of} 21. Rd1 {Black can react with} Rd8 22. Bc2 Nc6 {with a comfortable position. White does not have constructive ideas. At the same time, he should already reckon with the advance ...d5-d4.}) 21... Re8 {Suddenly, Black has the threat of ...Nf3+.} 22. Kf1 $6 {This is not the best way to deal with the threat.} ({More natural would have been} 22. Qd1 {when Black will continue with} Re6 {[%cal Gc7e7] Again, I would take Black in a practical game. He can consider increasing the pressure on the e-file with ...Qe7. In such a case, White should always watch for various knight jumps. Due to the counterplay on the e-file, White is unable to focus on the d5-pawn.}) 22... Re6 23. Bc2 $2 {This move, as well as the next one, are mistakes that we can often see in blitz games. Black is already winning.} Nc4 24. Qf3 $4 Nd2+ 0-1

