{ This position was reached in the game Abdusattorov,N - Keymer,V, 2023. Black should decide how to deal with the threat of Ne5 followed by f2-f4. Keymer decided to prevent this idea by means of } 13... Nd7 { Black not only stops Ne5 but also starts preparing the advance ...e6-e5. The only drawback of this move can be explained by the fact that the black knight leaves the kingside. Nevertheless, it's not easy for White to make use of this problem. } ( { It goes without saying that there is nothing wrong with the traditional } 13... Qc7 ) 14. Re3 { [%cal Ga1e1] Abdusattorov starts building his kingside attack. He is ready to proceed with Rae1 followed by h2-h4. } 14... g6 { We never forget to play this useful move! The following couple of moves are quite logical and natural. } 15. Rae1 Qc7 16. h4 { White starts his kingside attack. If allowed, he would like to proceed with g2-g3 followed by Kg2 and Rh1, and h4-h5. The problem is that Black can answer with the central break ...e6-e5. } 16... Kg7 17. g3 Re7 $1 { I like this idea very much. Black wants to prepare the advance ...e6-e5 as much as possible. With his last move, Black prepares to double the rooks on the e-file. We will see this thematic idea on many occasions. } 18. Kg2 Rfe8 19. Qd1 e5 $1 { We are all set for this break. } 20. dxe5 Ndxe5 { This version of IQP is pretty similar to the previous example. As we already know, Black is quite happy to play a position with queen and knight versus queen and light-squared bishop. In the game, Abdusattorov tried to maintain the pressure with } 21. Bb5 ( { It goes without saying that the endgame arising after } 21. Nxe5 Rxe5 22. Rxe5 Rxe5 23. Rxe5 Qxe5 { is pretty harmless for Black. Even if White manages to exchange the queens, Black is out of danger. A possible continuation would be } 24. Qd2 d4 25. cxd4 Nxd4 $11 { with equality. Still, White is more likely to make a mistake in such positions. } ) 21... Nxf3 22. Qxf3 Qb6 { A very precise move. Black put's pressure on White's entire position. White went for } 23. Qxd5 Rxe3 24. Rxe3 Rxe3 25. fxe3 Qxe3 26. Qd3 Qb6 $13 { when Black enjoys a very nice counterplay in view of the vulnerable white king. The game ended in a draw. } 27. Qe2 Qc5 28. Bxc6 Qxc6+ 29. Kh2 h5 30. c4 Qc5 31. b3 a5 32. Kg2 b6 33. Qb2+ f6 34. Qd2 Qc6+ 35. Kf2 Kf7 36. Qd5+ Qxd5 37. cxd5 Ke7 38. Ke3 Kd6 39. Kd4 Kd7 40. Kc4 Kc7 41. Kd3 Kd6 42. Kd4 Kd7 43. Kc4 Kc7 44. Kd3 Kd6 45. Kd4 1/2-1/2[Event "?"]
