{Now, we shall take a look at the typical structure with a white pawn on e5. Let's take a look at two games of GM Alexander Riazantsev who is a big expert in this line. I will not comment on the first 14 moves since we are familiar with them.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qd7 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Bxf3 10. Nxf3 Bd6 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Rae1 Qc7 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 {This is the more ambitious (and objectively riskier) continuation. White is relying on the space advantage provided by the e5-pawn to build a kingside attack. Later on, he will follow with moves such as Kh1, f2-f4, and Qd1. The problem is that the light-squared bishop can be easily neutralized with ...g7-g6. Hence, in this simplified position, White's attacking potential is severely restricted. At the same time. Black's minority attack based on ...b7-b5-b4 can be very annoying. Note that Black is more than happy to exchange his knight for the white bishop. The endgames with heavy pieces are better for Black for two reasons: 1) the possibility of playing on the semi-open c-file 2) the advance . ..b7-b5-b4.} Nd7 16. Qd1 g6 {As always, this move should be played as quickly as possible.} ({The alternative} 16... Nxe5 {is possible but less ambitious. The sequence} 17. Bxh7+ Kxh7 18. Qh5+ Kg8 19. Rxe5 g6 20. Qe2 Kg7 $11 {leads to equality. The problem is that it's not easy for Black to play for a win.}) 17. f4 b5 $1 {By making use of the exposed white king, Black immediately starts his minority attack. The advance ...b5-b4 will either provoke a weakness on c3 or create a strong passed pawn on d5. Black is statically better.} 18. Kh1 Rab8 19. Qe2 b4 20. c4 {A reasonable choice. On the other hand, after the exchange of the central pawns, Black will also get the d5-square for his knight. Therefore, Riazantsev immediately played} Nb6 ({Another good possibility would have been} 20... dxc4 21. Bxc4 Rfc8 22. Ba6 Rd8 $15 {Black is better in view of two factors: 1) superiority of the knight over the white bishop 2) White's overextended position Besides putting a knight on d5, Black can also try ...Nc5 folloowed by ...Rd4 and ...Rbd8. The white bishop is completely useless in this position.}) 21. Rc1 dxc4 22. Bxc4 Qe7 {This move is enough to keep the advantage.} ({Even more precise would have been} 22... Rbc8 {with the idea of provoking} 23. b3 {Now, White should always reckon with the weakness of the c3-square. After} Qe7 $17 {Black's advantage is undisputable.}) 23. Ba6 Rfd8 24. h3 h5 25. Rc6 Kg7 26. Rfc1 Nd5 27. Qf3 Rb6 28. Rxb6 axb6 29. Rd1 Qc7 30. Qf2 Ra8 31. Bd3 Rxa2 32. f5 exf5 33. Bxf5 Qxe5 34. Bd3 Rxb2 35. Qf3 Nf4 36. Rf1 g5 37. g3 Qd5 38. gxf4 Qxf3+ 39. Rxf3 g4 40. hxg4 hxg4 41. Rg3 Rb3 42. Kh2 Kf6 43. Be2 Rc3 44. Bxg4 Rc4 45. Be2 Rxf4 46. Rf3 Ke5 47. Rxf4 Kxf4 48. Kg2 Ke3 49. Bc4 f5 50. Kf1 f4 51. Ke1 Kd4 0-1

