{This example shows how Black can outplay his opponent in an endgame with heavy pieces.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qd7 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Bxf3 10. Nxf3 Bd6 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Rfe1 {[%cal Gf3e5] This move is also quite popular.Once again, the threat is Ne5 followed by f2-f4. Therefore, Black should play} Qc7 {when the nature of the game does not change in comparison to 13.Rae1. The play continued with} 14. Qd1 a6 {Note that ...a7-a6 is just one of the useful moves. Black could have played 14...g6 as well. Another typically useful move is ...Rae8, but we will speak about it a bit later.} 15. a4 Rab8 16. Qe2 {The construction Qe2-Bd3+a4 makes it very difficult for Black to start his minority attack. At the same time, White is ready to start gradually progressing on the kingside. Moves such as g2-g3 followed by Kg2 and h2-h4 are part of his plan. In my opinion, Black should be playing for ...e6-e5.} Rfc8 {This is one of the possible moves. A possible idea for Black is ...Na5-c4 followed by ...b7-b5.} ({My favourite move, however, is} 16... Rbe8 $1 {Black's idea is very deep. He is planning to prepare the advance ...e6-e5 by means of ...Re7 followed by ...Rfe8. We can also include the moves ...g7-g6 and ...Kg7. If Our idea is to provoke the move Ne5 after which Black will play ...Nxe5, getting a favourable pawn structure. Let's take a look at a possible line.} 17. h4 Re7 18. g3 ({At any moment, we are ready to play the structure arising after} 18. Ne5 Nxe5 19. dxe5 Nd7 $13 {In this case, Black can also follow with ...f7-f6, opening the f-file for the rook and eliminating White's space advantage. In such a scenario, the h4-pawn does not bring White any dividends.}) 18... Rfe8 19. Rad1 e5 {Black is ready for this thematic advance. The following sequence seems quite logical.} 20. dxe5 Nxe5 21. Nxe5 Rxe5 22. Qd2 g6 23. Rxe5 Qxe5 {As we have already seen, Black is always ready to play with queen and knight versus queen and light-squared bishop. In this structure, the counterplay along the e-file does not allow White to play against the d5-pawn. For instance, after} 24. Bf1 h5 25. Bg2 Qe2 $11 {Black's activity fully compensates the isolated pawn.}) 17. Ne5 {As we know, Black is perfectly ready for this knight jump in the centre.} ({In my opinion. better would have been to attack without Ne5. A possible idea is} 17. g3 {[%cal Gg1g2,Gh2h4] followed by Kg2 and h2-h4. Of course, Black can still return to the plan of preparing ...e6-e5.}) 17... Nxe5 18. dxe5 Nd7 19. Qh5 {This move is pointless since Black is going to play ...g7-g6 anyway.} g6 20. Qe2 Nc5 {The right approach to the position. Now, White should either allow a transition into an endgame with heavy pieces or give Black the chance to play ...b7-b5. In the game, White played} 21. h4 {initiating an attack which can never be successful.} ({After} 21. Bc2 {Black will answer with} b5 22. axb5 axb5 {[%cal Gb5b4] In this case, the minority attack on the queenside is very fast. For instance, after} 23. h4 b4 24. Qe3 bxc3 25. bxc3 Nd7 $17 {White is already in a huge trouble.}) 21... Nxd3 22. Qxd3 Qc4 {As we have already pointed out, in all these endgames with heavy pieces, Black is slightly better.The following moves are quite logical.} ({I am not sure whether Black should have rushed with the exchange of the queens. A possible alternative would have been} 22... Qb6 {followed by ...Rc4 and ...Rbc8. By keeping the position more complex, Black retains higher winning chances. White's position is quite overextended.}) 23. Qxc4 Rxc4 24. g3 b5 25. axb5 axb5 26. Ra7 b4 27. Re3 bxc3 28. bxc3 Rbc8 $15 {Black is slightly better in this rook endgame but with precise play, White would retain chances for a draw.} 29. Rf3 Rf8 30. Re3 h6 31. Rb7 g5 32. hxg5 hxg5 33. Rb4 Rfc8 34. Rxc4 Rxc4 35. Kf1 Kg7 36. Ke2 Kg6 37. Kd3 g4 38. f3 gxf3 39. Rxf3 Re4 40. Rf6+ Kg7 41. Rf1 Rxe5 0-1

