{The following example features the advance ...f7-f6 in positions with a white pawn on e5.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qd7 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Bxf3 10. Nxf3 Bd6 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Rfe1 Qc7 14. Qc2 {This is one of the many possible moves. The nature of the position, however, remains unchanged. The White queen will eventually land on e2. Nevertheless, we should pay attention to this move. Since the h7-pawn is attacked, the move Ne5 is even more interesting. The problem is that after the typical ...Nxe5 followed by ... Nd7, the h7-pawn will be hanging.} Rac8 {This move is a prophylactic against Ne5. Black is ready to answer it by means of ...Nxd4.} ({Another very good idea would have been the thematic} 14... g6) 15. Qe2 Rfe8 {As you know, Black has many good waiting moves in this position. Possible alternatives are 15... g6, 15...a6, and 15...Rce8.} 16. g3 a6 17. a4 Rb8 18. h4 {White is going for the most dangerous plan. He is attacking on the kingside without playing the commital Ne5. By advancing the h-pawn, White wants to create targets on the kingside. Since White has prevented our minority attack, we should play for the advance ...e6-e5.} Re7 $1 {[%cal Gb8e8] As you know, I am a big fan of this idea. By doubling the rooks on the e-file, Black is preparing ...e6-e5. We want to provoke the move Ne5.} 19. Kg2 Rbe8 {[%cal Ge6e5] Black is ready for the thematic break ...e6-e5. Therefore, White played} 20. Ne5 {White hopes that after} Nxe5 21. dxe5 Nd7 22. Rad1 {he gets a better version of this typical structure. This position was reached in the game Shalimov, V - Yevseev, D,2005. With his rooks being on e8 and e7, it's not so easy for Black to go for his minority attack. Black, however, has another resource at his disposal. At this point, Black should have played} f6 $1 {When we have doubled our rooks on the e-file, this advance is very effective.} 23. exf6 Nxf6 {Suddenly, it becomes clear that Black is perfectly coordinated. He is ready to continue with ...e6-e5. A logical continuation is} 24. Qe5 Kf7 25. h5 Qxe5 26. Rxe5 Nd7 27. Re2 Nf6 $11 {with balanced position.} 1-0

