{ The following fragment illustrates that White does not have enough attacking resources on the kingside. Actually, our minority attack on the queenside is much faster. In this position, Black played the standard } 19... Nc5 20. Bb1 b5 { The most straightforward way of handling the position. } ( { I would have preferred } 20... g6 ) 21. Rf3 { This rook-lift is White's most natural way of attacking. } ( { Making use of the fact that White didn't play ... g7-g6 by means of } 21. f5 { does not achieve anything. Black can just play } 21... exf5 22. Bxf5 g6 23. Bc2 b4 $15 { with an advantage. White does not have an attack. At the same time, the e5-pawn is a huge weakness. } ) 21... g6 22. Qd2 a5 23. Rh3 { This position occurred in the game Semeniuk, A - Yevseev, D, 2002. White tries to convince us that the idea f4-f5 followed by Qh6 is very dangerous. In order to eliminate any attacking ideas, Black opted for the maneuver ...Nd7-f8 which is quite thematic and strong. It turns out, however, that we can just ignore White's kingside play by means of } 23... b4 24. Qf2 { [%cal Gf2h4] White prepares Qh4. } ( { After } 24. f5 $2 exf5 25. Qh6 Ne4 $1 { it turns out that Qxh7 is not a real threat.After the moves } ( { In such positions, the move } 25... f6 { is always an option. } 26. Bxf5 Qg7 $15 { Black is already better in this position. } ) 26. Qxh7+ Kf8 27. Qh6+ Ke7 28. Bxe4 Qxe5 $17 { White is on the verge of losing. } ) 24... Qe7 { We need to prevent Qh4. Note that the aggressive } 25. f5 exf5 26. Bxf5 gxf5 27. Qxf5 { does not work in view of } 27... f6 $17 { when White does not have enough compensation for the sacrificed material. } *[Event "Rilton Cup 47th"]
