{ One of White's most challenging plans is to put the queen on the diagonal c1-h6 before playing Ne5. The following example shows how Black should react in this situation. The first 14 moves will be left without comments since they are quite thematic for the variation. } 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qd7 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Bxf3 10. Nxf3 Bd6 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Rae1 Qc7 14. Qc2 g6 15. Qd2 { A very interesting idea. Besides the simple idea of Qh6 White actually wants to get a better version of the Ne5 jump. The idea is that after the exchange of the knights, White will be able to defend the e5-pawn with the queen. There will be no need to make the committal f2-f4 move. } 15... Kg7 16. Ne5 { This position was reached in the game Dragnev,V - Rasmussen,A, 2017. Now, instead of the game continuation 16...Ne7, Black should have played } 16... Nxe5 17. dxe5 Nd7 { Even in this case, we should react in the same fashion. The idea of White's concept is that he can now protect the e5-pawn by means of } 18. Qg5 ( { In case of the usual } 18. f4 { besides the minority attack on the queenside, Black can also play } 18... Rae8 $13 { [%cal Gf7f6] followed by ...f7-f6. } ) 18... Nc5 19. Bc2 Qd8 { We should start harassing the white queen before the maneuver Re3-h3. } 20. Qf4 { Obviously, White is not interested in playing an endgame. The idea of Re3-h3 is still in the air. The best way to neutralize it is } 20... Rc8 21. Re3 Nd7 22. Rh3 h5 $13 { [%csl Re5][%cal Gc8c4] White has run out of attacking resources on the kingside. In case of necessity, Black can also play ...Rh8. At the same time, White should reckon with Black's queenside counterplay. The idea of ...Rc4 is quite annoying. Additionally, note that the e5-pawn might also become vulnerable. All in all, Black has an excellent counterplay in this position. } *[Event "?"]
