{ As we have pointed out in the introduction, in the Exchange Variation, Black often manages to successfully execute the so-called minority attack on the queenside. Since this plan is quite typical and known, we will not examine it in a great depth. The following examples are designed to illustrate how the minority attack work in this line. In this position, Black's pieces are optimally arranged for the advance } 19... b5 { This move marks the beginning of the minority attack. The idea is to create queenside weaknesses with the advance ...b5-b4. At the same time, White's kingside play tends to be too slow. The game went } 20. Qd3 Nf8 21. axb5 axb5 22. Ne5 $2 { This is already a serious mistake. Black can now go on with his minority attack. } ( { White should have taken measures on the queenside. The most precise would have been } 22. b4 { preventing ...b5-b4 and fixing the b5-pawn. White has enough resources to cover the vulnerable c3-pawn. The game could have continued } 22... Ne7 23. Rc1 Qd8 { [%cal Ge7c8,Gc8d6,Ge7f5,Gf5d6] Obviously, Black is slightly better. He will try to further improve his position by bringing the e7-knight to d6. At the same time, however, White can go for the maneuver Nf3-d2-b3. Even though Black's position is slightly more pleasant, White maintains the balance. } ) 22... Nxe5 23. Rxe5 b4 { After this move, Black is better. White cannot avoid the formation of queenside weaknesses. At the same time, without a knight or dark-squared bishop, White's attacking potential on the kingside is limited. } 24. R5e3 Rbc8 25. Qd2 Nd7 26. Rg3 Kf8 { It turns out that White does not have any kingside play at all. At the same time, Black is already winning the battle on the other wing. } 27. Ree3 $2 { A mistake in a difficult position. Now, the g3-rook becomes completely useless. } ( { More tenacious would have been } 27. Rc1 ) 27... Nf6 $17 { This move is enough for a huge advantage. Later on Black won the game without effort. } ( { Even more precise would have been } 27... bxc3 28. bxc3 Nf6 $19 { with a completely winning position. Ideas such as ...Qa6-Qa1 are extremely annoying for White. } ) 28. h3 bxc3 29. bxc3 Ra7 30. Rgf3 Ra2 31. Qd3 Ra1+ 32. Bd1 Ne4 33. Qc2 Qa3 34. Kh2 Rc1 35. Qe2 Qd6+ 36. g3 Nxc3 37. Rxc3 R1xc3 38. Rf4 g5 39. Rf6 Kg7 40. Rf3 Rxf3 41. Qxf3 Qe7 42. Kg2 Rc4 43. Qd3 Qf6 0-1[Event "Wch Blitz"]
