{The following game is another illustration of the rule that White cannot attack successfully when the only remaining minor piece is his light-squared bishop. In this structure, Black often tries to get a position with queen and knight against queen and light-squared bishop. I leave the first 15 moves without comment since we are already familiar with them.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qd7 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Bxf3 10. Nxf3 Bd6 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Rae1 Qc7 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. Rxe5 {As we know, taking with the pawn is more ambitious. White's main problem now is that he does not have a minor piece that can challenge the f6-knight. If needed, the bishop can be further restricted with ...g7-g6. In the game, Black just started preparing his minority attack with} Rab8 16. g3 {This move is designed to eliminate any ideas based on ...Ng4. On the downside, it allows the advance ...b7-b5.} ({As a matter of fact, the move} 16. a4 {cannot prevent ...b7-b5.} b5 {Remember this important idea which is based on the opposition on the b-file. The natural} 17. axb5 {is answered with} a6 {White has no comfortable defence against the simple threat of ...axb5, and ...Qb6 if needed. The only attempt to keep the extra material is} 18. c4 {Now, Black can opt for the following sequence -} dxc4 19. Qxc4 Qxc4 20. Bxc4 axb5 {The simplest solution.} ({Another option is} 20... Nd7 21. Rxe6 fxe6 22. Bxe6+ Kh8 23. Bxd7 axb5 24. d5 $11 {with equality.}) 21. Rxb5 Rxb5 22. Bxb5 Rb8 {Now, only the weakness of our backrank allows White to avoid an unpleasant endgame. He should play} 23. Ra1 {when after} g6 24. Ra5 Rc8 25. Ra1 Rb8 $11 {the draw is obvious.}) 16... b5 17. a3 Qc6 {Overprotecting the b5-pawn before proceeding with ...a7-a5.The following couple of moves are quite natural.} ({Even more precise would have been the straightforward} 17... a5 18. Qc2 ({It turns out that after} 18. Bxb5 Ne4 {[%cal Ge4d6,Gb8b7,Gf8b8] Black has a more pleasant position. His idea is very simple - ...Nd6 followed by doubling the rooks on the b-file.}) 18... b4 19. axb4 axb4 $15 {Black will manage to create a queenside weakness. He is already slightly better.}) 18. h4 a5 19. Qd1 Qd6 20. Rfe1 Rfc8 {A very nice positional move. When conducting a minority attack, before playing ...b5-b4, we often take the c4-square under control. In this case, we make sure that the opponent cannot respond with axb4 followed by c3-c4.} 21. Qf3 $6 {This move is already an inaccuracy. Now, the white queen does not have influence on the queenside.} ({Better would have been} 21. Kg2 {planning to answer} b4 {with the thematic} 22. cxb4 axb4 23. a4 {in return for the weak d4-pawn, White gets a distant passer on the a-file. Black should handle the position with care since such a pawn can be an important asset in the endgame. After} b3 $13 {[%cal Gd6b4] followed by ...Qb4, Black has an excellent counterplay in this complex position.}) 21... b4 22. cxb4 $2 {With the misplaced f3-queen, this move is already a mistake. Instead, White should have entered a passive but defendable position by playing axb4.} axb4 23. a4 b3 24. Bb5 Qb4 $17 {Black has a huge question. Besides putting pressure on d4, Black is planning to follow with ...Rc2 on the next move.} 25. R5e2 Rc2 26. Qe3 Rbc8 27. Kg2 h6 28. Ra1 Ng4 29. Qf4 Nf6 30. Qe3 Ng4 31. Qf4 Nf6 32. Rae1 Ne4 33. Qe3 Nf6 34. Kh3 Kf8 35. g4 Ne4 36. f3 Rxe2 37. Rxe2 Nd6 38. Bd3 Qxa4 39. Qf4 Qd7 40. Kg2 Nc4 41. g5 hxg5 42. hxg5 Kg8 43. Qh4 g6 44. Kg1 Kf8 45. Qh8+ Ke7 46. Qg7 Kd6 47. Rh2 Qe7 48. f4 Ra8 49. Bxc4 dxc4 50. Qe5+ Kd7 51. Qb5+ Kc7 52. Qxc4+ Kb7 53. Qxb3+ Ka7 54. Qa4+ Kb7 55. Qb5+ Ka7 56. Rh3 Rb8 57. Qa5+ Kb7 58. Rb3+ Kc8 59. Qa6+ 1-0

