{Let's take a look at another fragment illustrating White's limited attacking resources when he remains with a light-squared bishop. The position of interest arises after White's 17.a3.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qd7 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Bxf3 10. Nxf3 Bd6 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Rae1 Qc7 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. Rxe5 Rab8 16. Re3 b5 17. a3 {As we know, this move will not stop the minority attack. This position was reached in the game Pulpan,J - Belozerov,A, 2019. Now, instead of the game continuation 17...Rb6, Black should have played} a5 {The following sample line shows how fast is Black's queenside attack.} 18. Rh3 b4 19. axb4 axb4 20. Qd1 {White is creating the threat of Bxh7+ followed by Qh5. Therefore, Black can play} h6 ({Of course, there is nothing wrong with the traditional} 20... g6 {Even if White brings his queen to h6, Black is out of danger. Remember that White's main problem in such positions is that he cannot challenge Black's most important defender - the f6-knight.}) 21. Qf3 {The idea of Rxh6 is just an illusion. For instance, after} bxc3 22. bxc3 Rb3 23. Rxh6 gxh6 24. Qxf6 Qxc3 $19 {White can already resign.} *

