{ Another very interesting way of handling the Exchange Variation is } 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. h3 { With this move White is playing against our light-squared bishop. Black can no longer play ...Bg4 followed by ...e7-e6. If allowed, White will continue with Bf4 followed by Nf3, and Nbd2, thus getting his dream setup. The main drawback of this concept is that the e5-square is now temporarily left without sufficient control. Therefore, Black's most principled continuation is } 6... e5 7. dxe5 Nxe5 { We already know that this version of IQP is more favourable for Black than the classical one with a pawn on e3. Additionally, in this particular position, White wasted time for pawn moves such as h2-h3 and c2-c3. Therefore, Black can look in the future with optimism. The move } 8. Qe2 { is quite a logical continuation in this position. The idea is to provoke the move ...Qe7. } ( { Very popular but harmless is } 8. Nf3 { Black can get a decent position by playing natural moves. A logical follow-up would be } 8... Nxd3+ 9. Qxd3 Bd6 10. O-O O-O { Black has an excellent version of IQP. In the future, he can develop an initiative with moves such as ...Re8, ...Ne4, ...Bf5, and ...Qd7. Very often, the idea ...Bc7 followed by ...Qd6 comes into consideration. In my opinion, White's most challenging continuation is } 11. Bg5 { pinning the knight and putting pressure on d5. } ( { A calm move like } 11. Be3 { gives Black even higher degree of liberty. The game might continue } 11... Re8 12. Nbd2 h6 13. Rfe1 Ne4 14. Rad1 Bf5 $13 { with an excellent counterplay for Black. Black's active pieces prevent White from playing against the d5-pawn. } ) 11... h6 { This is the usual reaction to Bg5. Before anything else, we need to clarify the position of the g5-bishop. } 12. Bh4 { The most ambitious. White is keeping the tension. } ( { Taking the pawn with } 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Qxd5 { would give Black a very strong compensation.White's position is practically very dangerous. With such a huge lag in development, he should play very carefully not to lose on the spot. The optimal play according to the computer goes } ( { It goes without saying that after } 13. Nbd2 Rd8 14. Rfe1 Bc7 $13 { Black is doing fine. The strong bishops pair gives enough compensation for the isolated pawn. Additionally, White does not have enough resources to put pressure on the d5-pawn. } ) 13... Rd8 14. Qh5 g6 15. Qxh6 Bf4 16. Qh4 g5 17. Qh5 Kg7 18. Nd4 Rh8 19. Qe2 Bxh3 20. gxh3 Rxh3 21. Qe4 Rah8 22. Nf5+ Kg8 23. Na3 Bc7 $11 { This position is just a draw. Black is ready to repeat with ...Rh1+ followed by ...R1h2+. White can also force the draw by means of the repetition Qe8-Qe4. Of course, it's quite unlikely that some of your opponents will find all these moves. } ) 12... Re8 13. Nbd2 { Only after completing the development and activating his pieces, White can consider taking the d5-pawn. Black, however, can react immediately with } 13... g5 14. Bg3 Bxg3 15. fxg3 g4 16. hxg4 Nxg4 { We reached an irrational position in which both sides have weak kings and spoiled pawn structures. In such cases, piece activity and precise calculation are the most important factors. The game can continue with } 17. Rae1 Qb6+ 18. Nd4 Rxe1 19. Rxe1 Bd7 $13 { Black has an excellent counterplay in this complex position. } ) ( { Simplifying the position with } 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Nf3 { looks natural and tempting. White's problem is that Black's remaining pieces are quite active. As a matter of fact, Black can even fight for more than equality. The most precise reaction is } 10... Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3 Qe6+ { Surprisingly, White does not have a comfortable reaction to this check. } ( { Another natural line is } 11... Bc5 12. O-O O-O 13. Nd2 Rfe8 14. Nb3 Bb6 $13 { This position is a good illustration of Black's two main advantages in this version of IQP. 1) Control of the e-file 2) Pressure on the diagonal a7-g1. Under favourable circumstances, Black will increase the pressure by means of ...Ne4 followed by a possible rook-lift via the 6th rank. } ) 12. Qe2 Bc5 { Once again, our bishop is the first to occupy the important diagonal a7-g1. It turns out that White cannot castle because of the unstable queen. On the other hand, after } 13. Qxe6+ fxe6 $15 { Black is already better due to his better central control and superior development. } ) ( { Keeping the light-squared bishop with } 8. Bc2 $6 { is dubious. After } 8... Bc5 9. Ne2 O-O 10. O-O Re8 $15 { Black is already better. The white king is quite vulnerable in this position. For instance, after a natural move such as ...Qd6, White should already reckon with the threat of ...Bxh3 followed by ....Nf3.+ } ) ( { Very similar to the previous line is } 8. Be2 Bc5 9. Nf3 { In this case, the play might continue with } 9... Qd6 10. O-O O-O 11. Na3 Bd7 12. Nc2 Bb6 $15 { Once again, White's position is pretty dangerous. Since the f3-knight will disappear soon, all the ideas based on ...Bc7 are quite dangerous. Also, in such structures, White should always watch for the sacrifice ...Bxh3, especially if the black queen can later appear on g3. } ) 8... Ne4 $5 { In my opinion, this dynamic continuation is better and simpler than the traditional 8...Qe7. } 9. Bb5+ { This move indicates White's intention to play an endgame. } ( { Accepting the sacrifice by means of } 9. Bxe4 dxe4 10. Qxe4 { is pretty dangerous. After } 10... Bd6 11. Nf3 O-O { Black enjoys excellent compensation in view of his better development and powerful bishop pair. } 12. O-O { White has nothing better than completing the development. } ( { The alternative } 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. O-O Re8 14. Qf3 Bd7 { leads to a position that is extremely dangerous for White. The white king is quite vulnerable here. Black is ready to proceed with ...Bc6 followed by ...Re6-g6. One of the possible scenarios is well illustrated by the following sample line - } 15. Qxb7 Rb8 16. Qf3 Re6 17. Nd2 Bc6 18. Qd1 Rg6 $19 { Black is winning. } ) 12... Re8 13. Rd1 Nxf3+ 14. Qxf3 Qc7 $44 { Once again, Black has more than enough compensation for the pawn. } ) 9... Bd7 10. Nf3 { Understandably, White keeps insisting on the exchanges of the minor pieces. Even in the endgame, however, Black will retain an annoying initiative. } ( { In case of } 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. Nf3 { Black can keep the position more complex by playing } 11... Ng6 { The g6-knight can be quite annoying for White. In contrast with the classical IQP with a pawn on e3, here Black has access to the important f4-square. A possible line is } 12. Be3 Bd6 13. O-O O-O 14. Nbd2 Rad8 $13 { [%cal Gf8e8] with ...Rfe8. In my opinion, the superior activity of Black's minor pieces overweights the isolated pawn. } ) 10... Bxb5 { Black is ready to play an endgame.This is how White can force the transition into an endgame. It's important to correctly evaluate the position arising after } ( { Of course, we always have the option of playing } 10... Ng6 $5 { keeping more pieces on the board. the game might continue } 11. O-O Bc5 12. Be3 O-O 13. Bxd7 Qxd7 14. Bxc5 Nxc5 $15 { Again, Black is slightly better due to his better development and active knights. Placed on e4 and f4, our knight can become extremely annoying for the opponent. At the same time, White is very far from putting any pressure on d5. } ) 11. Qxb5+ Qd7 12. Qxd7+ Nxd7 13. Be3 Bc5 14. Bxc5 Ndxc5 { Despite the exchanges, Black is the one who is fighting for an advantage in this endgame. The most important factor is the difference in the activity of the minor pieces. For instance, the threat of ...Nd3 is extremely annoying for White. After castling long, Black will bring the h8-rook to e8. } 15. Ke2 $6 { covering the d3-square and preparing Rd1. The problem is that the king is often vulnerable on e2. This position was reached in the game 1/2-1/2 (38) Antipov,M (2600) -Saric,I (2647) Chess.com INT 2023At this point, Black could have played } ( { Better would have been } 15. O-O { Even in this case, however, after } 15... Nd3 16. Rd1 Nxb2 17. Rxd5 O-O $13 { Black's play is easier. } ) 15... Na4 16. Nbd2 Nxb2 17. Nxe4 dxe4 18. Ng5 Na4 19. Nxe4 O-O-O $17 { with a huge advantage. } *[Event "?"]
