[SourceVersionDate "2002.01.01"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd6 7. O-O Ne7 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Nb3 Bd6 10. Bg5 O-O 11. Re1 Qc7 12. c3 Bg4 13. h3 Bh5 14. Be2 h6 15. Bxe7 Nxe7 16. Nfd4 Bxe2 17. Qxe2 a6 18. Qf3 Rad8 19. Rad1 Rd7 20. Nf5 Nxf5 21. Qxf5 Rfd8 22. Re3 g6 23. Qf3 Bf8 24. Red3 Qc6 { [#]We have an identical material situation as in the previous game. The only important difference is that White has a pawn on c3 instead of e3. This implies a series of consequences: First of all, after the desirable minor piece exchange the Isolani undermining plan will be based on c3-c4. This allows Black to defend with ...b7-b5 which, unlike ...f7-f5 (similar to f2-f4 in the previous game) does not weaken the king. Secondly, the e-file is open, meaning that Black could get counterplay closer to the enemy king (unlike his hypothetical play along the c-file) . Besides, a similar rook lift to the fifth rank with Rb4 above would be safer, as White would hardly consider weakening his king with f2-f4. Finally, after a2-a3 provoked by Black's next move, the queenside weakening will be more significant than with the pawn on e3. } 25. Nd4 Qa4 26. a3 h5 27. R1d2 Bh6 { With the actual material, we notice a further positive aspect: the bishop can fight against the major pieces' tripling on the d-file. In the Queen's Gambit Isolani structure this would not be available. } 28. Qd1 { [#] } ( { In view of the next comment, } 28. Re2 { may be more consistent, even though White would have to work harder to reach the game position without minor pieces: } 28... Qc4 29. Rd1 Bg7 30. g3 b5 31. h4 ) 28... Qc4 ( { Botvinnik evaluates the position after } 28... Qxd1+ 29. Rxd1 { as slightly better for White. But actually exchanging major pieces is part of Black's defensive plan. The following analysis suggests the position is just equal. } 29... Rd6 30. Kf1 Rb6 31. b4 ( { Another effect of the bishop's activity as there is no other reasonable way of defending b2. } 31. Rb1 { is too passive, of course. } ) 31... Re8 $5 ( 31... a5 { is premature due to } 32. Nb3 axb4 33. cxb4 $5 { keeping some tension. } ) ( 31... Rbd6 $6 32. Nb3 { planning Nc5 leads to a position where the absence of the queen can be felt. If on the board, she could defend both d5 and b7 from c6. After the suggested move, White cannot approach his king and has no effective plan against the isolani as c3 is also weak. } ) 32. Nb3 ( 32. Ne2 { runs into } 32... Rbe6 ) ( { Or if } 32. h4 Bg7 33. Ne2 Rc6 { the mutual weaknesses compensate for each other. } ) 32... Rc8 33. h4 Bf8 34. Na5 Rc7 35. g3 Re6 ) 29. Re2 Qc7 30. Nc2 b5 { Taking measures against White's thematic c3-c4. } 31. Ne3 ( { White does not achieve much with } 31. Nb4 { trying to prove the knight's superiority over the bishop. } 31... Qb7 { [%cal Ga6a5] } 32. Re5 { Otherwise .. .a6-a5. } 32... d4 $1 ( { But now } 32... a5 $2 { is met with } 33. Rexd5 $1 ) 33. cxd4 Bg7 { with preferable play already. We can notice that the bishop is very active, actually. } ) 31... Qc5 32. Red2 { [#]Black cannot avoid the minor pieces' exchange anymore. } 32... Bxe3 33. Rxe3 Re7 $1 { Kortschnoj chooses a similar plan as in the previous example, intending to place one rook on the fifth rank. This is the most effective method now, as the e-file is closer to the enemy king.[#] } ( 33... d4 $2 { would lose a pawn to } 34. Red3 $16 ) ( { But it is instructive to check what would happen if Black defends passively as in some cases he might not be in time to fight for the e-file: } 33... Kg7 34. g3 Rd6 $5 35. Red3 ( { The point behind Black's previous move is revealed after } 35. h4 d4 $1 36. Red3 dxc3 37. Rxd6 Rxd6 38. Rxd6 c2 $11 { In this line it is essential that the d6-rook is hanging. This tactical operation would not work with the rook on d7. } ) 35... R8d7 36. Rd4 Qc6 37. h4 Qc5 38. a4 { This reduces the number of queenside pawns and Black's worries in general, but otherwise b2-b3 would not be possible. } 38... Qc6 39. axb5 axb5 40. R2d3 Qc5 41. Qd2 ( 41. b3 Re6 $1 { possibly followed by ...Qe7 would allow Kortschnoj's game regrouping. } ) 41... Qc6 42. b3 Ra7 43. Rxd5 ( { White also needs to be careful. If } 43. c4 $2 Ra1+ 44. Kh2 dxc4 $19 ) 43... Ra1+ 44. Kh2 Rf1 45. Kg2 Rc1 $11 ) 34. Rxe7 ( 34. Red3 Re5 { does not pose problems either: } 35. g3 ( { Only not } 35. h4 $2 Qe7 $17 { [%cal Re5e1,Re7h4] attacking h4 and threatening ...Re1+. } ) 35... Qe7 36. Kg2 Kg7 37. Rd4 Qe6 38. h4 Rd7 39. a4 Rd8 40. axb5 axb5 41. b3 Rc8 $1 42. R2d3 ( 42. Rxd5 Rxc3 $11 { is drawish. } ) 42... Rd8 $5 43. c4 ( { What else? If } 43. Qf3 Re4 $11 { or 43...Rf5 and else Black could think of using the e-file with ...Re1 and if Qf3 then ...Re4. } ) 43... bxc4 44. bxc4 dxc4 $11 { with an obvious draw. } ) 34... Qxe7 35. g3 ( { In the QG Isolani structure } 35. Rxd5 { would win a pawn but here } 35... Rxd5 36. Qxd5 Qe1+ $1 37. Kh2 Qxf2 $11 { retrieves it at once. } ) 35... Qe6 36. h4 Kg7 37. Kg2 Qe4+ 38. Kh2 Qf5 39. Kg2 Qe4+ 40. Qf3 $11 ( { Botvinnik recommends } 40. Kg1 $1 { giving the following line: } 40... Qe6 41. Rd4 Qc6 42. Qd2 Rd7 43. a4 Rd8 ( 43... bxa4 44. c4 $14 ) 44. axb5 axb5 45. b3 Rc8 46. Rxd5 Qxc3 47. Qxc3+ Rxc3 48. Rxb5 $16 ) ( 40. Kg1 { But Black can avoid reaching this worse (even though most likely drawn) ending with: } 40... Re8 $1 41. Rxd5 ( 41. Kh2 Re5 $11 { consolidates the pawn avoiding any further pin. } ) 41... Qe1+ { Once again we notice that the control of the e-file is very useful. } 42. Qxe1 ( 42. Kg2 Qxd1 43. Rxd1 Re2 44. Rb1 Rc2 $11 { does not offer White any winning chances either. } ) 42... Rxe1+ 43. Kg2 Re2 44. Rd6 ( 44. b4 Ra2 $11 ) 44... Rxb2 45. Rxa6 Rb3 $11 { with an obvious draw. } ) 40... Qxf3+ 41. Kxf3 Kf6 42. Kf4 Re8 $1 ( 42... Re8 { The simplest. In view of } 43. Rxd5 Re2 44. Rd6+ Ke7 45. Rxa6 Rxf2+ 46. Ke3 Rxb2 $11 { the players agreed to a draw. } ) 1/2-1/2[Event "Barcza mem"]
