{ The starting position of the Panov Attack is being reached after } 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 { This line is quite annoying for many Caro-Kann Defence players. The main source of worry is not that White has an objective advantage. Black's main problem is that it's quite difficult to get a playable position in which White cannot force a draw. I have decided to suggest the variation } 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 { In my opinion, this is a very practical choice against the Panov Attack. In this line, before doing anything else, Black will complete the kingside development. Therefore, almost always, our next two moves are going to be ...Bg7 and ...0-0. One of the main advantages of our variation is that we are always playing with a safe king. If we manage to neutralize White's temporary initiative, our g7-bishop is excellently placed in all IQP positions that arise from the Panov Attack. At the end of the lecture, you will find an analysis dedicated to the move order 1.e4 c6 2.c4 which can also transpose to the Panov Attack. White, however, has some independent options that are explained as well. } *[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Panov Attack"]
[Black "Theoretical Coverage"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[ECO "B14"]
[EventDate "????.??.??"]
[PlyCount "56"]
[SourceVersionDate "2024.02.29"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 { In my opinion, this is a very practical choice against the Panov Attack. In this line, before doing anything else, Black will complete the kingside development. Therefore, almost always, our next two moves are going to be ...Bg7 and ...0-0. One of the main advantages of our variation is that we are always playing with a safe king. If we manage to neutralize White's temporary initiative, our g7-bishop is excellently placed in all IQP positions that arise from the Panov Attack. } 6. cxd5 { This is White's only serious try to fight for an advantage. If Black immediately takes the pawn back, we will embark on a complicated dynamic battle. } ( 6. Nf3 { Many games featured the position arising after the moves } 6... Bg7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Nc6 { Black is already fighting for an advantage. As a rule, our line is showing fantastic results against passive play. We basically got a Tarrasch Defence with colours reversed. Sooner or later, we will get an IQP position where the black bishop is very well placed on g7. We are now planning to put indirect pressure on d4 by playing ...Bg4. White can prevent this idea by means of } 9. h3 { A thematic idea to remember in this position is } 9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 Na5 $1 { Remember this typical move. It's vital for Black to chase the white bishop away from the diagonal a2-g8. The idea can be seen after } 11. Be2 Be6 $15 { Black's bishop is excellently placed on e6. Black is now ready to provoke further simplifications by means of ...Nd5. Very often, Black goes for ... Nd5-Nxc3, thus creating a backward pawn on c3. In such a case, it's quite easy to establish a blockade on the light squares. This position will be featured in some of the model games in this lecture. } ) 6... Bg7 { The safest continuation. Before anything else, we are going to complete the development. } 7. Bc4 { The main continuation. Sticking to the pawn is White's only chance to fight for something in this line. } ( 7. Bb5+ { With this move, White hopes to spoil Black's coordination. Black should play } 7... Nbd7 { In case White plays passively, Black will be glad to proceed with ...0-0 followed by ...Nb6. White's most energetic continuation is considered to be } 8. d6 { White wants to get a symmetrical pawn structure in which he would enjoy extra space and slightly more active pieces. } ( 8. Nf3 { when Black follows his usual strategy - } 8... O-O 9. O-O Nb6 10. Re1 Nbxd5 { Black achieved everything he wanted. Now, he should only decide on the future of the light-squared bishop. White can try to put some pressure by means of } 11. Bg5 { The pressure on the e-file, as well as the control of the e5-square, gives White some temporary initiative. He is now planning to further increase the pressure with Qb3 followed by Ne5. In my opinion, the easiest solution for Black is } 11... h6 12. Bh4 Bf5 $15 { Our bishop is excellently placed on f5. Later on, Black would like to continue with ...g6-g5 followed by ...e7-e6. In this case, White always needs to reckon with ...Nxc3 followed by ...Ne4. Black is already slightly better. } ) 8... O-O { This pawn sacrifice is Black's most precise solution. Instead of defending a slightly more passive position, Black is playing for compensation based on his superior development. An important crossroads arises after } 9. dxe7 Qxe7+ 10. Nge2 a6 { White should now decide on the future of his light-squared bishop. Black is planning to follow with ... b7-b5 and ...Bb7. } 11. Bd3 { This move strategically more ambitious. White tries to retain his control of the light squares. } ( 11. Bxd7 { After } 11... Bxd7 12. O-O Bc6 { Black's superior development and bishop pair give him excellent compensation for the pawn. The game might continue } 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. d5 Bd7 $44 { White's main problem in this position is that there are no good squares for his knights. Black has every chance to play for a win in this position. } ) 11... b5 12. O-O Bb7 { In return for the pawn, Black managed to achieve harmonious development for his pieces. He is now ready to decentralize the c3-knight by means of ...b5-b4. Therefore, a logical move would be } 13. a3 ( 13. Bg5 { Black can react with } 13... b4 14. Na4 Qd6 { when White struggles to coordinate his pieces. The idea of ...Qd5 is very annoying in this position. A logical follow-up would be } 15. Bf4 Qd5 16. f3 Rfe8 17. Qd2 Bc6 { questioning the a4-knight. } 18. b3 { White has nothing better than this natural move. } ( 18. Qxb4 { In this case, Black can go for the following forced sequence - } 18... Bf8 19. Qb3 Rxe2 20. Bxe2 Qxd4+ 21. Be3 Qxa4 22. Qxa4 Bxa4 $15 { White does not have enough compensation for the material. } ) 18... Bb5 { After exchanging the important d3-bishop, Black would like to install a knight on d5. The game might continue } 19. Nb2 Bxd3 20. Nxd3 Qb5 21. Bg3 Nd5 $44 { when Black has an excellent compensation for the pawn. } ) 13... Rfe8 14. Bg5 Rad8 15. Re1 Nf8 16. f3 Ne6 $44 { This position was reached in the game 1/2-1/2 (54) Carlsen, T (2360) -Fleury, F (2347) Remote email 2014. White is under a lot of pressure. } ) ( 7. Qb3 O-O { Now, White should decide whether to complete the development with simple moves or stick to the pawn. Against normal developing moves such as Nf3 and Bc4, Black will follow with the standard maneuver ...Nd7-b6. Against artificial moves like Nge2 or g3, we play for compensation by using the advance ...a7-a6. The move } 8. Be2 { is the most challenging one and requires special handling. White wants to defend the d5-pawn with Bf3 followed by Nge2. This position requires energetic play from Black. } ( 8. Nge2 { planning to defend the d5-pawn with Nf4 on the next move. In this case, I would advocate the energetic } 8... e6 $1 9. dxe6 Nc6 { Black is playing for the initiative. His active pieces and superior development provide enough compensation for the material. The most logical sequence is } 10. exf7+ Rxf7 11. d5 Na5 12. Qb4 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Nc3 Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 Bd7 $44 { Black has very nice compensation for the pawn. Playing with a king stuck in the centre is practically very difficult for White. } ) ( 8. g3 { White is getting ready to defend the d5-pawn with Bg2. The problem is that the advance g2-g3 does not contribute to the development. Therefore, Black should initiate a dynamic play with } 8... e6 9. Bg2 { The safest. } ( { Quite risky is } 9. dxe6 Bxe6 10. Qxb7 { White managed to win two pawns but his lag in development and exposed king make the position very difficult from a practical perspective. Black can keep developing the initiative with very simple moves. The following line is quite illustrative: } 10... Re8 11. Nge2 Nbd7 12. Bg2 Rb8 13. Qxa7 Bc4 14. Bf3 Nd5 15. O-O { In this position, Black can either force a draw with } 15... Ra8 ( { or play } 15... N7b6 $44 { with an excellent compensation. } ) ) 9... Nxd5 10. Nf3 Nc6 $13 { Black does not have any problems whatsoever in this position. } ) ( { The natural developing move } 8. Nf3 { is well met by the standard } 8... Nbd7 { [%cal Gd7b6] planning to regain the pawn with ...Nb6 on the next move. In order to keep his material advantage, White should go for } 9. Bg5 Nb6 10. Bxf6 exf6 { This structure is typically quite favorable for Black in view of the bishop pair, the vulnerable d5-pawn, and the good central control provided by the doubled pawns. White's main problem is the lack of good squares for his knights. After the natural } 11. Be2 { we can play } 11... a5 $1 { Remember this thematic idea. By creating the threat of ...a5-a4, Black wants to provoke the weakening } 12. a4 { which can be answered with } 12... Qd6 $44 { Black is ready to make use of the weak b4-square by playing ...Qb4 on the next move. Additionally, we can increase the pressure on d5 by means of ...Rd8. This position will be featured in some of the model games. } ) ( { In case of } 8. Bc4 { the most precise reaction is } 8... Nbd7 { The maneuver ...Nd7-b6 is an excellent antidote against the construction Qb3-Bc4. } 9. Nge2 { Obviously, White should proceed with the development. } ( { Another possible direction is } 9. Bg5 Nb6 10. Nge2 Nxc4 11. Qxc4 b6 12. O-O Bb7 { Black is threatening to win the pawn back with all the comfort. Therefore, White's most logical continuation is } 13. Bxf6 { when after } 13... exf6 { we reach our familiar structure which is typically quite favourable for Black. I remind you that White's main problem is the lack of good squares for his knights. The play might continue } 14. Rad1 Rc8 15. Qb3 Re8 16. Rfe1 Bh6 $15 { The bishop is excellently placed on this square. Now, White does not have the resource of Nf4. Black can start playing around the doubled pawns. Ideas such as ...Ba6-c4 or ...Rc7-e7 come into consideration. } ) 9... Nb6 10. O-O Nxc4 11. Qxc4 b6 { Quite a thematic way of handling the position. After eliminating the c4-bishop, Black usually tries to regain the pawn with ...b7-b6 followed by ...Bb7. } 12. Bg5 Bb7 13. Nf4 { An ambitious approach. White wants to keep the pawn without parting with his bishop. } ( { After } 13. Bxf6 exf6 { we transpose to 9.Bg5. } ) 13... Qc8 $1 { The most precise continuation. Besides the idea of exchaning the queens, Black also wants to play ...Qf5. The endgame arising after } 14. Qxc8 Raxc8 $15 { is in Black's favour. Black bishop pair and better pawn structure are more important than White's meaningless extra pawn. } ) 8... Na6 { We play this move with a very concrete idea in mind. This idea will become clear in the annotations to Black's next move. If White plays a slow move such as Nf3, Black is ready to start surrounding the pawn with ...Nc7 followed by ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7. } 9. Bf3 { This is the critical continuation. White defence the pawn in a very solid way. His next move is going to be Nge2. At this point, my suggestion is } 9... b5 $5 { Black immediately goes for dynamic play. If White takes the pawn, we will need the b8-square for the rook. That's why we started with 8...Na6. } ( { The traditional continuation } 9... Qb6 { is sufficient for equality as well. White's main continuation is } 10. Qxb6 ( { The alternative } 10. Nge2 { is well met by } 10... Qxb3 11. axb3 Rd8 { White should now reckon with the annoying idea of ...Nb4. The critical line goes } 12. Ra5 Bg4 $1 { An important move. The exchange of the light-squared bishops will definitely weaken the d5-pawn. } 13. Bxg4 Nxg4 14. O-O Nf6 15. Bf4 Nb4 16. d6 e6 17. Rb5 Nbd5 $13 { Black managed to stabilize the position. The d6-pawn is doomed in the long run. The position is objectively equal. } ) 10... axb6 11. Nge2 { This position was featured in many games. It turns out that Black is in time to put strong pressure on the d5-pawn by means of } 11... Nb4 12. O-O Rd8 { White can no longer defend the pawn. Therefore, he can try to transform the advantage by sacrificing the pawn for initiative. The critical line goes } 13. d6 Rxd6 14. Bf4 Rd7 { The black rook is forced to temporarily occupy this awkward square. We need to prevent the move Bc7. Black is ready to continue with ...Nfd5 on the next move. The critical line goes } 15. Rfd1 Nfd5 16. Bg3 Nxc3 17. bxc3 Nc6 18. Nf4 Ra5 { Preventing Nd5 and preparing the advance ...e7-e5. Practice, as well as computer analysis, show that Black has enough counterplay in this position. } ) 10. a3 { The most natural continuation. White should stop the advance ...b5-b4. } ( { In case of } 10. Nge2 b4 11. Na4 Bb7 $15 { Black is already better since he will regain the pawn by keeping a stable static advantage. } ) 10... Rb8 { A very important part of Black's strategy. Once again, White should reckon with the advance ...b5-b4. White should play } 11. Bf4 Rb6 12. Nge2 { The most natural development. Note that White is now ready to answer ...b5-b4 with Na4. Black, however, is just in time to put strong pressure on d5 by playing } 12... Bb7 13. O-O Nc7 { White can no longer defend the d5-pawn. The move 14.Bxc7 is out of the question as well. In the long run, White will not be able to keep the d5-pawn. The most logical idea is } 14. d6 exd6 15. d5 { By giving the extra pawn, White is playing for a space advantage. Indeed, if Black allows the maneuver Nd4-c6, he will be in trouble. } ( { Another possible version of the same idea is } 15. Bxb7 Rxb7 16. d5 { The exchange of the light-squared bishops is in Black's favour. Every exchange reduces the significance of White's space advantage. This position was seen in the game 0-1 (34) Ciuffoletti, P (2106) -Kozlov, O (2294) Chess.com INT 2022. Now, the most straightforward would have been } 16... a5 { Depending on White's reaction, Black can proceed either with ...b5-b4 or ...a5-a4. } 17. Nd4 { The most ambitious.At this point, Black can exploit the unprotected d4-knight by playing } ( { After } 17. Rad1 b4 18. axb4 axb4 $13 { Black is doing fine. Once the white knight leaves the c3-square, the d5-pawn becomes quite vulnerable. } ) 17... a4 18. Qa2 Nfxd5 { After } 19. Nxd5 Bxd4 20. Rad1 Bg7 $13 { White's maximum is to get the pawn back and make a draw. } ) 15... Nd7 { This move is the key to Black's counterplay. He wants to proceed with ...Nc5 followed by ...b5-b4. An important crossroads arises after } 16. Be3 Nc5 17. Qc2 b4 18. axb4 Rxb4 19. Rfd1 { Now, I like the move } ( { Of course, not } 19. Rxa7 $2 { when after } 19... N7a6 $17 { [%cal Gd8b8] the a7-rook will be trapped. The next move is ...Qb8. } ) 19... Nd7 { which was played by the renowned theoretician Ntirilis, N in one of his correspondence games. Black's obvious idea is to create counterplay with ...Ne5. } 20. Nf4 { This is the most natural continuation. White needs to free the e2-square for his bishop. On the other hand, the knight is artificially placed on f4. } ( { It goes without saying that after } 20. Rxa7 Ne5 $44 { Black has an excellent compensation for the pawn. } ) 20... Ne5 21. Be2 Bc8 { Another very precise move. White should now reckon with both ...Bf5 and ...Ng4. After } 22. Rxa7 Ng4 23. Bxg4 Bxg4 $44 { Black's strong bishop pair and active pieces gave him decent compensation in the game 1/2 (31) -1/2 (31) Compagnone,G (2306) -Ntirlis,N (2322) ICCF email 2018 } ) ( { After } 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Bc4 Nbd7 { we transpose to 7.Bc4. } ) 7... O-O 8. Nge2 { The most ambitious continuation. The knight is ready to protect the d5-pawn via f4. } ( { Another very popular continuation is } 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O ( { The symmetrical structure arising after } 9. d6 exd6 { is quite harmless for Black. Actually, having a pawn on d6 instead of d5 gives Black two important advantages: 1) the e5-square is under control 2) Black can use the d5-square for one of his minor pieces Very often, Black's play revolves around the lights squares in the centre. A possible idea is ...Nb6 followed by ...Bf5, and eventually ...Ne4. In this lecture, I provide some model games featuring this position. } ) 9... Nb6 { The only challenging continuation. } 10. Bb3 ( { After } 10. Qb3 Nxc4 11. Qxc4 b6 { we transpose to a position that was already discussed. } ) 10... a5 $1 { This extremely rare move is Black's most precise continuation. The idea is to provoke the advance a2-a3. Later on, Black will make use of the vulnerable b3-bishop.This is the most natural response. } ( { I am not a big fan of the traditional } 10... Nbxd5 { After } 11. Re1 b6 ( { The position arising after } 11... Bg4 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 e6 14. Bg5 $14 { is slightly better for White in view of his bishop pair and active pieces. } ) 12. Ne5 Bb7 13. Bg5 { it's not so easy to deal with White's pressure. } ) 11. a3 ( { Ignoring the resource of ...a5-a4 by playing } 11. Re1 { might backfire. Black should play } 11... Bg4 { when after } 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 { the move } 13... a4 { is already possible. } 14. Bc2 Nfxd5 $15 { Black is already slightly better. White should play very energetically in order to compensate for his structural problems. } ) ( { As usual, we answer } 11. Bg5 { with } 11... h6 { clarifying the position of White's dark-squared bishop. } 12. Bxf6 ( { Worse is } 12. Bh4 { when after } 12... Nfxd5 13. Re1 g5 14. Bg3 Bg4 { Black manages to achieve perfect coordination. He is now ready to strengthen the position even further with the advance ...e7-e6. } ) 12... exf6 $1 { The right way to recapture. Black is always happy to play this structure. A possible development would be } 13. h3 Bd7 { [%cal Ga5a4] This developing move is also creating the threat of .. .a5-a4. Therefore, White should answer with } 14. a4 Re8 15. Nd2 { At this point, a very good idea would be } 15... Nc8 16. Rc1 Bf8 $13 { If Black manages to play ... Bb4 followed by ...Nd6, he will be better. White's extra pawn is not significant at all. } ) 11... Nbxd5 12. Re1 { White is playing in a classical fashion. He is now ready to increase the pressure with Bg5 and Ne5. The following line shows how the inclusion of the moves a2-a3 and ... a7-a5 helps Black. } 12... Bg4 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 e6 15. Bd2 Qb6 { This is the subtle difference. The b3-bishop is now vulnerable due to the advance a2-a3. After } 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Bxd5 exd5 $11 { we reach an equal position. } ) 8... Na6 { Since White is planning to defend the pawn, Black is getting ready to put maximum pressure. His next moves are going to be ...Nc7 followed by ...b7-b6, and ...Bb7. In some cases, Black can even consider ...b7-b5. } 9. O-O Nc7 10. Nf4 { The most principled continuation. Besides protecting the pawn, White also opens the e-file for the rook. } ( { The alternative } 10. Qb3 { is quite harmless. } 10... b6 { This is the most natural continuation. Black is planning to continue with . .. Bb7. } ( { Another very interesting direction is } 10... b5 $5 11. Bxb5 Rb8 { giving a second pawn in order to put the opponent under pressure. A correspondence game saw } 12. Bf4 Nfxd5 13. Nxd5 Rxb5 14. Bxc7 Qxd5 15. Qxd5 Rxd5 { In this endgame, Black has an excellent compensation for the pawn due to his bishop pair. 1/2 (21) -1/2 (21) Belanoff,S (2193) -Gredescul,A (2025) ICCF email 2015 } ) 11. Bf4 Bb7 { White can no longer keep the pawn without accepting strategic concessions. } 12. d6 { We have already seen this typical sacrifice followed by d4-d5. White is giving the pawn back in order to play for a space advantage. } ( { The move } 12. Bxc7 $6 { is dubious. White does not have good prospects without the dark-squared bishop. For instance, after the moves } 12... Qxc7 13. Rac1 Bh6 14. Rc2 Rfc8 15. Bd3 Qd6 $15 { Black is already better. He will regain his pawn with all the comfort. } ) 12... exd6 13. d5 { In this position, the simplest solution would be } 13... b5 $1 { Black sacrifices a pawn in order to free his pieces.The critical direction is } ( { Of course, } 13... Rb8 { is playable as well. } ) 14. Nxb5 Nxb5 15. a4 { Only this move asks some questions.Black should opt for the following sequence - } ( { After } 15. Qxb5 Rb8 $13 { Black is in time to regain the d5-pawn by maintaining a very nice piece activity. } ) 15... Nxd5 16. Bxd5 Bxd5 17. Qxd5 Nc7 18. Qxd6 Nd5 $44 { Black has enough compensation. Most likely, he will soon regain the sacrificed pawn. } ) 10... b6 11. Re1 Bb7 12. Qb3 Qd6 $11 { [%cal Ga8d8] Blacc managed to solve all the problem. His next move is going to be ...Rad8 when White can no longer keep the extra pawn. White should play energetically to maintain the balance. You can take a look at the following example. I leave the remaining moves without comment. } 13. a4 Rad8 14. Nb5 Nxb5 15. axb5 Bxd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Rxa7 Bxd4 18. Bxd5 Qxd5 19. Qxd5 Rxd5 20. Raxe7 Rxb5 21. Bh6 Bg7 22. Bxg7 Kxg7 23. g3 Rd8 24. R1e3 Rxb2 25. Rf3 Rf8 26. h4 Rc2 27. Rb7 Rc6 28. Kg2 Rf6 { 1/2-1/2 (28) Edouard,R (2628) -Van Foreest,J (2615) Germany 2016 } *[Event "?"]
