{The following model games feature some positions with IQP which are quite favourable for Black.} 1. c4 ({Our move order will be} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. cxd5 Bg7 7. Bc4 O-O 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O Nb6 10. Qb3 Nxc4 11. Qxc4 b6 {transposition to the game.}) 1... c6 2. e4 d5 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. exd5 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Nf3 Bg7 7. Bc4 O-O 8. O-O Nbd7 9. d4 Nb6 10. Qb3 Nxc4 11. Qxc4 b6 {This is the first position of interest. As mentioned in the theoretical part, Black is planning to regain the pawn by means of ...Bb7 followed by ...Nxd5. In such a case, Black will be statically better due to the superior pawn structure. In this game, White went for the energetic} 12. Ne5 Bb7 13. Nc6 {It turns out, however, that after} Qd7 {White's position is quite vulnerable. Black's next move is going to be ..Rac8 when White can no longer keep the pawn.} 14. b4 {Played with the intention to stabilize the knight with b4-b5. Nevertheless, White's development is not sufficient to support such an overextended queenside.} ({Even worse would be} 14. Ne5 {when after} Qd6 {The d5-pawn will be lost. In case of} 15. Nc6 Rfc8 $17 {White's position is getting even more problematic due to the vulnerable knight.}) ({The most reasonable choice would have been} 14. Re1 {In this case, Black can respond with the simple} Rfe8 $15 {[%cal Ga8c8] followed by ...Rac8. Most probably, Black will regain the pawn by keeping a slight advantage in view of the better pawn structure.}) 14... a6 {This is a prohylaxis against b4-b5.} ({According to the computer, even more precise would have been} 14... e6 {The point is that the position arising after} 15. Ne5 Rfc8 16. Qd3 Qd6 17. dxe6 Qxe6 $15 {offers Black tremendous compensation for the pawn. The advance b2-b4 is a huge weakening of the queenside.}) 15. Re1 Rfe8 $15 {Again, Black is slightly better. After ...Rac8, the pawn will be regained under favourable circumstances. Later on, Black managed to win the game.} 16. Bg5 Rac8 17. Qb3 Nxd5 18. Nxd5 Qxc6 19. Nf4 Bxd4 20. Rad1 e5 21. b5 axb5 22. Rxd4 exf4 23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. f3 Qc1+ 25. Rd1 Re1+ 26. Kf2 Qxd1 0-1

