{This example is quite similar to the previous one. The purpose of this game is to show how easily White can get worse by playing natural moves. The position of interest arises after White's 15.Bf4.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. cxd5 Bg7 7. Bc4 O-O 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. O-O Nb6 10. Qb3 Nxc4 11. Qxc4 b6 12. Ne5 Bb7 13. Nc6 Qd7 14. Re1 Rfe8 {We are familiar with everything that has been played so far. In this position, White decided to play} 15. Bf4 {White just wants to complete the development with Rad1 on the next move. It turns out, however, that after} Rac8 {There is no way to the equality. Black is ready to take on d5. The game went} 16. Rad1 Nxd5 {This natural move is enough for a small advantage.} ({Another very good option, also advocated by the computer is} 16... e6 {Remember this typical idea which is designed to undermine the white knight. The game can continue} 17. Qb3 Nxd5 18. Ne5 Qe7 $15 {with a stable advantage for Black.}) 17. Qxd5 Qxc6 18. Qg5 Qd7 $15 {[%cal Gc8c4] Black obtained a better position due to his bishop pair and better pawn structure. White should reckon with the idea of ...Rc4. The advance ...b6-b5 is another thematic idea to watch for.} 19. Qg3 Rc4 20. d5 b5 21. a3 a5 22. Be5 f6 23. Bf4 b4 24. axb4 axb4 25. Ne4 Bxd5 26. Qd3 Rd8 27. b3 Rcc8 28. Nd6 Rc5 29. Nc4 Bf8 30. h3 Qb7 31. Be3 Bxg2 32. Qxd8 Bxh3 33. f3 Qxf3 0-1

