{ Let's take a look again at this typical position. Some of your opponents might opt for the active } 12. Bf4 Bb7 13. Bc7 $2 { It turns out that this idea is a tactical mistake because of the precise } 13... Qc8 $1 { The pin along the c-file tends to be very annoying. The following line is a good illustration of Black's problems. } 14. Rac1 { This position was reached in the game Granero Roca, A - Camarena Gimenez, Rufino, 2018. At this point, Black should have played } 14... Ne8 $1 { This move marks the beginning of the following forced sequence } 15. Nb5 Bh6 $1 { An important move, forcing the white rook into an unfavorable square. } 16. Rc3 { The most tenacious. } ( { Even worse is } 16. Rc2 { when after } 16... Qf5 17. Qe2 Rc8 $19 { White's position is falling apart. The simplest among Black's numerous threats is ... a7-a6. } ) 16... a6 17. Na3 b5 18. Qe2 Nxc7 19. Qe5 { White is lucky enough to have at least this resource. Otherwise, he is just losing a piece. Nevertheless, the position arising after } 19... Bg7 20. Qg3 Qd8 21. Rxc7 Bxd5 $19 { is just winning for Black due to the poorly coordinated white pieces. Very soon he is going to win material. One of the threats is ... Bxf3 followed by ... e7-e5. } *[Event "Olympiad-41"]
