{Now, we shall take a look at one of the most favourable types of IQP that we can get in the Panov Attack. In this example, White was outplayed in a very classical way.} 1. d4 ({Our move order will be} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Nf3 Bg7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Nc6 9. h3 dxc4 10. Bxc4) 1... Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 5. e3 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 7. O-O cxd4 8. exd4 Nc6 9. h3 dxc4 10. Bxc4 {In the theoretical section, we have already examined this position which is basically a Tarrasch Defence with colours reversed. White would be glad to put some pressure with natural moves such as Re1 and Bg5. Black, however, has an important resource at his disposal -} Na5 11. Be2 Be6 {Occupying the extremely important a2-g8 diagonal. In this position, White does not have any initiative in return for the isolated pawn. At the same time, Black is ready to continue with ...Rc8 and ...Nd5. The game went} 12. Bf4 Rc8 13. Rc1 Nd5 {This move forces further simplifications after which the isolated pawn will become even more vulnerable. The following couple of moves are quite natural.} 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15. b3 Rxc1 16. Bxc1 Rd8 17. Bb2 Nc6 $17 {White is doomed to passive defence. It is getting harder and harder to protect the d4-pawn. Later on, Fier managed to convert his advantage.} 18. Bc4 Qd6 19. Bxe6 Qxe6 20. Qa1 Qd5 21. Rc1 e6 22. Rc4 Qd6 23. Qc1 Qb8 24. Qe3 Rd5 25. Qe4 Qd8 26. Bc3 Qd7 27. Ne5 Bxe5 28. dxe5 b5 29. Rxc6 Qxc6 30. Qb4 Qc5 0-1

