{ The following example shows how White's active play can backfire in this line. In this position, White played } 12. Ne5 Rc8 13. Qa4 { White not only takes the important c4-square under control but also tries to prove that our a5-knight can be vulnerable. White would like to proceed with natural moves such as Bg5, Bf3, and Rad1. It turns out, however, that the white queen is too exposed on a4. Black's most precise reaction is } 13... a6 { [%cal Gb7b5] Immediately creating the threat of ...b7-b5. White should already by precise. } 14. Rd1 b5 15. Qa3 Qb6 { This active move does not break the balance but forces White to play precisely. Indeed, after } 16. Qxe7 Rfe8 { White immediately made a blunder by playing } 17. Qa3 $4 { This move is losing on the spot. } ( { Probably Polak rejected } 17. Qb4 { in view of } 17... Bf8 { Nevertheless, White has } 18. Na4 { at his disposal. Black should opt for } 18... Bxb4 19. Nxb6 Rb8 20. Bg5 Rxb6 21. Bxf6 Bb3 22. axb3 Rxf6 $44 { with an excellent compensation for the pawn. } ) 17... b4 18. Na4 { Probably, White was relying on this move, but it turns out that Black is winning on the spot. } 18... bxa3 19. Nxb6 axb2 20. Bxb2 Rc2 $19 { Black is winning a piece, thus securing a decisive advantage. } 21. d5 Rxb2 22. dxe6 fxe6 0-1[Event "?"]
