{In the following couple of model games, we will see what happens when White forces a transition into a symmetrical pawn structure with the advance d5-d6.} 1. e4 c5 (1... c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. cxd5 Bg7 7. Bc4 O-O 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. d6 exd6 {transposing to the game position.}) 2. c3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. cxd4 d5 5. exd5 Nf6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Bc4 O-O 8. Nf3 Nbd7 9. d6 {Instead of playing with a vulnerable IQP, White goes for a symmetrical position with a space advantage. As we have pointed out in the theoretical part, this approach is quite harmless. In my opinion, Black's simplest reaction is} exd6 10. O-O Nb6 11. Bb3 Bf5 {Our main strategy in this type of position should be playing on the light squares around the d4-pawn. Therefore, ...Ne4 and ...Rc8 followed by ...Nc4 are natural ideas for Black. In many cases, Black can also use the d5-square for one of his minor pieces.} 12. a4 {The attempt to disturb the b6-knight is counterproductive. Black wants to play ...Rc8 followed by ...Nc4 anyway.The following couple of moves are quite logical and fit into the spirit of the line.} ({Another option would have been} 12. Re1 Rc8 13. Bf4 Qd7 $13 {Once again, Black is doing fine. Our main ideas remain unchanged. Pay attention to the power of the d6-pawn. The control of the important squares e5 and c5 is quite important in this position.}) 12... Rc8 13. a5 Nc4 14. Bxc4 Rxc4 15. Qb3 Qc8 {Black is already slightly better due to his domination on the light squares. White's next move, however, is already a serious mistake. As you will see in a while, this move does not create a real threat.} 16. Nb5 $2 Be6 {This continuation is enough for an advantage.} ({Another very strong reaction would have been} 16... Bc2 17. Qe3 Re8 18. Qf4 Qd7 $17 {with a tremendous advantage. Note that 19.Nxd6 does not work in view of ...Nh5.}) 17. Qa3 Qd7 $17 {Black has a huge advantage. Later on, he managed to win the game.} 18. Nc3 (18. Nxd6 Rc6 $19) 18... Bg4 19. Ne2 Nd5 (19... Re8 $17) 20. h3 Bf5 21. Ng3 Bc2 22. b3 Rc3 23. Qa4 Qxa4 24. bxa4 Rc4 25. Ba3 Rd8 26. Rfc1 Bh6 27. Re1 Rxa4 28. Re2 Bd3 29. Rb2 Rd7 30. Rb3 Bc4 0-1

