{ Let's take a look at another example in which Black managed to outplay his opponent in this symmetrical pawn structure. In this position, White played } 12. a4 { and answered } 12... Rc8 { with } 13. Bg5 { In my opinion, this is a dubious idea since White will either give his dark-squared bishop for the knight or allow the move ...Ne4. } 13... h6 { This is almost always the most precise reaction to Bg5. Black immediately wants to clarify the position of White's dark-squared bishop. In the game, after } 14. Bh4 g5 15. Bg3 { Black played } 15... Ne4 { which is a thematic way of fighting for domination on the light squares around the d4-pawn. } 16. Nxe4 Bxe4 17. Nd2 { White tries to improve his problematic knight. If allowed, he can continue with a4-a5 followed by Nc4. Additionally, the f3-square is now available for the queen. } 17... Bd3 { Black wins an important tempo. His idea is to proceed with ...d6-d5 on the next move. The drawback of this plan is that after ...d6-d5, the e5-square will become available for the white knight. } ( { More in the spirit of the structure would have been } 17... Bd5 18. Bxd5 Nxd5 { In this position, White should play very energetically since Black is statically better. If provided with enough time, Black will prepare the advance ...f7-f5. White should immediately put pressure on d6 by means of } 19. Ne4 { when Black should answer with } 19... Rc6 { Unfortunately, ...f7-f5 is not an immediate threat in view of Qb3. Black, however, wants to exchange the powerful white knight with ...Nf6. After such an exchange, Black's play will be easier due to the superiority of his bishop. Therefore, White's most logical try is } 20. Rc1 { The d6-pawn is in danger. Black should look for concrete solutions. The following sequence seems quite logical - } 20... Ne7 21. Rxc6 Nxc6 22. d5 Nd4 23. Nxd6 f5 24. f3 Qb6 25. Bf2 Qxd6 26. Bxd4 Qxd5 $11 { with a draw. } ) 18. Re1 d5 19. Nf3 { The white knight is immediately heading for the e5-square. On the other hand, we can use the space gained with the advance ... d6-d5 by playing } 19... Bf5 20. Ne5 Nc4 { We not only challenge the e5-knight but also start exerting pressure on the queenside. The game went } 21. Qf3 Be6 22. Qh5 $6 { This is a dubious decision because the queenside is now left unprotected. } ( { More to the point would have been } 22. Re2 { protecting the b2-pawn and planning to double the rooks. In my opinion, Black should play } 22... Nd6 { planning to put the knight on f5. In case of } 23. Bxd5 Bxd5 24. Qxd5 Nf5 25. Qxb7 Nxd4 $44 { Black's piece activity gives him enough compensation for the pawn. } ) 22... Nxb2 $15 { The most logical choice. Now, White should try to prove compensation for the pawn. In the game, he didn't manage to do so. } 23. Re2 Nc4 24. Ng4 Bxg4 25. Qxg4 f5 26. Qh5 f4 27. Rae1 fxg3 28. hxg3 Qf6 29. Re7 Rf7 30. R7e6 Qxf2+ 31. Kh2 Rcf8 32. R1e2 Qxd4 33. Bc2 Rf1 0-1[Event "Casino op 3rd"]
