{ Let's take a brief look at another fragment. In this example, the jump ...Ne4 was even more effective in comparison with the previous game. In this familiar position, White played } 12. Bg5 { It goes without saying that Black's most precise reaction is } 12... h6 { immediately clarifying the position of the dark-squared bishop. The game went } 13. Bh4 Rc8 14. Rc1 Qd7 { White should have paid attention to this move. Black unpins the knight and prepares the thematic ...Ne4. In the game, White played the careless } 15. Qd2 $6 { which is playing into Black's hand. Better would have been to opt for a cautious move like 15. Re1. The game saw } 15... Ne4 16. Nxe4 Bxe4 $15 { White already faces problems since there is no favourable way of preventing ... Bxf3. White should accept a compromised pawn structure. } 17. Bg3 Bxf3 18. gxf3 d5 19. h4 Qf5 20. Kg2 Nc4 21. Bxc4 dxc4 22. d5 Rfd8 23. Rfd1 h5 24. d6 Rd7 25. Qb4 a5 26. Qa4 Kh7 27. Rd5 Qxd5 28. Qxd7 Rf8 29. Qe7 f5 30. Bf4 Rf7 31. Re1 Bxb2 32. Qg5 Bg7 33. Re7 c3 34. Rxf7 Qxf7 35. Qe7 Kg8 36. Qd8+ Qf8 37. Qc7 Bf6 38. d7 Bxh4 39. Bd6 Qd8 40. Qc4+ Kg7 41. Qxc3+ Kh7 42. Qc7 b5 43. Qc6 Qg5+ 44. Kf1 Qd2 45. Bc5 Qc1+ 46. Kg2 Bd8 47. Qd5 Qg5+ 48. Kf1 Qc1+ 49. Kg2 Qg5+ 50. Kf1 1/2-1/2[Event "?"]
