{Now, we will cover the more ambitious 13.Bf4.} 1. e4 c6 2. c4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. cxd5 Nf6 5. Qa4+ Nbd7 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bc4 Bg7 8. d3 O-O 9. Nf3 a6 10. Qa3 b6 11. O-O Bb7 12. Re1 Re8 13. Bf4 {White keeps the e-file open for the rook and makes the advance ...d5-d6 possible in many variations. Another very thematic idea for White is the maneuver Ng5-e4. In my opinion, Black's most precise move is} Rc8 $1 {By putting pressure on the c4-bishop, Black is fighting against the maneuver Ng5-e4. With a rook on c8, after ...Nxe4, White will not be able to recapture with the pawn. Since the rook controls the c5-square as well, another good idea for Black is ...b6-b5 followed by ...Nc5.} 14. Rad1 ({A mistake would be} 14. Nd4 $2 {when after} b5 15. Bb3 Qb6 {Black is already clearly better. A game of Riazantsev saw} 16. Qb4 $4 {when after} a5 17. Qxb5 Qxd4 $19 {Black was winning.}) ({The most principled continuation is} 14. d6 {when Black should play} e6 {[%csl Rc4,Rd6][%cal Gf6h5,Gd7c5,Gb6b5] White cannot support the d6-pawn for a long time due to the unstable position of his bishops. Black's thematic ideas are ...Nh5 and ...Nc5 with or without .. .b6-b5.} ({With a bishop on f4, the move} 14... Bxf3 $2 {is met by} 15. dxe7 $18 {[%csl Rd8,Be3,Gf4]}) 15. Bb3 Nc5 16. Rad1 Nh5 17. Bg3 Nxg3 18. hxg3 Nxb3 19. Qxb3 Qxd6 $17 {Black is clearly better. He has a better pawn structure and a strong bishop pair. 1/2 (60) -1/2 (60) Serner,A (2507) -Rydholm,L (2525) ICCF email 2009 Corr 2013 [5.Qa4 - 13.Bf4]}) 14... b5 15. Bb3 Nc5 $17 {Without the move ...Rc8, this knight jump would have been impossible. Now, Black will regain the d5-pawn with comfort. He is already better and won a model game.} 16. Be5 Nxb3 17. Qxb3 Nxd5 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Ne4 Nf4 20. d4 Qd5 21. Qe3 Qxe4 22. Qxe4 Bxe4 23. Rxe4 Nd5 24. Re2 {[%csl Gd5]} f6 $1 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg7f7,Gg6g5,Gh7h5,Gg5g4,Gc8c4,Ge8c8,Gc4c2]} 25. g3 Rc4 26. Kf1 Kf7 27. Ne1 Rec8 28. Red2 a5 29. Ng2 Ke6 30. Ke2 Ra4 31. Ra1 b4 (31... h5) 32. Kd3 Kd6 33. Rc2 Rxc2 34. Kxc2 b3+ 35. Kxb3 Rxd4 36. Ne3 Nxe3 37. fxe3 Rd2 38. h4 Rg2 39. Ka4 Rxb2 40. Kxa5 Ke5 41. a4 Ke4 42. h5 e5 43. hxg6 hxg6 44. g4 Kxe3 45. Rf1 Rf2 46. Ra1 e4 47. Kb6 f5 48. gxf5 gxf5 49. a5 Rh2 50. a6 Rh6+ 51. Kc7 Rh7+ 52. Kb6 f4 53. a7 Rxa7 {1/2-1/2 (53) Najer, E (2669) -Kacheishvili, G (2613) Philadelphia 2009 CBM 131 Extra [5. Qa4 - 13.Bf4 (NB) ]} *

