{In this chapter, I am going to cover 13.Ng5. Even though this move is not particularly dangerous, it requires some concrete knowledge.} 1. c4 c6 2. e4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. cxd5 Nf6 5. Qa4+ Nbd7 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Bc4 O-O 9. d3 a6 10. Qa3 b6 11. O-O Bb7 12. Re1 {[%cal Ge1e7]} Re8 13. Ng5 {[%cal Gg5e4] Besides putting pressure on f7, White wants to follow with Nge4. In the event of exchange on e4, he will get rid of the doubled pawns, thus establishing a powerful pawn centre. Therefore, Black's most precise move is} Rc8 $1 {[%cal Gb6b5,Gd7c5] Taking the c4-bishop under control and preparing ...b6-b5 followed by ...Nc5.} ({After} 13... b5 14. Bb3 Nb6 $6 15. d6 e6 16. Bf4 $14 {White can put some pressure.}) 14. d6 {The most active continuation.} ({Very slow is} 14. Be3 {when Black should play} h6 15. Nf3 {The knight is forced to go back.} ({After} 15. Nge4 Nxe4 {White cannot recapture with a pawn since the c4-bishop is hanging. This is one of the main points behind 13...Rc8. In the event of} 16. Nxe4 {Black will start expanding on the queenside by means of} b5 17. Bb3 a5 $17 {with a big advantage. The game might continue} 18. Rac1 a4 19. Rxc8 Qxc8 20. Rc1 Qa8 21. Bd1 Bxd5 $17) 15... b5 {[%cal Gd7b6] Once the bishop has landed on e3, Black can go for the plan based on ...Nb6.} 16. Bb3 ({In case of} 16. Qb4 {Black can prepare the advance ...a6-a5 by means of} Rb8 $1 {[%cal Ga6a5]} 17. Bb3 a5 18. Qh4 (18. Qxb5 Bxd5) 18... a4 19. Bd1 h5 $15 {[%csl Rd5] Black will comfortably regain the pawn. His position is already slightly better.}) 16... Nb6 17. Bxb6 Qxb6 18. Qb4 Qd8 ({There is nothing wrong with the thematic} 18... Qd6 $5) 19. Ne5 (19. a4 Nxd5 $15) 19... Nxd5 20. Bxd5 Bxd5 $15 {with a slight advantage for Black.}) (14. Nge4 Nxe4 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Rd3e4]} 15. Nxe4 Ne5 {[%csl Rd5] When the c5-square is controlled by the knight, Black should opt for this thematic reaction.} 16. Bf4 {This position arose in the game Yankovsky - Erenburg, 2012. Now, Black should have played} b5 $1 {[%csl Rd3]} 17. Bxe5 (17. Nc5 bxc4 18. Bxe5 Qxd5 19. Nxb7 Bxe5 $19) 17... Bxe5 18. Bb3 Qb6 {[%cal Ga6a5] followed by . ..a6-a5. White is in trouble.}) 14... e6 15. Bf4 {We already know that the f4-bishop is not a stable defender of the pawn. Black can disturb it by means of ...Nh5.} ({After} 15. Nge4 Nxe4 {[%csl Rc4,Gc8][%cal Gc8c4] we can see another important idea -} 16. Nxe4 Bxe4 17. Rxe4 b5 18. Bb3 Nc5 {[%csl Ra3,Gd6][%cal Ga6a5,Gb5b4] Not only the d6-pawn is doomed but as it often happens in this line, White has problems with the mobility of his queen.} 19. Re2 ({After} 19. Bf4 a5 $1 20. d7 Qxd7 21. Qxa5 Nxe4 22. dxe4 Bxb2 $17 {White doesn't have compensation for the exchange. 0-1 (67) Ehmann,T (2320) -Schlosser,P (2507) Baden 2018 EXT 2020 [5. Qa4 - 13.Ng5]}) 19... Qxd6 20. Be3 Red8 {Black was clearly better in 0-1 (28) Kulkarni, R (2321) -Postny, E (2600) Chess. com INT 2020 CBM 196 Extra [5.Qa4 - 13.Ng5]}) ({The sacrifice} 15. Bxe6 $2 {does not work in view of} fxe6 16. Nxe6 Nc5 $1 {[%csl Re1] when Black is immediately winning.}) 15... b5 16. Bb3 Nc5 17. Rad1 Nh5 $1 18. Be3 {We have arrived at a very important position for the variation. Now, Black should play} Nxb3 19. axb3 f5 $1 {[%csl Rc3,Re4,Rg5][%cal Gf5f4] Remember this thematic move. Black not only restricts the white knights but also creates the threat of ...f5-f4. The following moves are forced} 20. Nh3 Be5 {[%csl Bd6]} 21. Bc5 Rxc5 22. Qxc5 Bxd6 $44 {with a tremendous compensation for the exchange.} 23. Qe3 Qc7 24. g3 Qc6 25. f3 Qxf3 (25... e5 $1 {[%cal Bh5f6,Bd6c5,Be5e4]} 26. Kg2 Nf6 $17) 26. Qxf3 Bxf3 27. Rd2 Bb7 28. d4 h6 29. Nf2 Nf6 30. Rde2 Kf7 31. Nd3 b4 32. Na4 Bd5 33. Nac5 a5 34. Ra1 Ra8 35. Ne5+ Bxe5 36. dxe5 Ng8 37. Re3 Ne7 38. Nd7 Ra7 39. Nb6 g5 40. Rc1 Kg6 41. Rd3 Ra6 42. Nxd5 Nxd5 43. Rd4 f4 44. g4 h5 45. h3 hxg4 46. hxg4 Ra8 47. Rc6 Kf7 48. Rd2 Re8 49. Rh2 Ne3 50. Rh6 Kg7 51. Rhxe6 Rxe6 52. Rxe6 Nxg4 53. Re7+ Kg6 54. e6 Kf6 55. Re8 Ne5 56. Kg2 Nc6 57. Kh3 Nd4 58. e7 Nxb3 59. Kg4 Kf7 60. Rg8 Kxe7 61. Rxg5 Kd6 62. Kxf4 Nc5 63. Ke3 a4 64. Rg1 Kd5 65. Kd2 Kc4 66. Rc1+ Kd4 67. Kc2 Kc4 68. Rh1 Nb3 69. Rh4+ Nd4+ 70. Kb1 Kc5 71. Ka2 Nb3 72. Rh8 Kb5 73. Rb8+ Kc4 74. Rb7 Nc1+ 75. Kb1 Ne2 76. Rc7+ Kb3 77. Rd7 Kc4 78. Rh7 Nd4 79. Ka2 Nb3 80. Rh2 Nc1+ 81. Kb1 Nb3 82. Rh4+ Nd4 83. Ka2 Kd3 84. Rh8 Kc4 85. Rh4 Kd3 86. Rh5 Nb3 87. Rg5 Kc2 88. Rg2+ Kd3 89. Rg7 Kc4 90. Ra7 Kb5 91. Ra8 Nd2 92. Rd8 b3+ 93. Ka1 Nc4 94. Kb1 Kc5 95. Rb8 Ne5 96. Rh8 Nd3 97. Rh4 Nb4 98. Rh5+ Kb6 99. Rg5 Na2 100. Rg4 Kb5 101. Rh4 Ka5 102. Rg4 Kb5 103. Rh4 Ka5 104. Rg4 {1/2-1/2 (104) Socko,B (2637) -Laznicka,V (2598) Ostrava 2009 CBM 130 [5.Qa4 - 13.Ng5]} *

