{Time has come to adress the systems based on 5.Bb5+. Our approach will be similar to what we have been doing against the systems with 5.Qa4+.} 1. c4 c6 2. e4 d5 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. exd5 Nf6 5. Bb5+ Nbd7 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5] Once again, Black is planning to proceed with ... a7-a6 followed by ...b7-b5 and ...Bb7 with the idea of comfortably regaining the pawn.} 6. Nc3 a6 7. Be2 {This continuation leads to a positional battle. In favourable moment, White is ready to undermine ...b7-b5 with a2-a4. Additionally, in some cases, the bishop can put pressure on Black's position from the f3-square.} b5 8. d4 {The main continuation.} ({To similar positions leads} 8. Nf3 b4 9. Na4 Bb7 10. d4 Bxd5 {when most likely we will transpose to the main line.}) ({The setup with} 8. Bf3 {does not work very well here.} Bb7 9. d4 {And now, Black manages to simplify the position with} b4 10. Na4 Bxd5 $15 {Since White has no attacking chances, the isolated pawn will remain a long-term static weakness.}) ({The attempt to keep the pawn with} 8. Qb3 {is very well met by} Nc5 9. Qd1 e5 $1 {Instead of trying to regain the pawn, Black starts fighting for the initiative by gaining space in the centre. A correspondence game went} 10. Nf3 e4 11. Ne5 Bd6 12. d4 exd3 13. Nxd3 Nxd3+ 14. Qxd3 O-O $44 {[%cal Gb5b4] Black enjoys decent compensation for the pawn. His next move will be ...b5-b4. 1/2 (31) -1/2 (31) Millstone, M (2463) -Walker, G (2438) ICCF email 2011}) 8... b4 {This move played by Gelfand is Black's most precise continuation. He is ready to recapture the d5-pawn with the bishop.} ({After} 8... Nb6 9. Nf3 Nbxd5 10. a4 $1 b4 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Ne5 e6 (12... Bb7 $4 13. a5 $18 {[%cal Gd1a4]}) 13. Bd3 $14 {Black is under slight pressure due to the weakened queenside and White's kingside attacking chances.}) 9. Na4 Bb7 {As pointed out earlier, I think that it's better for Black to take the d5-pawn with the bishop.} ({Nevertheless, the alternative} 9... Nxd5 {completely playable -} 10. Bf3 Bb7 11. Ne2 e6 12. Nf4 Be7 (12... N7f6 13. O-O Be7 14. Nc5 Bc6 $11) 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. Bxd5 exd5 15. O-O O-O $11 {1/2-1/2 (17) Galanov,S (2616) -Noble,M (2574) ICCF email 2011 Corr 2013}) 10. Nf3 Bxd5 11. Bf4 {[%cal Ga1c1] Given the fact that White has no kingside attacking chances, he will try to use Black's queenside weaknesses.} e6 12. Rc1 Be7 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ga8a7,Gd8a8] Black is about to complete the development. White cannot make use of the c7-square. In the long run, Black's better pawn structure will be an important factor.} 13. O-O ({Nothing gives} 13. Bc7 Qc8 14. Bg3 Qd8 $11) 13... O-O 14. b3 Ra7 $1 {[%cal Gd8a8] Remember this thematic idea. The queen will be perfectly placed on a8. In this case, the mobility of the f3-knight will be seriously restricted.} 15. Ne5 Qa8 16. f3 {This move is already a concession. Now, the white king will be potentially weak.} Qd8 {[%csl Ga8,Be5][%cal Gd5a8,Gd7b6] After having provoked f2-f3, Black return the queen back to d8. After that, he will follow with ...Ba8 and ...Nb6. After f2-f3, putting a knight on d5 would make a lot of sense.} 17. Bd3 Ba8 $1 {[%cal Gf6d5] Black is already slightly better.} 18. Qe2 a5 $15 {Ponomariov, R - Gelfand, B} (18... Nb6 19. Nxb6 Qxb6 20. Qf2 Nd5 $15) *

