1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. f3 Qb6 4. Nc3 { This is the most popular and principled approach. White not only develops a piece but also puts pressure on the centre. } ( { Another interesting idea is } 4. a4 { White's idea is to harass the black queen by means of a4-a5. On the downside, this move does not contribute to the development. Black's most precise reaction is } 4... e5 $1 { Remember this idea! In the Fantasy Variation, Black is often ready to sacrifice a pawn in order to exploit the diagonal a7-g1. The natural } 5. dxe5 { should be answered with } 5... a5 { [%cal Gf8c5] Before following with ...Bc5, we need to secure the position of the queen. } 6. Bd3 Bc5 7. Ne2 { The most natural way of development. } ( { A high-profile game saw } 7. Kf1 $6 { which is quite suspicious. After } 7... dxe4 8. fxe4 Be6 $17 { [%cal Gb8d7,Gg8e7,Ge7g6] Black was clearly better in the game 0-1 (51) Bauer, C (2638) -Ragger, M (2666) Haguenau 2013. He is now ready to start surrounding the e5-pawn by means of typical moves such as ...Ne7-g6, and ...Nd7. } ) 7... Ne7 8. exd5 cxd5 9. Nbc3 { The most natural. Besides putting pressure on d5, White can potentially make use of the b5-square. } ( { An alternative would be } 9. Nd2 { planning to challenge the c5-bishop by means of Nb3. Black, however, gets a very nice position by playing natural moves. The following line is quite illustrative. } 9... Nbc6 10. Nb3 Bf2+ 11. Kf1 O-O 12. Bf4 Be6 $44 { Black has an excellent compensation for the pawn in view of White's vulnerable king. At this point, he can consider further opening the position with ...f7-f6. } ) 9... O-O 10. Bf4 Nbc6 $15 { Once again, Black has an obvious advantage. White's only way of securing the king would be Qd2 followed by 0-0-0. In this case, Black can react with ... d5-d4 followed by ...Nd5. } ) ( { Some games saw } 4. a3 { which is designed to take the important b4-square under control. Once again, Black's most precise reaction is } 4... e5 5. exd5 { The most popular move which was also played by the legendary Ivanchuk.The IQP type of position arising after } ( { In such positions, we should always consider } 5. Qe2 { which is also the first suggestion of the computer. This position was reached in the game 1/2-1/2 (14) Smith, B (2478) -Ippolito, D (2409) Rockville 2014. At this point, Black could have reacted with the thematic } 5... exd4 6. exd5+ Kd8 7. dxc6 Nxc6 $13 { Even though the computer evaluates this position as balanced, Black's play is practically much easier. He can develop the initiative with natural moves such as ...Nf6, ...Bd6, and ...Re8. } ) 5... cxd5 6. Nc3 exd4 7. Nb5 a6 8. Nxd4 Nc6 9. Nge2 { is favourable for Black in view of his superior development and White's vulnerable king. 0-1 (41) Plenca,J (2334) -Ragger,M (2655) Sibenik 2011. At this point, Black could have played } 9... Bc5 10. c3 Nge7 $17 { with a huge advantage. It's not clear how White is going to complete the development. } ) ( { A very interesting alternative to the main line is } 4. c3 { strengthening the centre. If White manages to consolidate by completing the development, he will have the advantage in view of the strong pawn centre. It goes without saying that Black should act very energetically - } 4... e5 { Once again, this thematic move is the key to our counterplay. } 5. Qe2 { We are already familiar with this typical move. As we know, however, the opposition on the e-file is not dangerous for Black. } ( { A logical continuation is } 5. Ne2 { White is getting ready for a position with an isolated pawn on d5. In this case, the knight will land on the d4-square. Alternatively, White can also play Ng3. At this point, Black gets a nice position by means of natural development - } 5... Bd6 { One of the points is answering } 6. exd5 { with } 6... Ne7 { Black is playing for a compensation based on his superior development and White's vulnerable king. The following sequence shows how difficult is White's position in practice. } 7. dxc6 { The most principled. } ( { Of course, after } 7. Qb3 { Black should refrain from the exchange of the queens. He can just play } 7... Qc7 $44 { keeping an excellent compensation. } ) 7... Nbxc6 { Black has tremendously strong piece play in this position. It's not clear how White will manage to develop the pieces. It's very important that the move } 8. d5 { will be met by } 8... Bc5 { immediately targetting the white king. The best computer line goes } 9. Ng3 Bf2+ 10. Ke2 Nxd5 11. Qxd5 Be6 12. Qe4 O-O $44 { Black has fantastic compensation for the piece. He is ready to play ...f7-f5 on the next move. In a practical game, White wouldn't survive for too long with such a king. } ) ( { In my opinion, White's best continuation is } 5. exd5 cxd5 6. Bd3 { with the simple idea of completing the development by means of Ne2 and 0-0. This move was tried by the strong grandmaster Igor Kovalenko. } 6... Nc6 7. Ne2 Nf6 8. O-O { This position was reached in the game 1/2-1/2 (79) Kovalenko, I (2626) -Starostits, I (2444) Tallinn 2018. Now, my choice would have been } 8... Bd7 { threatening to take on d4. } 9. Kh1 Be7 $15 { Black is already slightly better in view of the superior development. As we already know from the previous lectures, the IQP position arising after dxe5 is quite favourale for Black. } ) 5... exd4 $1 { As always, this move is the most precise continuation. Black is ready to answer } 6. exd5+ { with } 6... Kd8 { As we know, on d8. the black king is safer than its white counterpart. In all these positions, the white queen is quite problematic. The critical position arises after } 7. cxd4 Nf6 8. Nc3 { Black has more than one good option here. For instance, both 8...Bd6 and 8...Bb4 are quite decent options. In both cases, Black's play is practically easier. I would like to demonstrate the computer's suggestion - } 8... c5 $1 { Black is immediately hitting the vulnerable d4-pawn. At the same time, we can use the d5-pawn as a shelter for the king. White's most precise reaction is } 9. Ne4 cxd4 10. Qb5 { trying to bail out by exchanging the queens. Nevertheless, after } 10... Bf5 11. Nxf6 gxf6 $36 { Black keeps the initiative due to his superior development. } ) 4... dxe4 5. fxe4 { This is the most principled choice. } ( { An interesting option is } 5. Nxe4 { White is trying to get a structure typical for the Classical Variation of the Caro-Kann Defence which starts with 3.Nc3. White's main strategy is to prevent our counterplay based on the breaks ...c6-c5 and ...e7-e5. Therefore, if allowed, he will continue with f3-f4 and Nf3. In my opinion, Black's most logical reaction is } 5... Bf5 6. c3 Nd7 7. Bd3 e5 $1 { Just in time! We need to carry out this break before White manages to get f3-f4 advance. After } 8. Ne2 { Black can play the simple } 8... Bg6 { preparing Ngf6. I find the following sequence quite logical } 9. Be3 Ngf6 10. Nxf6+ Nxf6 11. Qd2 Nd5 12. Bf2 O-O-O $13 { Black's better development and active pieces provide an excellent counterplay. It's very important that 13.dxe5 will be answered with 13...Bc5. } ) ( { A very serious alternative to the main line is } 5. Bc4 { This move reminding of the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit is quite justified here. White sacrifices a pawn for the sake of quick development and attacking prospects. } 5... Nf6 { Balck should prioritize the development since accepting the sacrifice is quite dangerous. } 6. fxe4 { The most natural continuation. } ( { Another very serious alternative is } 6. Bb3 { This is a typical move for the variation. Besides retreating the bishop to a safe square, White also protects the b2-pawn. } 6... Nbd7 { Remember this typical move. A recurring idea in the Fantasy Variation is answering fxe4 with .. .e7-e5. With his last move, Black prepares the advance ...e7-e5. } 7. Be3 { White keeps delaying the move fxe4. After this move, he can consider castling on the queenside by starting with Qd2 (e2) . } ( { Harmless is } 7. Nxe4 { Black can easily prepare the thematic advance ...c6-c5. } 7... e6 8. Ne2 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Be3 c5 $13 { This position was reached in the game. 1-0 (55) Adamson, R (2201) -Liang, J (2340) Charlotte 2020. Black gets a very nice version of this structure featuring majorities on the wings. } ) ( { The idea behind 6...Nbd7 can be seen in the line } 7. fxe4 $6 e5 8. Nf3 exd4 9. Nxd4 Bc5 { Black has an excellent play on the dark squares. The following sequence illustrates some of the typical ideas in such positions. } 10. Be3 O-O 11. O-O Ng4 { Remember this typical deflecting move. } 12. Qxg4 Bxd4 13. Bxd4 Qxd4+ 14. Kh1 Nc5 $15 { [%cal Gc8e6] with ...Be6 to follow. Once we manage to neutralize the pressure on the diagonal a2-g8, we are better in view of the superior pawn structure. } ) 7... Qa5 $5 { Even though 7...exf3 is perfectly playable as well, I like this little move which is designed to disturb the coordination in White's camp. } 8. fxe4 { The most principled choice. White wants to develop the knight via f3. } ( { In case of } 8. Bd2 { Black can return the pawn with } 8... e3 { trying to slow down White's development. The position arising after } 9. Bxe3 e6 10. Ne2 b5 11. O-O Be7 $13 { offers Black an excellent counterplay. At some point, he will opt for ...Bb7 followed by the thematic ...c6-c5. } ) 8... Nxe4 9. Nf3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 e6 { Black should play this move. The idea is just to complete the development with ...Be7 and ...0-0. } ( { Of course, we cannot play } 10... Qxc3+ $4 { After } 11. Bd2 Qb2 12. a3 $18 { [%cal Ga1a2] the queen is trapped. } ) 11. O-O Be7 { In this position, White has enough compensation for the pawn but nothing more. Black has enough resources to defend the kingside. Let's take a look at an example. } 12. Qe1 O-O 13. Qg3 Nf6 { Black has a very solid position. The ideas of ...Ne4 and ...Qxc3 are really annoying for White. A possible follow-up would be } 14. Ne5 Qxc3 15. Rad1 Ne4 16. Qf3 Nc5 17. Qg3 Ne4 $11 { with repetition, } ) ( { Another interesting gambit continuation is } 6. Qe2 { If Black takes on d4, White is ready to play Be3 followed by 0-0-0. Even though taking the d4-pawn is quite playable, I prefer to stick to the classical concept - } 6... Nbd7 { Once again, we see this very important typical idea. Black wants to answer } 7. fxe4 { with } 7... e5 { In this case, the white queen is not optimally placed on e2. After } 8. Nf3 Bd6 9. Bb3 O-O $13 { Black manages to solve all the problems. } ) 6... e5 { This thematic move is again the cornerstone of our counterplay. } 7. dxe5 { The most principled choice. Black should waste time to regain the pawn. Meanwhile, White will complete the development.The following couple of moves are logical and almost forced. } ( { Worse is } 7. Nf3 exd4 8. Qxd4 { since Black is in general interested in playing an endgame. } ( { Note that } 8. Nxd4 $2 { is very well met by } 8... Bg4 { [%cal Gb8d7,Ge8c8] when Black will develop a very strong initiative in view of his superior development. He is ready to proceed with ...Nbd7 followed by ...0-0-0. The game might continue } 9. Be2 Bxe2 10. Ncxe2 Nbd7 11. O-O O-O-O $17 { with a huge advantage for Black. White is hanging everywhere. } ) 8... Qxd4 9. Nxd4 { The endgame is balanced since Black's slightly better structure is compensated by the activity of the white pieces. The following correspondence game was developed in a very logical way. } 9... Nbd7 10. Bf4 Bb4 11. O-O-O O-O 12. Rhe1 Nb6 13. Bd3 Bg4 14. Nf3 Rfe8 $13 { Black enjoyed a decent position in the game 1/2-1/2 (28) Heyn, W-Meyner,H DESC email 2012. If White does not play energetically enough, Black's static advantage will tell in the long run. } ) 7... Ng4 8. Qe2 Nxe5 9. Bb3 Bg4 10. Nf3 Nbd7 11. Bd2 O-O-O { Black completed development and is ready to engage in a piece play. Connecting the rooks and securing the powerful e5-knight are our top priorities. } 12. O-O-O { The most natural continuation. } ( { White can also start with the immediate } 12. h3 { After } 12... Nxf3+ 13. gxf3 Bh5 14. O-O-O Ne5 $13 { This position was reached in the game 0-1 (53) Beerdsen, T (2520) -Bluebaum, M (2651) Sant Boi de Llobregat 2022. The vulnerable f3-pawn provides Black with more than enough counterplay. Later on, we can try to fix the kinside with the advance ...g7-g5. } ) 12... Bb4 { The best square for the bishop. Black wants to keep the d2-bishop tied to the defence of the knight. } 13. a3 { Before disclosing his further actions, White wants to clarify the position of the black bishop.The most precise reaction. We should keep our control of the c3-square. If allowed, Black will continue with ... Rhe8 followed by ...Nc5. A correspondence game went } ( { As usual, White can also play } 13. h3 { We already know that Black's thematic reaction is } 13... Nxf3 14. gxf3 Bh5 { In this structure, the bishop is very well placed on h5. Besides putting pressure on f3, it also protects the f7-pawn. Black is now ready to follow with ...Ne5. A logical continuation of the game would be } 15. a3 Ba5 16. Be3 Qc7 17. Qf2 Bb6 { Of course, Black is interested in exchanging the dark-squared bishops. After such an exchange, it would be easier for us to use the weak dark squares around the pawn chain f3-e4. The move } 18. Rhg1 { is well met by } 18... g6 $13 { eliminating any potential pressure on the g-file and overprotecting the h5-bishop. The f7-pawn is not actually hanging in view of ...Rhf8. } ) 13... Ba5 14. Na4 Qc7 15. Bxa5 Qxa5 16. Qf2 f6 $11 { Black managed to exchange the dark-squared bishops and stabilize the e5-knight. He does not have any problems whatsoever. 1/2-1/2 (28) Tylecek, D (2265) -Rodrigues, A (2272) LSS email 2017 } ) 5... e5 { Without this thematic break, the whole concept behind ...Qb6 wouldn't make any sense. } 6. Nf3 { This is the only good move in the position. } ( { It's very important to answer } 6. dxe5 { with } 6... Be6 $1 { The control of the diagonal a2-g8 is a recurring theme in the Fantasy Variation. Therefore, Black starts with this important move. White's extra pawn is not significant in this position. Black's next moves are going to be ...Nd7 followed by ...Ne7-g6. At some point, Black will regain the pawn with all the dividends. } 7. Nf3 Nd7 8. Ng5 $6 { This attempt to challenge the stability of Black's construction does not work. White wastes way too much time to exchange the e6-bishop. } ( { Nothing gives } 8. Qd4 { when Black can just continue with } 8... Ne7 $15 { followed by ...Ng6. Black is already better. } ) ( { The line } 8. Nd4 O-O-O 9. Nxe6 fxe6 { transposes to 8.Ng5 } ) ( { Some high-level games saw } 8. Bd3 Ne7 9. Qe2 Ng6 10. Qf2 { It goes without saying that the endgame is better for Black in view of his superior structure. On the other hand, it's difficult for White to complete the development without this move. } ( { Pointeless is } 10. Ng5 { when the simple } 10... Ndxe5 { would give Black a huge advantage. } ( { A decent alternative is } 10... O-O-O 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. Bc4 Bc5 13. Bxe6 Nxe5 $17 { Black has tremendous initiative in return for the pawn. White will not survive for too long with the king on e1. } ) 11. Nxe6 fxe6 { White didn't achieve anything by exchanging our bishop. The e6-pawn is actually useful since it controls important squares. Quite often, Black can even sacrifice this pawn for initiative. } 12. Bc4 Nxc4 13. Qxc4 O-O-O $17 { This position was reached in the game 1-0 (48) Sindarov, J (2661) -Keymer, V (2700) Astana 2023. Black has a tremendous advantage. } ) 10... Ngxe5 11. a3 $2 { This is a huge mistake. White should have exchanged the queens, accepting a difficult endgame. After } 11... Bc5 $19 { White has a winning advantage since White is unable to find a safe haven for the king. 0-1 (22) Erigaisi,A (2750) -Keymer,V (2600) Almaty 2022 } ) 8... O-O-O 9. Nxe6 fxe6 10. Bc4 Nxe5 { Once again, Black sacrifices the pawn for the purposes of his attack. } 11. Bxe6+ Kb8 12. Qe2 Nf6 $17 { with the usual compensation for the pawn. In a practical game, White is objectively lost. } ) 6... exd4 7. Nxd4 { The only way to fight for an advantage. White is going for a quick development based on Bc4 and 0-0. } ( { It goes without saying that the endgame arising after } 7. Qxd4 Qxd4 8. Nxd4 { is quite safe for Black. In my opinion, the most precise continuation is } 8... Bd6 { taking the e5-square under control. The immediate ...Nf6 will be answered with e4-e5. } 9. Bc4 Nf6 10. O-O Bc5 { Only now, when we don't have development problems, we can relocate the bishop to this more advantageous diagonal. After } 11. Be3 O-O 12. h3 Nbd7 $11 { The position is around equal. White's active pieces are compensated by Black's better pawn structure. } ) 7... h5 $5 { This rare idea was first tested by Vincent Keymer. The idea is to prepare ...Bg4 which disturbs the coordination in White's camp. The main alternative is 7... Nf6 but after 8.e5 Black should memorize very long lines in order to make a draw. } 8. Be2 { White proceeds with the development by preventing ...Bg4. This was the choice of Lagarde in his game against Keymer. } ( { A very important alternative is } 8. Bc4 Bg4 9. Nf3 Be7 $1 { Remember this move! The idea is to go for ...Bh4 in a favourable moment. } 10. Qe2 Nd7 { It's important to include this move before playing ...Bh4. The reason will become clear in a while. } 11. Bb3 { By protecting the b2-pawn. White is getting ready for Be3. } 11... Bh4+ 12. g3 ( { In case of } 12. Kd1 Bf6 $13 { Black has an excellent counterpay. The next move is going to be ...0-0-0. In a practical game, White's position is very difficult to handle. } ) 12... Ne5 { This is the reason why we needed the move 10. ..Nd7. Now, White should go for the following queen sacrifice - } 13. Nxe5 Bxe2 14. Bxf7+ Ke7 15. gxh4 { We must admit that White has an interesting compensation for the queen, but only computer can prove it. The best computer line goes } 15... Bg4 16. Bg5+ Nf6 17. Bb3 Qd4 18. Nc4 Rae8 19. Be3 Qd7 20. Ne5 Qd6 $15 { when White still needs to prove compensation. } ) ( { A recent game saw } 8. Be3 $6 { which is dubious since Black takes the important b2-pawn. After } 8... Qxb2 { White went all-in by playing } 9. Ndb5 $2 cxb5 10. Nd5 { This position was reached in the game 1-0 (23) Srija, S (2272) -Jarocka, L (2169) Stockholm 2023. At this point, Black could have played } 10... Bb4+ 11. Kf2 Bd6 $19 { when White does not have any compensation for the piece. } ) 8... Bg4 { We should play this move anyway. } 9. e5 { The point behind White's play. Black should now reckon with the advance e5-e6.This position was reached in the game 0-1 (33) Lagarde,M (2613) -Keymer,V (2693) Bydgoszcz 2022. At this point, the best would have been } ( { Another direction is } 9. Bxg4 hxg4 10. Qd3 { planning to proceed with Bf4 and 0-0-0. } ( { White does not have time for } 10. b3 $2 Na6 11. Bb2 { since after } 11... Rd8 $19 { Black is winning. } ) 10... Nd7 { [%cal Gd7c5] An important move. Black is now ready to harass the white queen via c5. The point is that after } 11. Bf4 { Black can exchange the queens with } 11... Nc5 12. Qc4 Qa6 { The endgame arising after } 13. Qxa6 Nxa6 14. O-O-O Nc5 $13 { is obviously acceptable for Black. } ) 9... Nd7 { White has nothing better than embarking on the following sequence } 10. e6 fxe6 11. Bxg4 hxg4 12. Nxe6 ( { After } 12. Qxg4 O-O-O 13. Nb3 { Black has the resource of } 13... Rxh2 $17 { with a huge advantage. } ) 12... Rxh2 { Once again, this typical idea works. The position arising after } 13. Rf1 Rxg2 14. Bg5 Ngf6 15. Qd3 Ne5 { is extremely complicated, but Black has fantastic play. I will provide the computer line, mainly for aesthetic pleasure. You can take a look but don't try to remember it. It's quite unlikely that your opponent will repeat the most precise computer moves. } 16. Qf5 Nf3+ 17. Rxf3 gxf3 18. O-O-O Kf7 19. Bxf6 Qe3+ 20. Kb1 Qxe6 21. Rd7+ Be7 22. Rxe7+ Kf8 23. Qxe6 Rg1+ 24. Qe1 f2 25. Bh4 Rxe1+ 26. Rxe1 fxe1 27. Bxe1 Kf7 $15 { /= The dust has settled. In this typical endgame, Black keeps winning chances. When rook is fighting against two minor pieces in the endgame, the presence of a distant passed pawn is a very important factor. } *[Event "?"]
