1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Ne5 { This strange-looking move is not at all innocent. It has been tried in a number of high-profile games. Besides preventing ...Bg4, White wants to obtain the bishop pair with Bb5+. This line can be extremely annoying if Black is not sufficiently well prepared. } ( { The idea of Bb5 can be executed also with } 4. d4 Nc6 5. Bb5 { Once again, White is planning to proceed with Ne5 and get the bishop pair if Black reacts with ...Bd7. } ( { An interesting idea is } 5. c3 { White is planning to proceed with Bf4, Bd3, and Nbd2, thus reaching the perfect setup for the Exchange Variation. Compared to the usual versions of the Exchange Variation, Black can make use of the fact that his knight is still on g8. Therefore, White cannot easily get control of the e5-square. Very often, Black goes for ...e7-e6 followed by ...Bd6, and ...Nge7. } 5... Bg4 { The most precise continuation. Before playing ...e7-e6, we need to get the bishop our of the pawn chain. White's most challenging response is } 6. h3 { Before playing Qb3, White would like to force the black bishop into the h5-square. } ( { The immediate } 6. Qb3 { is best answered with } 6... Qd7 ( { After } 6... Bxf3 7. Qxb7 Qc8 8. Qxc8+ Rxc8 9. gxf3 Nxd4 10. Kd1 $14 { White can rely on a small advantage since the bishop pair can be quite effective in asymmetrical pawn structures. } ) 7. Ne5 { This move is the reason why White wanted to force the black queen into the d7-square. } ( { In case of } 7. Be2 e6 8. Bf4 { Black can play } 8... f6 $1 { This is how we profit from the fact that the knight is still on g8. Besides taking the e5-square under control, Black can often expand on the kingside with the advance ...g7-g5 followed by ...h7-h5. A possible line would be } 9. Nbd2 g5 10. Bg3 Bf5 11. O-O h5 $13 { We have reached a typical position that is quite favourable for Black. White should already reckon with the threat of ...h5-h4. A typical regrouping in this structure would be ...Ne7 (h6) followed by ...Bg6 and ...Nf5. At the same time, White does not have constructive ideas. } ) 7... Nxe5 8. dxe5 a6 { First of all, Black needs to prevent the threat of Bb5. If he manages to consolidate the position with ...e7-e6 followed by ...Ne7-c6, he will be statically better in view of two factors: the semi-open c-file and the potentially vulnerable e5-pawn. White should play energetically. } 9. Na3 { [%cal Ga3b5] planning to follow with Nb5 on the next move. } ( { As pointed out in the comments, slow play by White would give Black an excellent position. For instance, after } 9. Be3 e6 10. Nd2 Ne7 $13 { [%cal Ge7c6] Black's position is easier from a practical perspective. He is ready to complete the development with ...Nc6 followed by ...Be7. } ) ( { Another dynamic attempt is putting pressure on the centre by means of } 9. c4 e6 10. Nc3 { After } 10... Ne7 { , however, Black's position is pretty solid. Now, White would regret not including the move h2-h3-Bh5. With the bishop on g4, after } 11. cxd5 exd5 $13 { [%csl Rh5][%cal Gg4e6,Gg4h5] the black bishop has the excellent e6-square. This wouldn't be the case in a position with a bishop on h5. } ) 9... e6 10. Nb5 Rc8 11. a4 { The construction Nb5-a4 can be quite annoying since it's not easy for Black to develop the kingside. For instance, 11...Bc5 is well met by 12. Be3. In this position, the computer likes } 11... Bh5 { which is a prophylactic move against a4-a5 followed by Ra4. Later on, Black wants to challenge White's space advantage with ...f7-f6. A possible line is } 12. Bd3 f6 13. Bf4 Bc5 $13 { Black is ready to proceed with ...Ne7. Very soon, the white knight will be forced to leave its active position. } ) ( { With the black knight being on g8, the plan with } 6. Bf4 { is completely harmless. After the moves } 6... e6 7. Nbd2 Bd6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. Bd3 Nge7 $13 { Black gets a favourable version of the Carlsbad structure since White cannot exploit the e5-square. Black can even offer an exchange of the light-squared bishops with the move ...Bf5. In the future, we will focus on our minority attack on the queenside. If White plays passive moves, however, we can often consider ...f7-f6 followed by ...e6-e5. } ) 6... Bh5 7. Qb3 { As explained above, this move is more challenging after the inclusion of the moves h2-h3 and ...Bh5. } 7... Qd7 8. Ne5 { the only constructive idea. Otherwise, Black will opt for ...e7-e6 followed by ...Bd6, and ...Nge7. } 8... Nxe5 9. dxe5 a6 10. c4 { This time, the advance c3-c4 is much more challenging. The thing is that after 10...e6 11.cxd5 exd5, the black bishop does not have e6-square at its disposal. Instead, we should opt for the following sequence - } 10... dxc4 11. Bxc4 e6 12. O-O b5 13. Bd3 Rd8 14. Be4 Bc5 $13 { [%cal Gg8e7] Black is doing fine. His next move is going to be ...Ne7. White should play very energetically since the e5-pawn might become vulnerable in the long run. } ) ( { Nothing changes } 5. Bf4 { Black can answer with the simple } 5... Bg4 $13 { [%cal Ge7e6,Gf8d6,Gg8e7] followed by ...e7-e6, ...Bd6, and ...Nge7. } ) ( { The move } 5. Ne5 { is usually connected with Bb5 which is covered in the move order starting with 4.Ne5. } 5... e6 6. c3 { This harmless move is the only independent continuation after 5.Ne5.Black can fight against the e5-knight by means of } ( { After } 6. Bb5 a6 { we transpose to 4.Ne5. } ) 6... Bd6 7. f4 Nge7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O f6 { We are already statically better because the advance f2-f4 creates weaknesses. White can try to justify his previous play with the aggressive } 10. Qh5 Nf5 11. g4 { The most consistent.Strangely enough, this natural move turns out to be a novelty. } ( { A huge strategic mistake would be } 11. Bxf5 $2 { when after } 11... exf5 12. Nd3 Re8 $17 { Black has a huge advantage in view of his bishop pair and weak e4-square. } ) ( { Another dubious approach is } 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Nd2 { Among all the other good options, I would prefer } 12... Qb6 { [%cal Gc8a6, Gc6c5] planning to follow with ...Ba6 and ...c6-c5. White's lag in development and poor coordination will tell. } ) 11... Nh6 { White can try to make use of the h6-knight by means of } 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. f5 { Such play, however, cannot be justified since the situation in the centre is not stable. The most precise is } 13... e5 { White is more than happy to sacrifice a pawn. He enjoys a powerful centre, better development, and a bishop pair. } ( { Even the simple } 13... Qe8 $15 { is enough for a small advantage. } ) 14. Bxh6 gxh6 15. Qxh6 exd4 $15 { [%cal Ga8b8,Gd8c7, Gc7g7] White's position is already difficult. Black is ready to increase the pressure with ...Rb8. Another good idea is going for an endgame with ...Qc7-g7. Note that after } 16. cxd4 $2 Qb6 $19 { White's position is falling apart. } ) 5... Qa5+ { In my opinion, this is the simplest solution. The idea is to force the white knight into the unfavourable c3-square. A very typical position would arise after } 6. Nc3 Bg4 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 e6 9. O-O Nf6 $13 { Due to the misplaced c3-knight, in this structure, Black often manages to generate pressure along the semi-open c-file. White would very much like to have a pawn on c3 in this position. } ) 4... e6 { The most precise move order. Black is planning to play against the e5-knight with ...Nc6 followed by ...Bd6, and ... Nge7. } 5. d4 { This move should be played before Bb5+. } ( { The immediate } 5. Bb5+ { is less precise in view of } 5... Bd7 6. Nxd7 Nxd7 { Now, it turns out that White cannot get d2-d4 without a strategic concession. } 7. d4 ( { After } 7. O-O a6 { The White bishop will be forced to retreat to the passive e2-square. Ideally, White would like to play d2-d4 followed by Bd3. } ) 7... Qa5+ { This is the point. White is again forced to play } 8. Nc3 { which is a strategic concession. After } 8... Nf6 $11 { Black is doing fine due to the misplaced c3-knight. As explained above, in such positions, the pressure along the c-file is quite annoying. } ) 5... Nc6 6. Bb5 { The idea of this move is to provoke ...Bd7 after which White can obtain the bishop pair. In this position, my suggestion would be the extremely rare } 6... a6 $5 { which was played only in 3 games so far, including 1 game of GM Petar Arnaudov and 1 game of mine. } ( { White's idea can be seen in the line } 6... Bd7 7. Nxd7 Qxd7 8. c3 Bd6 9. Nd2 Nf6 10. O-O { [%cal Gd2f3, Gd1e2,Gb5d3] In this position, White can fight for a small advantage. After simple moves such as Nf3 followed by Qe2 and Bd3, White will start gradually developing his kingside activity. In order to prevent any kingside actions, he will play a2-a4. Even though Black's position remains solid, I would take White here. } ) 7. Nxc6 { This is the most challenging continuation. } ( { The alternative } 7. Bxc6+ { is not dangerous for Black since he has a bishop pair and good central control. } 7... bxc6 8. O-O { After completing the development, White is planning to develop a kingside activity. For instance, ...Bd6 can be answered with Qg4. } ( { Taking the pawn } 8. Nxc6 { is not dangerous for Black. The following sequence seems quite logical - } 8... Qc7 9. Ne5 Bd6 10. O-O Ne7 11. Re1 f6 12. Nf3 g5 $44 { Black's bishop pair and good central control provide good compensation for the pawn. Additionally, we can expand on the kingside with ...Kf7 followed by ...h7-h5, and ...Nf5. In this case, White should always reckon with the advance ...g5-g4. } ) 8... Ne7 { The most flexible choice. It's not easy for White to prevent the idea of ...f7-f6 followed by ...Ng6. For instance, after } 9. Re1 f6 10. Nd3 Ng6 $13 { [%cal Gf8d6] Black is doing great. His next move is going to be ...Bd6 followed by ...0-0. Later on, the advance ...e6-e5 comes into consideration. In such positions, we can easily outplay our opponent in view of the good central control and the bishop pair. } ) ( { If White insists on getting the bishop pair, he can try } 7. Ba4 Bd7 8. Nxd7 Qxd7 9. c3 { The problem, however, is that the bishop is slightly misplaced on a4. Therefore, White is not in time to prevent Black's minority attack starting with ...b7-b5. The game might continue } 9... Bd6 10. Bc2 Nf6 11. Nd2 b5 $13 { when Black's minority attack on the queenside provides enough counterplay. } ) 7... Qc7 $1 { This is the point behind the move 6...a6. The idea is to regain the material by keeping a favourable pawn structure. } 8. Ba4 { The only way to fight for an advantage. } ( { The position arising after } 8. Na7+ Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. O-O Rxa7 { was reached in two games. In both of them Gadimbayli, A is playing White (against me and GM Petar Arnaudov) . Against Petar, he played } 11. a4 { trying to discourage Black from the minority attack. } ( { Our game continued } 11. Bf4 Nf6 12. Nd2 Be7 13. a4 O-O 14. c3 Raa8 { [%cal Gb7b5] This version of the Carlsbad structure in which the light-squared bishops, as well as a pair of knights have been exchanged, is quite favourable for Black. He can carry out his minority attack while White does not have attacking potential on the kingside. The game went } 15. Qe2 b5 16. Nf3 $6 { This move is a mistake since it leaves the a4-pawn without protection. The position occurred in the online blitz game 1-0 (46) Gadimbayli, A (2394) -Grigorov, G (2505) Chess.com INT 2019. Here, I should have played } 16... bxa4 $17 { with an obvious advantage. If White tries hard to regain the pawn, Black can play ...a4-a3, spoiling the opponent's queenside structure. } ) 11... Bd6 12. Be3 Ra8 13. g3 { This dubious move gives Black a good possibility to start active actions on the kingside. Petar played } 13... h5 { when after } 14. c4 dxc4 15. Nd2 Rc8 $15 { he was already better. I don't comment on the quality of the White's move since this is just an online blitz game. The conclusion, however, is clear. White cannot rely on an advantage in this version of the Carlsbad structure with colours reversed. 1/2-1/2 (54) Gadimbayli,A (2470) -Arnaudov,P (2471) Chess.com INT 2020 } ) 8... Bd7 { This is the simplest solution in terms of playing for equality. } ( { If you are looking for a more complicated position, I would suggest } 8... b5 $5 { when the critical position arises after } 9. Ne5 bxa4 { From a statistical perspective, Black is doing fine in view of his bishop pair and good central control. His plan is quite simple and logical. After ... Bd6 and ...Nge7, we can proceed with ...0-0 and ...f7-f6. White should play very energetically in this position. The most challenging continuation is } 10. c4 ( { Another interesting direction is } 10. O-O Bd6 11. Bf4 Ne7 12. c4 dxc4 13. Nd2 { The threat of Ndxc4 is very annoying. Black should, therefore, find a concrete solution. } ( { A double-edged position arises after } 13. Nxf7 Bxf4 14. Nxh8 Nf5 15. Re1 { In a practical game, playing this position as White is riskier since the h8-knight can easily get lost without any compensation. } ( { After } 15. d5 Bxh2+ 16. Kh1 Be5 $15 { Black is already better. His next move is going to be .. .g7-g6. } ) 15... Bxh2+ 16. Kh1 g6 17. Qf3 Bb7 { The most straightforward solution which is practically forcing a draw. After } 18. Rxe6+ Kd7 19. d5 { the simplest is } 19... Qf4 { [%cal Gf4h4] Besides the idea of exchanging the queens, Black is also planning ...Qh4 on the next move. A logical end would be } 20. Qh3 Qc1+ 21. Kxh2 Qf4+ $11 { with a repetition, } ) 13... a3 { The most straightforward solution. } 14. Ndxc4 { This is the main line of the computer. } ( { Another logical sequence is } 14. bxa3 c3 15. Ne4 O-O 16. Nxd6 Qxd6 17. Ng6 { In this position, the key resource is } 17... e5 $1 { when Black is getting a good version of opposite-coloured bishops by force. } 18. Nxe7+ Qxe7 19. Bxe5 Bb7 $44 { The counterplay on the light squares gives Black an excellent compensation for the pawn. The game might continue } 20. Qb3 Rac8 21. Rac1 Rfd8 22. Rxc3 Rxc3 23. Qxc3 f6 24. Bc7 Qe4 $11 { with equality. Black will inevitably win the d4-pawn. } ) 14... Bxe5 { This is the simplest. After } 15. Nxe5 axb2 16. Rb1 Qa7 17. Rxb2 O-O $11 { The position is equal. Black will soon install a powerful knight on d5 which stabilizes the position. The advance ... a6-a5 followed by .. .Ba6 comes into consideration as well. } ) 10... f6 11. Qh5+ { The most straightforward.The following sequence is quite forced. } ( { An interesting alternative is } 11. Qxa4+ { White is going to win a pawn after } 11... Ke7 12. Nf3 Qxc4 13. Qxc4 dxc4 14. Na3 Kf7 15. Nxc4 { Nevertheless, I am convinced that the bishop pair, as well as the better pawn structure, provide Black with excellent compensation. A logical sequence would be } 15... Bb7 16. Bd2 g5 { Gaining space on the wings is one of the main strategies in positions with a bishop pair. } 17. Rc1 Rb8 18. b3 Nh6 19. Ne3 Bd6 20. O-O Rhc8 $44 { Black enjoys full compensation for the pawn thanks to the powerful bishops. } ) 11... g6 12. Nxg6 Qf7 13. Nf4 Qxh5 14. Nxh5 dxc4 15. Nd2 Kf7 16. Nxc4 Bd7 { [%cal Gd7b5, Gf8b4,Gg8e7] The bishop pair is very strong in this asymmetrical pawn structure. Black is ready to develop the initiative with ...Bb5. After } 17. O-O Bb5 18. b3 Bb4 19. Rd1 Ne7 $44 { we have an excellent compensation for the pawn. } ) 9. c4 Bxc6 10. cxd5 exd5 { This is the simplest way to the equality. Black will gradually neutralize White's slight initiative in this pawn structure. For the time being, we will just develop the pieces with natural moves such as ...Nf6 and ...Be7. The most White can get out of this position is } 11. Nc3 Nf6 12. O-O Be7 13. Bg5 O-O 14. Rc1 Qd6 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Na4 { White's obvious idea is to start playing against Black's queenside weaknesses. Black's counterplay, however, is based on three important factors: 1) the vulnerable d4-pawn 2) the semi-open b-file 3) the open e-file. A simple solution is } 16... Rae8 { planning to answer } 17. Nc5 { with } 17... h6 18. Bh4 ( { After } 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 { our counterplay is based on the pressure on d4. For instance, the careless } 19. Nxa6 $6 { will be met by } 19... Re4 $13 { with an excellent counterplay for Black. } ) 18... Ne4 $11 { After the simplifications, the position will be completely equal. } *[Event "?"]
