1. e4 c6 2. d3 d5 3. Nd2 { This is the main move order that White uses to get the King's Indian Attack setup. } ( { We are quite familiar with the structure arising after } 3. Qe2 dxe4 4. dxe4 e5 $13 { This structure was discussed in detail in the lecture featuring 2.Nf3 d5 3.d3. The white queen is obviously misplaced on e2. } ) ( { Gaining space with } 3. f4 { is hardly a serious option. After } 3... dxe4 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 { we can play in the spirit of the Alekhine by } 5... Nf6 $1 6. e5 ( { in reply to } 6. Bd3 { Black can successfully strike at the center with } 6... e5 7. f5 g6 $15 ) 6... Nd5 7. Nf3 Bg4 8. c4 Nc7 9. Nd2 Bf5 $5 10. Nh4 e6 $1 11. Nxf5 exf5 $13 { Black enjoys an excellent position. The f5-pawn provides space on the kingside while the e6-square is a very nice spot for the knight. } ) ( 3. Be2 dxe4 $5 ( 3... e5 $5 ) 4. dxe4 Qc7 $5 { Once again, we get the structure typical for the line with 2.Nf3 d5 3.d3. Obviously, this version is favourable for Black since the white bishop is misplaced on e2. The game might continue } 5. Nf3 e5 6. O-O Nf6 7. Nbd2 Be7 $11 { with equality. } ) 3... e5 4. Ngf3 Bd6 { This position is the main tabiya of the King's Indian Attack setup. Black is planning to play in the style of the Torre Opening with colours reversed. The natural development includes the moves ...Nf6 followed by ...0-0, and ...Bg4. White's most ambitious continuation is } 5. d4 { White tries to use his slightly better development in order to achieve a better structure. } ( { The classical version of the King's Indian Attack based on } 5. g3 Nf6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O { As explained above, Black can play in the style of the Torre opening with } 7... Bg4 { [%cal Gb8d7,Gf8e8,Gd8c7] This type of position is excellently explained by Papaioannou in his Torre Opening camps. You don't need any theory to play this position as Black. I will just explain some basic ideas and you will be perfectly ready to face this line in your own games. Black is planning to proceed the development with natural moves such as ...Nbd7, ...Re8, and ...Qc7. We will release the central tension by means of ...dxe4 in two cases: 1) after fully mobilizing our pieces 2) when White is putting pressure on the centre. The symmetrical structure arising after ...dxe4-dxe4 is usually favourable for Black due to the misplaced g2-bishop. We have already discussed this structure in the lecture dedicated to 1.e4 c6 2.Nf3 d5 3.d3. Therefore, here, I will limit myself to just one sample line. } 8. h3 Bh5 9. c3 ( { Remember that the advance } 9. g4 { is usually a bad idea in this structure. After } 9... Bg6 { [%csl Gf4][%cal Gd5e4,Gb8d7,Gd7c5,Gc5e6]  Black can already fight for an advantage. When there are weaknesses in the camp of our opponent, we are usually happy to go for a symmetrical pawn structure. Black, therefore, is planning to take on e4 and bring the b8-knight all the way to e6. } ) 9... Nbd7 10. Qc2 Re8 { The rook is excellently placed on this square. We should make sure that the maneuver Nh4-f5 can be always answered with ...Bf8. } 11. Re1 a5 $1 { Another important move. Sooner or later, we will get a symmetrical structure after ...dxe4. As explained above, in this case, we are going to play on the queenside. Therefore, Black immediately starts gaining space on the queenside. The following sequence provides a good illustration of Black's ideas. } 12. Nh4 Bf8 13. Nf5 Qc7 14. Nf1 dxe4 { Since all our forces are mobilized, it's time to clarify the structure. } 15. dxe4 Nc5 $15 { [%cal Gf6d7,Gf7f6,Gh5f7,Gb7b5] Black is already better. Bringing the light-squared bishop to f7 should be our first priority. Therefore, Black is going to proceed with ...Nfd7 followed by ... f7-f6, and ...Bf7. Later on, we can start gaining space on the queenside with . ..b7-b5. } ) ( { Winning a pawn with } 5. Qe2 $6 Nf6 6. exd5 cxd5 7. Nxe5 $2 { is quite dubious since White is not developed. After } 7... O-O { [%cal Ge8e1,Gd6e5, Gf8e8] } 8. d4 Nc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 { [%cal Gf8e8] Black has a winning advantage. } ) ( { In case of } 5. Be2 { Black's most precise reaction is } 5... Bc7 $14 { This strong novelty was suggested by GM Pavel Eljanov in his database My Caro-Kann - Part 4. I provide his analysis and explanations. Indeed, the idea is to prepare Nf6, which is, in my opinion, definitely the better square than e7. } ( { the problem with } 5... Nf6 { is that White can successfully push } 6. d4 $1 dxe4 ( 6... Nxe4 7. dxe5 Nxd2 8. Bxd2 Bc7 9. Bg5 $14 ) ( 6... Nbd7 7. exd5 cxd5 8. dxe5 Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Bxe5 10. Nf3 Bd6 11. Bb5+ $5 Bd7 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. O-O $14 ) 7. dxe5 exf3 8. Nxf3 { may not seem as a big achievement, but White retains some initiative in all the ensuing lines, e.g. } 8... Bc7 ( 8... Be7 9. exf6 Qxd1+ 10. Bxd1 Bxf6 11. c3 O-O 12. Bb3 Nd7 13. Be3 $14 ) 9. exf6 ( 9. Qxd8+ Bxd8 10. exf6 Bxf6 11. O-O O-O 12. a4 Bf5 13. c3 Nd7 14. Be3 a5 15. Rfd1 $14 { /= } ) 9... Qxf6 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 h6 $1 ( 11... Rd8 12. Bd3 h6 13. Bd2 $36 ) 12. Be3 Nd7 13. c3 Bb6 14. Bd3 $14 { /= } ) 6. O-O ( { After } 6. d4 exd4 7. exd5 cxd5 8. Nxd4 Nf6 $13 { we get our familiar strucure which is examined in the main line. } ) 6... Nf6 7. b4 $5 ( 7. Re1 O-O 8. Bf1 d4 $1 9. c3 c5 $15 ) ( 7. d4 $2 { is dropping a pawn for nothing after } 7... dxe4 ) 7... O-O 8. Bb2 Re8 9. Re1 { The game has miraculously transposed to a reversed version of the Breyer variation of the Ruy Lopez, Black is comfortable in all lines - } 9... Nbd7 ( { or } 9... a5 10. a3 { before } 10... Nbd7 11. Bf1 h6 12. h3 b6 $5 13. d4 $5 dxe4 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Bxe5 16. Bxe5 Rxe5 17. Nxe4 Bf5 $11 ) 10. Bf1 b6 11. b5 ( 11. d4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Rxe4 Nf6 14. Re1 e4 15. Ne5 Qd6 $36 ) 11... Bb7 12. a4 h6 $13 { Even though the position remains complex, I would take Black in view of his space advantage. } ) 5... exd4 6. exd5 cxd5 { In my opinion, this continuation is simpler than 6... Nf6 which is considered the main line. You can play this line without knowing any concrete theory. The structure arising after } 7. Nxd4 { was already discussed in the lecture featuring the Exchange Variation. Let me remind you that this version of IQP is more favourable for Black than the classical one in which White has a pawn on e3. In this line, Black can just fight for the initiative by making natural developing moves. After } 7... Nc6 { White has a choice, but the nature of play remains unchanged. } 8. N2f3 { This is the most popular continuation. White not only increases the control of the d4-square but also secures the protection of the kingside. } ( { The main alternative is } 8. N2b3 { In this case, a logical answer would be } 8... Nf6 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O h6 $13 { [%cal Ga7a6,Gc8d7,Gf8e8,Ga8c8,Ge8e1,Gc8c1,Gc6c4,Gf6e4,Gd6c7,Gd8d6] Before anything else, Black takes the g5-square under control, thus ruling out any Bg5-based ideas. It's, therefore, not easy for White to find a good square for his dark-squared bishop. Later on, after putting the rook on e8, Black can build a typical attacking construction - ...a7-a6 followed by ...Bc7, and ... Qd6. Obviously, the f6-knight will be installed on e4. Black's play is definitely easier in this position. } ) ( { Quite harmless is } 8. Bb5 { The only idea of this move is to force our king's knight into the passive e7-square. In this case, we would have a transposition into one of the French Defence lines arising after 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nd2 c5. I would suggest the natural development based on } 8... Bd7 9. N2f3 Nf6 10. O-O O-O $13 { with a decent version of IQP. We have already discussed the typical plans in such positions. } ) 8... Nf6 { Of course, the knight should be developed via the active f6-square. The following moves are quite natural - } 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Re8 11. c3 h6 { In this typical IQP position, I would suggest } 12. Re1 a6 { [%cal Gd6c7,Gd8d6] planning to build our usual battery with ...Bc7, and ...Qd6. Black has an excellent counterplay. } ( { Of course } 12... Bg4 { is playable as well. } ) *[Event "?"]
