{White has tried a lot of tricky move orders on move 2 and 3, but only a few of them are sound in my opinion and deserve to be mentioned. This part of the lecture will be based on the analysis of GM Pavel Eljanov. He provided excellent coverage of these minor lines in his course My Caro-Kann - Part 4.} 1. e4 c6 2. Ne2 (2. Bc4 $6 d5 3. Bb3 (3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bb3 Nf6 $15) 3... dxe4 4. Qh5 (4. Nc3 Nf6 5. f3 exf3 6. Nxf3 Bf5 7. d4 e6 $17) 4... g6 5. Qh4 Nf6 6. Nc3 (6. f3 Qd4 7. Ne2 (7. Nc3 exf3 $1) 7... Qe5 8. Nbc3 exf3 9. gxf3 Qh5 $17) 6... Bg7 7. f3 (7. Nxe4 a5 $1 8. a4 Na6 9. Nf3 Nb4 10. d3 Be6 $17) 7... exf3 8. Nxf3 {is almost a gamble, which Black must be able to disprove with prudent play -} h6 $5 (8... Nbd7 $14 9. d4 e6 $6 10. Bh6 $40 {A. Shimanov - R. Svane, Titled Tuesday, 7th Jun 2022}) 9. d3 (9. d4 Bf5 $1 10. h3 Nbd7 $17) 9... Nbd7 {with solid position and a pawn up, e. g.} 10. Be3 Nf8 $1 11. O-O-O Be6 $15) (2. g3 $6 d5 3. Bg2 dxe4 4. Bxe4 (4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Nxe4 Nxe4 6. Bxe4 e5 7. d3 Bd6 8. Bg2 O-O $15) 4... Nf6 5. Bg2 e5 $1 {Simple and strong - such centralization is definitely the most consistent way to proceed.} 6. d3 Bc5 7. Nd2 O-O ({or} 7... Bg4 $5 8. Ngf3 Nbd7 {with easy development as well} 9. O-O O-O 10. h3 Bh5 11. Nc4 Re8 $13) 8. Ngf3 Re8 9. O-O Bf5 10. Nc4 Nbd7 $13) (2. Nc3 d5 {may just transpose, but there are some curious alternatives: The other queen move} 3. Qf3 {has more merits, it is often used by GM Farrukh Amonatov in blitz games.} (3. d3 {leaves Black with a broad choice. Let us examine at first} e5 $5 ({the idea to precede it by} 3... d4 $5 {also deserves attention, for instance} 4. Nce2 e5 5. g3 c5 6. f4 Nc6 7. Nf3 Bd6 8. Bg2 Nge7 9. O-O f6 $13) ({, while} 3... dxe4 {is, surprisingly to some extent, imprecise, because the exchange of the queens will enable a transfer of Nc3 to its perfect c4-square, thus with a nice version of the 3. d3-line from White's perspective, e.g.} 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Nxd1 Nf6 6. f3 e5 7. Ne3 Nfd7 8. Bd2 $14) 4. d4 $5 (4. Nf3 {is natural, when} Nf6 $5 {is an intriguing shot at taking over the initiative -} 5. exd5 cxd5 6. Nxe5 (6. d4 e4 7. Ne5 Bb4 $15) 6... d4 7. Qe2 Be7 8. Ne4 Nxe4 9. Qxe4 O-O $36) 4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Qxd4 {is already containing a pawn sacrifice by White:} 6. Bd3 (6. Qxd4 exd4 7. Nf3 Bf5 (7... c5 8. Bc4 Be6 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Bf4 Nf6 11. Neg5 Nc6 $11) 8. Bd3 $5 Bxe4 9. Bxe4 Nf6 10. Bf5 Bb4+ 11. Kf1 O-O 12. Nxd4 Rd8 13. c3 Bc5 $13) 6... Nf6 7. Nf3 Qd5 8. Qe2 Bg4 $13) ({In reply to} 3. Qe2 d4 {is the most logical reaction, because the knight should retreat back to the 1st rank -} 4. Nd1 e5 5. g3 c5 6. d3 Nc6 7. f4 Bd6 {and now:} 8. Nf3 (8. Bh3 {Pridorozhni - Le Quang, Titled Tuesday, 25th Aug 2020, when Black could create a target by} exf4 $1 9. gxf4 Nge7 10. Bxc8 Qxc8 11. Nf3 Ng6 $15) (8. Nf2 {can be analogously met by} exf4 9. gxf4 Nge7 10. Nf3 f6 $1 11. Rg1 (11. Bd2 Qc7 12. f5 Bd7 $17 {Laukhina - Salimova, Djerba, blitz, 2020,}) 11... O-O 12. Nh4 Kh8 13. Qh5 Be6 $15) 8... exf4 $5 {The same concrete approach for provoking weaknesses.} (8... Nge7 9. Bg2 Qc7 $5 {is also possible, then White can close the center by means of} 10. f5 f6 11. c4 $13 {, which might not be everyone's cup of tea}) 9. gxf4 Qc7 10. e5 Be7 11. Nf2 Nh6 {with decent chances after} 12. Bg2 Nf5 13. Ne4 O-O 14. O-O a5 $15 {[%cal Ga8a6,Ga6g6]}) 3... dxe4 $5 {seems to be in the spirit of Caro-Kann more than any other continuation.} ({Most of my own games vs. Farrukh on chess.com have seen} 3... d4 4. Bc4 e6 5. Nce2 c5 6. d3 {etc. with complex positions and mutual chances}) 4. Nxe4 Nf6 {Now it either leads to doubled f-pawns or if White does not take himself, to typical Caro-Kann structures. In both cases Qf3 is a bit misplaced in my view, here are several sample lines:} 5. Bc4 (5. c3 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Qd5 $11) (5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. Bc4 Bd6 (6... Nd7 $5) 7. Ne2 O-O 8. d4 c5 $1 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Be3 (10. O-O Nc6 $13) 10... Qa5+ 11. c3 Nc6 12. Bf4 Qb6 13. b4 Be7 14. Qe3 Qxe3 15. Bxe3 a5 $15 {Heinemann - Esipenko, AUT-chT2M, 2021}) 5... Nbd7 $1 6. Bb3 (6. Nxf6+ exf6 $5 7. Ne2 (7. d4 Nb6 8. Qe4+ Be7 9. Bd3 f5 $13) 7... Ne5 8. Qe3 Be7 $13) (6. d4 Nb6 7. Bd3 {is yet another gambit idea, which Black should better accept -} Qxd4 8. Ne2 Qe5 9. Bf4 (9. O-O Nxe4 10. Bxe4 h5 $5 11. h3 Qf6 $15) 9... Qe6 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 (10... gxf6 $5 11. h3 Nd7 $13) 11. Qg3 $1 Bf5 12. Be5 Qg6 13. Bxf5 Qxf5 14. O-O-O Qg6 $1 {with every chance to repel White's initiative -} 15. Qc3 f6 16. Bc7 Qf7 $15) 6... a5 $1 {A typical advance - it makes sense to define the structure and eliminate an eventual Ba4.} 7. a4 e6 8. d4 c5 $1 9. Nxf6+ Nxf6 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Be3 Qb6 $13 {Lazov - Vallejo Pons, Thessaloniki Vardaris, 2019}) 2... d5 3. e5 {was Short's pet line for a certain period. I have been usually meeting it (in blitz games) with 3...d4, but now I have realized that} Bf5 $5 (3... d4 4. c3 c5 5. f4 {is more complex}) 4. Ng3 Bg6 {must be easier, with a likely transposition to some rare deviations, for example} 5. h4 h5 6. e6 $6 {I do not find this enough even for equality.} (6. d4 {transposes to a subline, which I have analyzed in the 2nd part of My Caro-Kann}) (6. Be2 e6 7. Nxh5 (7. d4 c5 8. c3 Nc6 $15) 7... Bxh5 8. Bxh5 g6 9. Bf3 Rxh4 $15) 6... fxe6 7. d4 Qd6 $1 8. Bd3 (8. f4 Nh6 9. Bd3 Bf7 10. O-O g6 $17) 8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Nd7 {It seems to me that Ng3 is misplaced here and by this White's whole concept fails, here are some lines in confirmation -} 10. f4 (10. Qg6+ $6 Kd8 11. Nxh5 e5 $17) (10. O-O e5 $15) (10. Nd2 {1/2-1/2 (45) Felgaer,R (2560) -Donchenko,A (2631) chess24.com INT 2019} e5 11. O-O g6 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Qb3 O-O-O $17) 10... Nh6 11. O-O (11. Qg6+ Kd8 12. Qxh5 g6 $1 13. Qxg6 c5 $40) 11... Nf5 $1 12. Nxf5 exf5 13. Qxf5 Qf6 14. Qd3 Qxh4 $15 *

